{"title_page": "Richard Burbage", "text_new": "{{short description|16th/17th-century English actor and theatre owner}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n[[File:RichardBurbage.jpg|thumb|''Portrait of Richard Burbage'', [[Dulwich Picture Gallery]], [[London]]]]\n\n'''Richard Burbage''' (c. 1567 &ndash; 13 March 1619) was an English stage actor, widely considered to have been one of the most famous actors of the [[Globe Theatre]] and of his time. In addition to being a stage [[actor]], he was also a theatre owner, entrepreneur, and painter. He was the younger brother of [[Cuthbert Burbage]]. They were both actors in drama. Burbage was a business associate and friend to [[William Shakespeare]].\n\nThe son of [[James Burbage]], a [[joiner]] who became a theatrical impresario and entrepreneur, also founded the first theatre. Burbage was a popular actor by his early 20s. He excelled in plays with the theme of tragedies. His early acting career is poorly documented. As many young actors of his time, he may have played the part of women in productions before taking any of the roles he is known for. It has been suggested that he spent time working with the [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester|Earl of Leicester]]'s company, but there is no good evidence for this. He was probably acting with the [[Admiral's Men]] in 1590, with Lord Strange's Men in 1592, and with the Earl of Pembroke's Men in 1593; but most famously he was the star of William Shakespeare's theatre company, the [[Lord Chamberlain's Men]], which became the [[King's Men (playing company)|King's Men]] on the ascension of [[James I of England|James I]] in 1603. He played the title role in the first performances of many of Shakespeare's plays, including ''[[Hamlet]]'', ''[[Othello]]'', ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'', and ''[[King Lear]]''. But he was in great demand and also appeared in the plays of many of the great contemporary writers, such as [[Ben Jonson]] (the title role in ''[[Volpone]]'', and Subtle in ''[[The Alchemist (play)|The Alchemist]]''), [[John Marston (poet)|John Marston]] (''The Malcontent''), [[John Webster]] (''[[The Duchess of Malfi]]'') and [[Francis Beaumont|Beaumont]] and [[John Fletcher (playwright)|Fletcher]] (''[[The Maid's Tragedy]]'').\n\nBurbage was described as being short and stout but was said to be an impressive figure, with numerous praises written of him in contemporary accounts. His power and scope as an actor is revealed in the sheer size of the roles he played. He was a great box office draw. Of the hundreds of plays and thousands of roles for actors that date from the 1580&ndash;1610 era, there are only twenty or so roles that are longer than 800 lines. [[Edward Alleyn]] was the first English actor to manage such roles, in [[Christopher Marlowe|Marlowe's]] ''[[Tamburlaine]]'' and ''[[The Jew of Malta]];'' but the majority of these star roles, thirteen of the twenty, were acted by Burbage.{{Sfn|McMillin|1987|pp=61\u20133}} He was said to be quite rich because he was earning income from being the primary housekeeping of two playhouses, a sharer in the King's Men, a lead actor and a painter.\n\n== Life ==\n[[File:Portrait of Richard Burbage (4673658) (cropped).jpg|thumb|19th century print of Richard Burbage]]\nBurbage was baptised at St Stephen in London on 7 July 1568. He was the second son of his parents, followed by three younger sisters; Alice, Joane, and Ellen. His father brought Burbage to the theatre and had the greatest influence on his career. Being the son of a builder and owner of the first successful permanent playhouse gave him a great starting advantage in the theatre world. It is said that because he worked in the theatre with his father at such a young age, he learned the basics of working with colours and the techniques of painting, which helped him later in life.<ref>https://is.muni.cz/th/216983/ff_b/BA_Thesis.pdf</ref>\n\nAfter the death of their father in February 1597, Richard and his brother Cuthbert stepped in to rescue the family's interests in two London theatres and found themselves tied up in lawsuits. They kept the [[Blackfriars Theatre]] but leased it to lawyer and impresario [[Henry Evans (theatre)|Henry Evans]], who used it for a troupe of child actors. The other, called simply [[The Theatre]], was dismantled when they could not resolve terms for a new lease with Giles Allen, the landowner. The beams, posts, and other remnants of The Theatre were moved to a new location on the south side of the Thames River and reassembled into a new playhouse called the [[Globe Theatre|Globe]] in 1599. The Burbage brothers kept half the shares in the new theatre and gave the remainder to Shakespeare and other members of the Chamberlain's Men. Income from the Blackfriars lease helped fund the move to the Globe. In 1608 the brothers ended the Blackfriars lease and moved the company to the new theatre. Burbage was performing there on 29 June 1613, when it caught fire and burned down. During the winter months, when it was not practical to use the open-air Globe, they used the Blackfriars. It was much smaller and seated about 700 people.\n\nThe brothers maintained a close working and personal relationship throughout their lives; they were neighbours on Halliwell Street in [[Shoreditch]], near the Theatre. Burbage married Winifred Turner on 2 October 1600 at St Mary's, Rotherhithe. <ref>{{Cite article|title=Siobhan Keenan, \u2018New Evidence About Shakespearean \u201cStar\u201d Actor, Richard Burbage\u2019, Notes & Queries, June 2019}}</ref> Burbage fathered at least eight children;<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-lfweG1MIOEC&pg=PA234&lpg=PA234&dq=richard+burbage+eight+children&source=bl&ots=6-uULU9AAS&sig=h2z4atP-JNgH8O_lIDNA5iMCv7g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiU1afZzNHZAhVBy2MKHercB5kQ6AEwB3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=richard%20burbage%20eight%20children&f=false|title=Medieval and Renaissance Drama in England|last=Barroll|first=Leeds|date=March 1996|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|isbn=9780838636411|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424131052/https://books.google.com/books?id=-lfweG1MIOEC&pg=PA234&lpg=PA234&dq=richard+burbage+eight+children&source=bl&ots=6-uULU9AAS&sig=h2z4atP-JNgH8O_lIDNA5iMCv7g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiU1afZzNHZAhVBy2MKHercB5kQ6AEwB3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=richard%20burbage%20eight%20children&f=false|archivedate=24 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> after his death his widow Winifred married another of the King's Men, [[Richard Robinson (17th-century actor)|Richard Robinson]].{{Sfn|Halliday|1964|p=77}} [See also: [[Nicholas Tooley]].]\n\nIt has sometimes been argued that the famous [[Chandos portrait]] of Shakespeare was painted by Burbage. His skills were in demand. Some believe that the anonymous oil painting used so often nowadays to show what Burbage looked like was a self-portrait.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shakespeare-online.com/biography/richardburbage.html|title=Shakespeare's Friend Richard Burbage|last=Mabillard|first=Amanda|website=www.shakespeare-online.com|access-date=2018-03-04|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20132217085400/http://www.shakespeare-online.com/biography/richardburbage.html|archivedate=24 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DlfPUi_N0gwC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA36&dq=dulwich+college+burbage+painting&source=bl&ots=3kwWiGckHw&sig=qv0mku2S4oxwDBoJugPL66vlNDY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwigvvSAy9HZAhVFy2MKHUqMAD84ChDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=dulwich%20college%20burbage%20painting&f=false|title=Shakespeare by Stages: An Historical Introduction|last=Kinney|first=Arthur F.|date=2008-04-15|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470776926|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424131052/https://books.google.com/books?id=DlfPUi_N0gwC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA36&dq=dulwich+college+burbage+painting&source=bl&ots=3kwWiGckHw&sig=qv0mku2S4oxwDBoJugPL66vlNDY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwigvvSAy9HZAhVFy2MKHUqMAD84ChDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=dulwich%20college%20burbage%20painting&f=false|archivedate=24 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Dulwich College]] holds a painting of a female head in a roughly similar style that was generally regarded as his work until it was found out in 1987 that it was probably misattributed to him and that it is a work by a North Italian painter. The [[Portraits of Shakespeare|\"Felton\" portrait of Shakespeare]] is also attributed to Burbage,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sh5LAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA452&lpg=PA452&dq=felton+portrait+shakespeare+burbage&source=bl&ots=zPFYMfABLs&sig=I73NL7Lu1c9h8FkNaN_5Q63CwLA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjiga66y9HZAhVCGGMKHaXBAfMQ6AEwEHoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=felton%20portrait%20shakespeare%20burbage&f=false|title=The Theatre|date=1890|publisher=Wyman & Sons|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424131052/https://books.google.com/books?id=sh5LAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA452&lpg=PA452&dq=felton+portrait+shakespeare+burbage&source=bl&ots=zPFYMfABLs&sig=I73NL7Lu1c9h8FkNaN_5Q63CwLA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjiga66y9HZAhVCGGMKHaXBAfMQ6AEwEHoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=felton%20portrait%20shakespeare%20burbage&f=false|archivedate=24 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and also a portrait of a woman which is currently preserved at Dulwich College, in Southeast London.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nUnlike Alleyn or his fellow King's Man Shakespeare, Burbage never retired from the stage; he continued acting until his death, aged 52, in 1619. He was not such an astute businessman as either Alleyn or Shakespeare; at his death he was said to have left his widow \"better than \u00a3300\" in land&mdash;a respectable estate but far less than Alleyn's substantial wealth, and less than the net worth of Shakespeare at his death in 1616.{{Sfn|Gurr|1992|p=91}}\n\nHe remained a crowd favorite, even when younger actors emerged, for thirty-five years, and was an idol of his age. His last recorded performance was in 1610, but he acted with the King's Men until his death in 1619. His death caused such an outpouring of grief<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NR3buYsg0fAC&pg=PA231&lpg=PA231&dq=burbage+mourn+queen+anne&source=bl&ots=cNaFF_g69u&sig=lfiE8OlFEiCMCS3xDuQ9hQWOJvo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiU6_eHzNHZAhVQ8GMKHcasBss4ChDoATACegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=burbage%20mourn%20queen%20anne&f=false|title=The Shakespearean period in England|last=Mantzius|first=Karl|date=1904|publisher=Duckworth|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424131052/https://books.google.com/books?id=NR3buYsg0fAC&pg=PA231&lpg=PA231&dq=burbage+mourn+queen+anne&source=bl&ots=cNaFF_g69u&sig=lfiE8OlFEiCMCS3xDuQ9hQWOJvo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiU6_eHzNHZAhVQ8GMKHcasBss4ChDoATACegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=burbage%20mourn%20queen%20anne&f=false|archivedate=24 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> that it threatened to overshadow the official mourning for the death of [[Anne of Denmark|Queen Anne]] ten days prior.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/shakespearesthe00thorgoog|page=[https://archive.org/details/shakespearesthe00thorgoog/page/n433 387]|quote=burbage mourn queen anne.|title=Shakespeare's Theater|last=Thorndike|first=Ashley Horace|date=1916|publisher=Macmillan|language=en|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBurbage was buried in [[St Leonard's, Shoreditch]], a church close to two theatres: \"The Theatre\" and \"The Curtain Theatre.\" His gravestone was said to read \"Exit Burbage.\" Although his gravestone is now lost, a memorial to him and his brothers was erected in a later century. An anonymous poet composed for him ''A Funerall Elegye on the Death of the famous Actor Richard Burbage who died on Saturday in Lent the 13 of March 1619'', an excerpt of which reads:\n\n{{quote|<poem>\nHe's gone and with him what a world are dead.\nWhich he review'd, to be revived so,\nNo more [[Prince Hamlet|young Hamlet]], old Hieronimo{{Efn|\"Hieronimo\" or \"Hieronymo\" is the main character from [[Thomas Kyd]]'s ''[[The Spanish Tragedy]]''.}}\n[[King Lear|Kind Lear]], [[Othello (character)|the Grieved Moor]], and more beside,\nThat lived in him have now forever died.{{Sfn|Wells|2011}}\n</poem>}}\n\nOf the many elegies that followed his passing, perhaps the most poignant is the brief epitaph:\n\n{{quote|Exit Burbage.{{Sfn|Wells|2011}}}}\n\n==Portrayals==\n\nBurbage was played by [[Martin Clunes]] in the film ''[[Shakespeare in Love]]'' (1998), by [[Steve Speirs]] in the BBC sitcom ''[[Upstart Crow]]'' (2016), by Adam Colborne in the mini-series ''[[Good Omens (miniseries)|Good Omens]]'', co-produced by the [[BBC]] and [[Amazon Video]],  and by Mattias Inwood in the 2017 [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] drama ''[[Will (TV series)|Will]]''.\n\n{{NPG name|id=55653|name=Richard Burbage}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{Notelist}}\n\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{Cite web|title=The First Great Shakespearian Actor|last=Wells|first=Stanley|authorlink=Stanley Wells|date=26 May 2011|website=Blogging Shakespeare|accessdate=3 February 2018|url=http://bloggingshakespeare.com/the-first-great-shakespearian-actor|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |title = The Shakespearan Stage 1574\u20131642\n  |last = Gurr\n  |first = Andrew\n  |authorlink = Andrew Gurr\n  |location = Cambridge\n  |publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]]\n  |year = 1992\n  |edition = 3rd\n  |isbn = 9780521410052\n  |ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |title = A Shakespeare Companion 1564\u20131964\n  |last = Halliday\n  |first = F. E.\n  |authorlink = F. E. Halliday\n  |location = Baltimore\n  |publisher = [[Penguin Books|Penguin]]\n  |series = Penguin Reference Books\n  |volume = 27\n  |year = 1964\n  |edition = Revised\n  |oclc = 222822680\n  |ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |title = The Elizabethan Theatre and ''The Book of Sir Thomas More''\n  |last = McMillin\n  |first = Scott\n  |location = Ithaca, N.Y.\n  |publisher = [[Cornell University Press]]\n  |year = 1987\n  |isbn = 9780801420085\n  |ref = harv\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burbage, Richard}}\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:1568 births]]\n[[Category:1619 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of the Elizabethan era]]\n[[Category:People associated with Shakespeare]]\n[[Category:English male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:Theatre owners]]\n[[Category:16th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:17th-century English male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|16th/17th-century English actor and theatre owner}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n[[File:RichardBurbage.jpg|thumb|''Portrait of Richard Burbage'', [[Dulwich Picture Gallery]], [[London]]]]\n\n'''Richard Burbage''' (c. 1567 &ndash; 13 March 1619) was an English stage actor, widely considered to have been one of the most famous actors of the [[Globe Theatre]] and of his time. In addition to being a stage [[actor]], he was also a theatre owner, entrepreneur, and painter. He was the younger brother of [[Cuthbert Burbage]]. They were both actors in drama. Burbage was a business associate and friend to [[William Shakespeare]].\n\nThe son of [[James Burbage]], a [[joiner]] who became a theatrical impresario and entrepreneur, also founded the first theatre. Burbage was a popular actor by his early 20s. He excelled in plays with the theme of tragedies. His early acting career is poorly documented. As many young actors of his time, he may have played the part of women in productions before taking any of the roles he is known for. It has been suggested that he spent time working with the [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester|Earl of Leicester]]'s company, but there is no good evidence for this. He was probably acting with the [[Admiral's Men]] in 1590, with Lord Strange's Men in 1592, and with the Earl of Pembroke's Men in 1593; but most famously he was the star of William Shakespeare's theatre company, the [[Lord Chamberlain's Men]], which became the [[King's Men (playing company)|King's Men]] on the ascension of [[James I of England|James I]] in 1603. He played the title role in the first performances of many of Shakespeare's plays, including ''[[Hamlet]]'', ''[[Othello]]'', ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'', and ''[[King Lear]]''. But he was in great demand and also appeared in the plays of many of the great contemporary writers, such as [[Ben Jonson]] (the title role in ''[[Volpone]]'', and Subtle in ''[[The Alchemist (play)|The Alchemist]]''), [[John Marston (poet)|John Marston]] (''The Malcontent''), [[John Webster]] (''[[The Duchess of Malfi]]'') and [[Francis Beaumont|Beaumont]] and [[John Fletcher (playwright)|Fletcher]] (''[[The Maid's Tragedy]]'').\n\nBurbage was described as being short and stout but was said to be an impressive figure, with numerous praises written of him in contemporary accounts. His power and scope as an actor is revealed in the sheer size of the roles he played. He was a great box office draw. Of the hundreds of plays and thousands of roles for actors that date from the 1580&ndash;1610 era, there are only twenty or so roles that are longer than 800 lines. [[Edward Alleyn]] was the first English actor to manage such roles, in [[Christopher Marlowe|Marlowe's]] ''[[Tamburlaine]]'' and ''[[The Jew of Malta]];'' but the majority of these star roles, thirteen of the twenty, were acted by Burbage.{{Sfn|McMillin|1987|pp=61\u20133}} He was said to be quite rich because he was earning income from being the primary housekeeping of two playhouses, a sharer in the King's Men, a lead actor and a painter.\n\n== Life ==\n[[File:Portrait of Richard Burbage (4673658) (cropped).jpg|thumb|19th century print of Richard Burbage]]\nBurbage was baptised at St Stephen in London on 7 July 1568. He was the second son of his parents, followed by three younger sisters; Alice, Joane, and Ellen. His father brought Burbage to the theatre and had the greatest influence on his career. Being the son of a builder and owner of the first successful permanent playhouse gave him a great starting advantage in the theatre world. It is said that because he worked in the theatre with his father at such a young age, he learned the basics of working with colours and the techniques of painting, which helped him later in life.<ref>https://is.muni.cz/th/216983/ff_b/BA_Thesis.pdf</ref>\n\nAfter the death of their father in February 1597, Richard and his brother Cuthbert stepped in to rescue the family's interests in two London theatres and found themselves tied up in lawsuits. They kept the [[Blackfriars Theatre]] but leased it to lawyer and impresario [[Henry Evans (theatre)|Henry Evans]], who used it for a troupe of child actors. The other, called simply [[The Theatre]], was dismantled when they could not resolve terms for a new lease with Giles Allen, the landowner. The beams, posts, and other remnants of The Theatre were moved to a new location on the south side of the Thames River and reassembled into a new playhouse called the [[Globe Theatre|Globe]] in 1599. The Burbage brothers kept half the shares in the new theatre and gave the remainder to Shakespeare and other members of the Chamberlain's Men. Income from the Blackfriars lease helped fund the move to the Globe. In 1608 the brothers ended the Blackfriars lease and moved the company to the new theatre. Burbage was performing there on 29 June 1613, when it caught fire and burned down. During the winter months, when it was not practical to use the open-air Globe, they used the Blackfriars. It was much smaller and seated about 700 people.\n\nThe brothers maintained a close working and personal relationship throughout their lives; they were neighbours on Halliwell Street in [[Shoreditch]], near the Theatre. Burbage married Winifred Turner on 2 October 1600 at St Mary's, Rotherhithe. <ref>{{Siobhan Keenan, \u2018New Evidence About Shakespearean \u201cStar\u201d Actor, Richard Burbage\u2019, Notes & Queries, August 2019. ISSN:  0029-3970. Available at https://doi.org/10.1093/notesj/gjz077.}}</ref> Burbage fathered at least eight children;<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-lfweG1MIOEC&pg=PA234&lpg=PA234&dq=richard+burbage+eight+children&source=bl&ots=6-uULU9AAS&sig=h2z4atP-JNgH8O_lIDNA5iMCv7g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiU1afZzNHZAhVBy2MKHercB5kQ6AEwB3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=richard%20burbage%20eight%20children&f=false|title=Medieval and Renaissance Drama in England|last=Barroll|first=Leeds|date=March 1996|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|isbn=9780838636411|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424131052/https://books.google.com/books?id=-lfweG1MIOEC&pg=PA234&lpg=PA234&dq=richard+burbage+eight+children&source=bl&ots=6-uULU9AAS&sig=h2z4atP-JNgH8O_lIDNA5iMCv7g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiU1afZzNHZAhVBy2MKHercB5kQ6AEwB3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=richard%20burbage%20eight%20children&f=false|archivedate=24 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> after his death his widow Winifred married another of the King's Men, [[Richard Robinson (17th-century actor)|Richard Robinson]].{{Sfn|Halliday|1964|p=77}} [See also: [[Nicholas Tooley]].]\n\nIt has sometimes been argued that the famous [[Chandos portrait]] of Shakespeare was painted by Burbage. His skills were in demand. Some believe that the anonymous oil painting used so often nowadays to show what Burbage looked like was a self-portrait.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shakespeare-online.com/biography/richardburbage.html|title=Shakespeare's Friend Richard Burbage|last=Mabillard|first=Amanda|website=www.shakespeare-online.com|access-date=2018-03-04|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20132217085400/http://www.shakespeare-online.com/biography/richardburbage.html|archivedate=24 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DlfPUi_N0gwC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA36&dq=dulwich+college+burbage+painting&source=bl&ots=3kwWiGckHw&sig=qv0mku2S4oxwDBoJugPL66vlNDY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwigvvSAy9HZAhVFy2MKHUqMAD84ChDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=dulwich%20college%20burbage%20painting&f=false|title=Shakespeare by Stages: An Historical Introduction|last=Kinney|first=Arthur F.|date=2008-04-15|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470776926|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424131052/https://books.google.com/books?id=DlfPUi_N0gwC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA36&dq=dulwich+college+burbage+painting&source=bl&ots=3kwWiGckHw&sig=qv0mku2S4oxwDBoJugPL66vlNDY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwigvvSAy9HZAhVFy2MKHUqMAD84ChDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=dulwich%20college%20burbage%20painting&f=false|archivedate=24 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Dulwich College]] holds a painting of a female head in a roughly similar style that was generally regarded as his work until it was found out in 1987 that it was probably misattributed to him and that it is a work by a North Italian painter. The [[Portraits of Shakespeare|\"Felton\" portrait of Shakespeare]] is also attributed to Burbage,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sh5LAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA452&lpg=PA452&dq=felton+portrait+shakespeare+burbage&source=bl&ots=zPFYMfABLs&sig=I73NL7Lu1c9h8FkNaN_5Q63CwLA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjiga66y9HZAhVCGGMKHaXBAfMQ6AEwEHoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=felton%20portrait%20shakespeare%20burbage&f=false|title=The Theatre|date=1890|publisher=Wyman & Sons|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424131052/https://books.google.com/books?id=sh5LAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA452&lpg=PA452&dq=felton+portrait+shakespeare+burbage&source=bl&ots=zPFYMfABLs&sig=I73NL7Lu1c9h8FkNaN_5Q63CwLA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjiga66y9HZAhVCGGMKHaXBAfMQ6AEwEHoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=felton%20portrait%20shakespeare%20burbage&f=false|archivedate=24 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and also a portrait of a woman which is currently preserved at Dulwich College, in Southeast London.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nUnlike Alleyn or his fellow King's Man Shakespeare, Burbage never retired from the stage; he continued acting until his death, aged 52, in 1619. He was not such an astute businessman as either Alleyn or Shakespeare; at his death he was said to have left his widow \"better than \u00a3300\" in land&mdash;a respectable estate but far less than Alleyn's substantial wealth, and less than the net worth of Shakespeare at his death in 1616.{{Sfn|Gurr|1992|p=91}}\n\nHe remained a crowd favorite, even when younger actors emerged, for thirty-five years, and was an idol of his age. His last recorded performance was in 1610, but he acted with the King's Men until his death in 1619. His death caused such an outpouring of grief<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NR3buYsg0fAC&pg=PA231&lpg=PA231&dq=burbage+mourn+queen+anne&source=bl&ots=cNaFF_g69u&sig=lfiE8OlFEiCMCS3xDuQ9hQWOJvo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiU6_eHzNHZAhVQ8GMKHcasBss4ChDoATACegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=burbage%20mourn%20queen%20anne&f=false|title=The Shakespearean period in England|last=Mantzius|first=Karl|date=1904|publisher=Duckworth|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424131052/https://books.google.com/books?id=NR3buYsg0fAC&pg=PA231&lpg=PA231&dq=burbage+mourn+queen+anne&source=bl&ots=cNaFF_g69u&sig=lfiE8OlFEiCMCS3xDuQ9hQWOJvo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiU6_eHzNHZAhVQ8GMKHcasBss4ChDoATACegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=burbage%20mourn%20queen%20anne&f=false|archivedate=24 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> that it threatened to overshadow the official mourning for the death of [[Anne of Denmark|Queen Anne]] ten days prior.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/shakespearesthe00thorgoog|page=[https://archive.org/details/shakespearesthe00thorgoog/page/n433 387]|quote=burbage mourn queen anne.|title=Shakespeare's Theater|last=Thorndike|first=Ashley Horace|date=1916|publisher=Macmillan|language=en|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBurbage was buried in [[St Leonard's, Shoreditch]], a church close to two theatres: \"The Theatre\" and \"The Curtain Theatre.\" His gravestone was said to read \"Exit Burbage.\" Although his gravestone is now lost, a memorial to him and his brothers was erected in a later century. An anonymous poet composed for him ''A Funerall Elegye on the Death of the famous Actor Richard Burbage who died on Saturday in Lent the 13 of March 1619'', an excerpt of which reads:\n\n{{quote|<poem>\nHe's gone and with him what a world are dead.\nWhich he review'd, to be revived so,\nNo more [[Prince Hamlet|young Hamlet]], old Hieronimo{{Efn|\"Hieronimo\" or \"Hieronymo\" is the main character from [[Thomas Kyd]]'s ''[[The Spanish Tragedy]]''.}}\n[[King Lear|Kind Lear]], [[Othello (character)|the Grieved Moor]], and more beside,\nThat lived in him have now forever died.{{Sfn|Wells|2011}}\n</poem>}}\n\nOf the many elegies that followed his passing, perhaps the most poignant is the brief epitaph:\n\n{{quote|Exit Burbage.{{Sfn|Wells|2011}}}}\n\n==Portrayals==\n\nBurbage was played by [[Martin Clunes]] in the film ''[[Shakespeare in Love]]'' (1998), by [[Steve Speirs]] in the BBC sitcom ''[[Upstart Crow]]'' (2016), by Adam Colborne in the mini-series ''[[Good Omens (miniseries)|Good Omens]]'', co-produced by the [[BBC]] and [[Amazon Video]],  and by Mattias Inwood in the 2017 [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] drama ''[[Will (TV series)|Will]]''.\n\n{{NPG name|id=55653|name=Richard Burbage}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{Notelist}}\n\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{Cite web|title=The First Great Shakespearian Actor|last=Wells|first=Stanley|authorlink=Stanley Wells|date=26 May 2011|website=Blogging Shakespeare|accessdate=3 February 2018|url=http://bloggingshakespeare.com/the-first-great-shakespearian-actor|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |title = The Shakespearan Stage 1574\u20131642\n  |last = Gurr\n  |first = Andrew\n  |authorlink = Andrew Gurr\n  |location = Cambridge\n  |publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]]\n  |year = 1992\n  |edition = 3rd\n  |isbn = 9780521410052\n  |ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |title = A Shakespeare Companion 1564\u20131964\n  |last = Halliday\n  |first = F. E.\n  |authorlink = F. E. Halliday\n  |location = Baltimore\n  |publisher = [[Penguin Books|Penguin]]\n  |series = Penguin Reference Books\n  |volume = 27\n  |year = 1964\n  |edition = Revised\n  |oclc = 222822680\n  |ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |title = The Elizabethan Theatre and ''The Book of Sir Thomas More''\n  |last = McMillin\n  |first = Scott\n  |location = Ithaca, N.Y.\n  |publisher = [[Cornell University Press]]\n  |year = 1987\n  |isbn = 9780801420085\n  |ref = harv\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burbage, Richard}}\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:1568 births]]\n[[Category:1619 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of the Elizabethan era]]\n[[Category:People associated with Shakespeare]]\n[[Category:English male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:Theatre owners]]\n[[Category:16th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:17th-century English male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Skeenan00", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Burbage"}
{"title_page": "De Tomaso Pantera", "text_new": "{{short description|mid-engine sports car produced by Italian automobile manufacturer De Tomaso from 1971 to 1992}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = De Tomaso Pantera\n| image = De Tomaso Pantera GT5-S (7160836758).jpg\n| caption = De Tomaso Pantera GT5-S\n| manufacturer = [[De Tomaso|De Tomaso Automobili]]\n| assembly = Italy: [[Modena]]<ref name=\"danjedlicka.com\">1971-74 DeTomaso Pantera History by Dan Jedlicka: [http://www.danjedlicka.com/classic_cars/1971_74_detomaso_pantera.html 1971-74 DeTomaso Pantera History by Dan Jedlicka], accessdate: 8. July 2019</ref>\n| production = 1971-1992 (7,260 produced)<ref name=\"detomaso.it/gb/\">{{cite web|url=http://www.detomaso.it/gb/vetture/ieri/pantera.html|title=The Cars: Yesterday:pantera|accessdate=2008-08-09|work=detomaso.it/gb/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010628211627/http://www.detomaso.it/gb/vetture/ieri/pantera.html|archivedate=2001-06-28}}</ref>\n| designer = {{ubl\n|[[Tom Tjaarda]] at [[Ghia]]\n|[[Marcello Gandini]] (Pantera SI)\n}}\n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Rear mid-engine, rear-drive]]\n| engine = {{convert|351|CID|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[Ford 335 engine#351 Cleveland|''Ford Cleveland'' V8]]\n| powerout = \n| transmission = 5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2500|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <ref name=topspeed7191>[https://www.topspeed.com/cars/detomaso/1971-1991-de-tomaso-pantera-ar448.html 1971 - 1991 De Tomaso Pantera Review \u2013 Top Speed]</ref>\n| length = {{convert|158|in|mm|0|abbr=on|disp=flip}} \u2013 1971 spec <ref name=topspeed7191/><br>{{convert|4270|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} \u2013 later spec\n| width = {{convert|67|in|mm|0|abbr=on|disp=flip}} \u2013 1971 spec <ref name=topspeed7191/><br>{{convert|71.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on|disp=flip}} \u2013 later spec\n| height = {{convert|1100|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[De Tomaso Mangusta]]\n| successor = [[De Tomaso Guar\u00e0]]<br>[[Ares Design Project1]] (spiritual)\n}}\n\nThe '''De Tomaso Pantera''' is a [[mid-engine]] [[sports car]] produced by Italian automobile manufacturer [[De Tomaso]] from 1971 to 1993.<ref name=\"detomaso.it/gb/\"/> Italian for \"Panther\", the Pantera was the automaker's most popular model, with over 7,000 manufactured over its twenty-year production run.\n\n==History==\nThe Pantera was designed by the Italian design firm Ghia's American-born designer [[Tom Tjaarda]]<ref name=Motor197107/> and replaced the [[De Tomaso Mangusta|Mangusta]]. Unlike the Mangusta, which employed a [[steel]] backbone chassis, the Pantera's chassis was of a steel [[monocoque]] design, the first instance of De Tomaso using this construction technique. The Pantera logo included a T-shaped symbol that was the brand used by De Tomaso's Argentinian cattle ranching ancestors,<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.hemmings.com/hsx/stories/2010/04/01/hmn_feature16.html |title=De Tomaso: The Italian automaker's South American heritage is in its emblem|journal=Hemmings Sports & Exotic Car|date=April 2010 |first=Craig |last=Fitzgerals|accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref> as well as a version of the Argentinean flag turned on its side, inspired by the company's founder, Alejandro De Tomaso, having been born and raised in Argentina.\n\n[[File:Detomaso Pantera Interior.JPG|thumb|left|Interior (1972 model)]]\nThe car debuted in Modena in March 1970 and was presented at the 1970 [[New York International Auto Show|New York Motor Show]] a few weeks later.<ref name=Motor197107/> Approximately a year later the first production cars were sold, and production was increased to three per day.<ref name=Motor197107/>\n\nThe slat-backed seats which had attracted criticism at the New York Auto Show were replaced by more conventional body-hugging sports seats in the production cars: leg-room was generous but the pedals were off-set and headroom was insufficient for drivers above approximately {{cvt|6|ft|m|0|abbr=on}} tall.<ref name=Motor197107/> Reflecting its makers' transatlantic ambitions, the Pantera came with an abundance of standard features which appeared exotic in Europe, such as electric windows, air conditioning and even \"doors that buzz when ... open\".<ref name=Motor197107/> By the time the Pantera reached production stage, the interior was in most respects well sorted, although resting an arm on the central console could lead to inadvertently activating the poorly located cigarette lighter.<ref name=Motor197107/>\n\nThe first 1971 Pantera models were powered by a {{convert|351|CID|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[Ford 335 engine#351 Cleveland|''Ford Cleveland'' V8 engine]] having a power output of {{convert|335|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. The high torque provided by the Ford engine reduced the need for excessive gear changing at low speeds: this made the car much less demanding to drive in urban conditions than many of the locally built offerings.<ref name=Motor197107/>\n\nThe [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] [[transaxle]] used in the Mangusta was also used for the Pantera: a passenger in an early Pantera recorded that the mechanical noises emanating from the transaxle were more intrusive than the well restrained engine noise.<ref name=Motor197107/> Another Italian car that shares the ZF transaxle is the [[Maserati Bora]], also launched in 1971 although not yet available for sale.<ref name=Motor19710710>{{cite journal| first=Paul |last=Fr\u00e8re |title=Continental Diary....Up to now only two Bora have been built| journal =The Motor| volume = | pages=30\u201331|date =10 July 1971}}</ref> Power-assisted four-wheel [[disc brake]]s and [[rack and pinion]] steering were all standard equipment on the Pantera. The 1971 Pantera could accelerate to 97&nbsp;km/h (60&nbsp;mph) in 5.5 seconds according to ''[[Car and Driver]]''.\n\nIn the summer of 1971, a visitor to the De Tomaso plant at [[Modena]] identified two different types of Pantera awaiting shipment, being respectively the European and American versions.<ref name=Motor197107>{{cite journal|first=Pete |last=Coltrin | title =Leave the Homburg at home: [Report of a visit to the de Tomaso plant]| journal=The Motor| volume = | pages=29|date=10 July 1971}}</ref> From outside, the principal differences were the larger tail lamps on the cars destined for America, along with addition of corner marker lamps.<ref name=Motor197107/> The visitor was impressed by the large number of cars awaiting shipment; in reality, spending the best part of a year under dust covers in a series of large hangars probably did nothing for the cash-flow of the business by the time they crossed the Atlantic. \n\n{{Listen\n |filename =De Tomaso Pantera (1974).ogg\n |title    =De Tomaso Pantera at Goodwood Festival of Speed 2010\n |type     =sound\n |style    =float:right;clear:none\n}}\n\n===In the United States===\n[[File:1973 DeTomaso Pantera (931878515).jpg|thumb|left|The 1973 De Tomaso Pantera L, with bigger \"safety bumpers\"]]\n[[File:1983 De Tomaso Pantera GTS (US market), front right.jpg|thumb|Pantera GTS (US model)]]\nLate in 1971, Ford began importing the Pantera for the American market to be sold through its [[Lincoln (automobile)|Lincoln]] [[Mercury (automobile)|Mercury]] dealers. The first 75 cars were simply European imports and are known for their \"push-button\" door handles and hand-built [[Carrozzeria Vignale]] bodies. A total of 1,007 cars reached the United States that year. As with most Italian cars of the day, rust-proofing was minimal and the quality of fit and finish on these early models was poor with large amounts of [[body solder]] being used to cover body panel flaws. Subsequently, Ford increased their involvement in the production of the later cars with the introduction of precision stampings for body panels which resulted in improved overall quality.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pantera International |url=http://panterainternational.org/detomaso_history/fords_pantera.html}}</ref> \n \nSeveral modifications were made to the Pantera for the 1972 model year. A new {{cvt|351|cuin|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[4 Bolt Main]] [[Cleveland Engine]], was used with lower [[compression ratio]] (from 11:1 to 8.6:1, chiefly to meet US emissions standards and run on lower octane standard fuel) but with the more aggressive \"Cobra Jet\" camshaft (featuring the same lift and duration as the [[Ford Mustang (first generation)|428 Cobra Jet]]'s factory performance cam) in an effort to reclaim some of the power lost through the reduction in compression ratio along with a dual point distributor. Many other engine changes were made, including the use of a factory [[Exhaust manifold|exhaust header]].\n\nThe \"Lusso\" (luxury) '''Pantera L''' was also introduced in August 1972 as a 1972\u00bd model. For the US market, it featured a large black single front bumper that incorporated a built-in airfoil to reduce front end lift at high speeds, rather than the separate bumperettes still used abroad, as well as the Cleveland engine now having a power output of {{cvt|266|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}. The \"L\" model featured many factory upgrades and updates that fixed most of the problems and issues the earlier cars experienced. It was so improved that the 1973 DeTomaso Pantera was Road Test Magazine's Import car of the year beating offerings from Ferrari, Maserati, Lamborghini, and Porsche. During 1973 the dashboard was changed, deviating from two separate pods for the gauges to a unified unit with the dials angled towards the driver. The U.S. version of the 1974 '''Pantera GTS''' featured optional GTS badging but not the higher compression, solid lifter engine of its European GTS \"cousin\".\n\n=== Disengagement of Ford ===\n[[File:De Tomaso Pantera GT5.jpg|thumb|right|De Tomaso Pantera GT5]]\nFord stopped importing the Pantera to the US in 1975, having sold around 5,500 cars. De Tomaso continued to build the car in ever-escalating forms of performance and luxury for almost two decades for sale in the rest of the world. A small number of cars were imported to the US by [[Grey import vehicles|gray market]] importers in the 1980s, notably Panteramerica and AmeriSport. After 1974, Ford discontinued the Cleveland 351 engine, but production continued in Australia until 1982. De Tomaso started sourcing their engines from Australia once the American supplies stopped. These engines were tuned in Switzerland and were available with a range of outputs up to {{convert|360|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"AK87\">{{cite book|title=Auto Katalog 1987|publisher=[[:de:Motor Presse Stuttgart|Vereinigte Motor-Verlage GmbH & Co. KG]]|editor-last=Heitz|editor-first=Rudolf|location=Stuttgart|page=120|volume=30|language=German|date=1 August 1986}}</ref>\n[[File:1976 DeTomaso Pantera GT5S.jpg|thumb|Pantera GT5-S having wide steel fenders]]\nAccording to De Tomaso the chassis was completely revised in 1980, beginning with chassis number 9000.<ref name=Pantparts>{{citation | title = De Tomaso Pantera: Parts & Accessories | publisher = De Tomaso Automobili SpA | location =  | date = 1986 | url = http://www.pim.net/WebPIMCatalog2009.pdf | pages = 2\u20133 }}</ref> From May 1980, the lineup included the GT5, which had bonded and riveted-on fibreglass wheelarch extensions and from November 1984 the GT5-S model which had blended arches and a distinctive wide-body look.<ref name=Pantparts/> The GT5 also incorporated better brakes, a more luxurious interior, much larger wheels and tires and the fiberglass body kit also included an air dam and side skirts. Production of the wide body GT5 (and similarly equipped narrow body GTS models) continued until 1985, when the GT5-S replaced the GT5. Although the factory has not made its records available, an analysis based on [[Vehicle Identification Number]]s by the Pantera Owners Club of America (POCA) late model (9000 series) registrar has shown that fewer than 252 GT5 Pantera models were likely to have been built. The GT5-S featured single piece flared steel fenders instead of the GT5's bolted-on fiberglass flares, and a smaller steel front air dam. The 'S' in the GT5-S name stood for \"steel\". Otherwise the GT5-S was largely identical to the GT5. The POCA 9000 series registrar's VIN analysis indicates that fewer than 183 GT5-S Panteras were built. Concurrent GTS production continued, on a custom order and very limited basis, until the late 1980s.\n\nThe car continued to use a Ford V8 engine, although in 1988, when the supply of Ford 351 Cleveland engines from Australia ran out, De Tomaso began installing [[Ford small block engine#351W|Ford 351 Windsor engines]] in the Pantera instead. In all, about 7,200 cars in total were built.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Pantera Si==\n[[File:1990 De Tomaso Pantera Si.jpg|thumb|DeTomaso Pantera Si]]\nFor 1990 the 351 engine was replaced by the Ford 302 engine {{cvt|302|cuin|L|abbr=on}} engine and the Pantera received new styling penned by [[Marcello Gandini]], suspension redesign and a partial chassis redesign. The new model was called the Pantera 90 Si and it was introduced in 1990. Only 38 90 Si models were sold before the Pantera was finally phased out in 1993 to make way for the radical [[De Tomaso Guar\u00e0|Guar\u00e0]]. Some sources state that 41 were built (with the last one not finished until 1996), of which four were targa models. The targas were converted by Pavesi directly off the production lines. In the UK, the model was sold as Pantera 90.\n\n==Specifications==\n[[File:De Tomaso Pantera Series II Front.jpg|thumb|right|A one-off second generation Pantera prototype made by [[Ghia]].<ref name=\"italiaspeed.com/2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.italiaspeed.com/2008/cars/others/de_tomaso/05/villa_deste/0205.html|date=2008-03-05 |title=Long Forgotten Pantera Prototype Resurfaces at Villa d'Este|accessdate=2008-07-18|work=italiaspeed.com/2008}}</ref>]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+[[Model year]]\n!Specification data\n!1971 L<ref name=\"1971L\">{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1971/695495/de_tomaso_pantera.html\n|title=1971 De Tomaso Pantera L\n|website=automobile-catalog.com\n|editor=Pawel Zal\n|accessdate=September 23, 2018}}</ref>\n!1988 GT5 S <ref name=\"GT5S\">{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1988/695810/de_tomaso_pantera_gt5s.html|title=1988 De Tomaso Pantera GT5 S (man. 5) specifications|website=automobile-catalog.com|language=en-us|access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Engine configuration]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\" |{{convert|351|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Naturally aspirated]] [[Ford 335 engine#351 Cleveland|Ford Cleveland V8]]\n|-\n|Fuel system\n|[[Autolite]] 4-barrel [[carburetor]]\n|[[Holley Performance Products|Holley]] 4-barrel carburetor\n|-\n|[[Curb weight]]\n|{{convert|3123|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|3250|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|[[Wheelbase]]\n|{{convert|98.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|98.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|Front track\n|{{convert|57.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|59.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|Rear track\n|{{convert|58.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|62.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|Length\n|{{convert|158.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|168.1|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|Width\n|{{convert|67.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|77.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|Height\n|{{convert|43.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|43.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|[[Brake]]s\n|Front: {{convert|279|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} ventilated;<br/>Rear: {{convert|302|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} ventilated<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.supercars.net/blog/1974-detomaso-pantera-l/\n|website=Supercars.net\n|title=1974 De Tomaso Pantera L}}</ref>\n|Front: {{convert|284|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} ventilated;<br/>Rear: {{convert|297|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} ventilated<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.supercars.net/blog/1985-detomaso-pantera-gt5-s/\n|website=Supercars.net\n|title=1985 De Tomaso Pantera GT5-S}}</ref>\n|-\n|Power\n|{{convert|326|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 5,400 rpm\n|{{convert|350|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 6,000 rpm\n|-\n|Torque\n|{{convert|466|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on|order=flip}} at 3,500 rpm\n|{{convert|451|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on|order=flip}} at 3,800 rpm\n|-\n|Fuel economy\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\" |Highway (Extra-urban): {{convert|14.6|mpgus|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"1971L\"/><ref name=\"GT5S\"/><ref name=\"Willson2\">{{cite book|title=The Ultimate Classic Car Book|last=Willson|first=Quentin|publisher=DK Publishing, Inc.|year=1995|isbn=0-7894-0159-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ultimateclassicc00quen}}</ref>\n|-\n|Compression ratio\n|11.0:1\n|9.5:1\n|-\n|Gearbox\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\" |5-speed [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] [[manual transmission]]\n|-\n|Maximum speed\n|{{convert|159|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Willson2\" />\n|{{convert|174|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"GT5S\"/>\n|}\n\n==Motorsports==\n===Group 3===\n[[File:Paris - Bonhams 2014 - De Tomaso Pantera Group 3 - 1972 - 001.jpg|thumb|left|A De Tomaso Pantera GTS Group 3 prototype]]\n\nDe Tomaso offered a Pantera competition car built to special order according to the Group 3 class racing rules between 1972 and 1984 based on the Pantera GTS. 30 cars were built for private customer teams. Group 3 rules were very strict and allowed little modifications to the original road going production cars. Earlier Group 3 cars are infamously called \"push button\" chassis cars as they were built by hand because De Tomaso didn't have a proper assembly line when the Pantera began production. Special equipment of the Group 3 cars included Campagnolo wheels (15 x 8 inches at the front and 15 x 10 inches at the rear), adjustable Koni shocks, racing brakes and special safety equipment required at the time: plexi-glass windows with cutouts, a roll bar, fire extinguisher and racing bucket seats. The engine modifications included a reinforced camshaft, a 10-litre oil pan and a Holley racing 4 barrel carburetor. Displacement of the engine was also enlarged to 5.8-litres. The engine had a power output of {{cvt|336|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. The engine was mated to a 5-speed close ratio gearbox with a heavy duty single plate clutch and a limited slip differential. It was reported that with the long ratio gears, the Group 3 cars could achieve a top speed up to {{cvt|280|kph|mph|0|abbr=on}}. The Group 3 cars were so competitive that this prompted Porsche to speed up development of the more powerful 911 Carrera RS and Carrera RSR race cars. The use of racing brakes for the Pantera Group 3 was not allowed until 1975 and the car competed with the brakes of the road legal Pantera which proved to be its weak point. Due to an accident in 1973 at the Charade circuit, reinforced hubs developed by De Tomaso for the Group 3 car were approved in Group 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/17043/lot/136/?category=list|title=1973 DE TOMASO PANTERA GP3, 1973 De Tomaso Pantera Group 3 Coup\u00e9 Chassis no. 2006|date=2009-02-07|publisher=[[Bonhams]]|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://detomasodc.co.uk/pantera-gts|title=Pantera GTS|work=De Tomaso Driver's Club|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n===Group 4===\n[[File:De Tomaso Pantera GTS Group 4 Gen1 000 1972 frontleft 2013-03-17 U.jpg|thumb|left|A De Tomaso Pantera GTS Group 4 competition car]]\n\nAfter the Pantera had begun production, De Tomaso introduced a motorsport oriented Group 3 version of the car. This was followed by a modified Group 4 version in 1972. British engineer and driver Mike Parkes, who had previously developed racing cars for Ferrari was tasked with the development of the new car.\n\nAs per the regulations, the Group 4 car was based around the road car's steel monocoque chassis. The double wishbone suspension was substantially modified and Koni adjustable shocks were used in order to improve handling at the track and make room for wider Campagnolo wheels and tyres. Bigger ventilated brakes supplied by Girling and a quick ratio steering rack were used to refine handling and stopping power. The standard steel body shell of the Pantera also received modifications such as aluminium doors, front lid and engine cover along with flared fibre glass wheel arches in order to accommodate the wide wheels and tyres. Plexi glass windows were used throughout and holes were cut into the chassis where possible in order to reduce weight. The car had no front or rear bumpers and a front deep chin spoiler. It also didn't had any rustproofing and interior amenities. The interior was fitted with a cut-off switch instead of a radio, light weight cloth bucket racing seats, a vinyl trim, a roll-cage and drilled aluminium pedals. The final car had a weight of {{cvt|1100|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nFord, providing a good amount of financial backing in the development of the road going Pantera had little interest in the motorsport version of the car and refused to supply engines for the Group 4 Pantera. De Tomaso engaged a private US based engine builder Bud Moore to supply engines for the car.\n\nBased on the same Ford 351 Cleveland V8 engine used in the road going Pantera, the engine in the Group 4 Pantera was fitted with bespoke aluminium heads, TRW forged pistons, large capacity oil pans and titanium valves. Initially, a single Holley Racing 1150 CFM four barrel carburetor was fitted but this was replaced by four Weber carburetors and a revised intake. The engine had a higher compression ratio of 12.0:1. Displacement of the racing engine was unchanged from road going Pantera's engine. The \"spaghetti\" styled exhaust system similar to the one used in the [[Ford GT40]] was used. The engine had a claimed power output of {{cvt|507|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. Although the cars ran at a power output of {{cvt|446|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 7,000 rpm which was increased to {{cvt|477|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} when the Weber 850 CFM carburetors were used. The engine was mated to a ZF 5-speed close ratio manual transmission with a heavy duty single clutch plate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.janluehn.com/cars/1974-de-tomaso-pantera-group-4|title=De Tomaso Pantera Group 4|publisher=Jan B Leuhn|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\nThe first Group 4 Panteras were entered into the 1972 24 Hours of LeMans. The problems of the car then began to become apparent. The engine proved to be unreliable and the car was also subject to a weight penalty, increasing the weight to {{cvt|1250|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}. This was set reportedly high due to [[Porsche]]'s influence over the governing body of the race. Another problem of the car was the rigidity of its chassis. Nevertheless, the car continued to compete in Group 4 and the engine problem was addressed by sourcing replacement engines with a lower compression ratio. A total of 14 Group 4 cars were made. Some Group 3 cars were modified to Group 4 specifications by privateers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultimatecarpage.com/txt/6263/2/DeTomaso-Pantera-Group-4.html|title=De Tomaso Pantera Group 4|date=2015-06-17|first=Wouter|last=Melissen|publisher=Ultimate Car Page|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n===Group 5===\n[[File:De Tomaso Pantera Mallory Park.JPG|thumb|right|De Tomaso Pantera Group 5 competition car]]\n\nThe Group 5 Pantera race cars were converted by private racing teams from Group 4 and Group 3 cars and competed in Group 5 class racing from 1976 to 1981. The Group 5 cars only had wider body panels and no significant design, mechanical and chassis modifications.\n\nHowever, two cars were extensively modified to compete in the IMSA GTX and Group 5 class respectively. The first car having chassis number #001 was constructed from a new chassis by Italian racing team Sala and Marveti. The second car, having chassis number #1603 was a Group 4 car campaigned by Hugh Kleinpeter in the US and then underwent modification. Afterwards, the former was converted to Group C class specifications in 1983 and the latter was converted to IMSA GTP class specifications respectively. Both cars were uncompetitive in their categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gr5pantera.com/gr-5-panteras|title=Gr 5 Panteras, 1976 - 1981|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[AMC AMX#AMX/3]] - first shown a month earlier, and sometimes confused with.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|De Tomaso Pantera}}\n* (August, 1971) ''[[Car and Driver]]''\n* [http://www.poca.com Pantera Owners Club of America]\n* [http://www.DeTomasoRegistry.org The DeTomaso Registry]\n* [http://carplusautoblog.com/de-tomaso-pantera-the-top-speed-car/ Tomaso Pantera Review]\n\n{{De Tomaso}}\n\n[[Category:De Tomaso vehicles|Pantera]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Group 4 cars]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1970]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|mid-engine sports car produced by Italian automobile manufacturer De Tomaso from 1971 to 1992}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = De Tomaso Pantera\n| image = De Tomaso Pantera GT5-S (7160836758).jpg\n| caption = De Tomaso Pantera GT5-S\n| manufacturer = [[De Tomaso|De Tomaso Automobili]]\n| assembly = Italy: [[Modena]]<ref name=\"danjedlicka.com\">1971-74 DeTomaso Pantera History by Dan Jedlicka: [http://www.danjedlicka.com/classic_cars/1971_74_detomaso_pantera.html 1971-74 DeTomaso Pantera History by Dan Jedlicka], accessdate: 8. July 2019</ref>\n| production = 1971-1992 (7,260 produced)<ref name=\"detomaso.it/gb/\">{{cite web|url=http://www.detomaso.it/gb/vetture/ieri/pantera.html|title=The Cars: Yesterday:pantera|accessdate=2008-08-09|work=detomaso.it/gb/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010628211627/http://www.detomaso.it/gb/vetture/ieri/pantera.html|archivedate=2001-06-28}}</ref>\n| designer = {{ubl\n|[[Tom Tjaarda]] at [[Ghia]]\n|[[Marcello Gandini]] (Pantera SI)\n}}\n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Rear mid-engine, rear-drive]]\n| engine = {{convert|351|CID|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[Ford 335 engine#351 Cleveland|''Ford Cleveland'' V8]]\n| powerout = \n| transmission = 5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2500|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} <ref name=topspeed7191>[https://www.topspeed.com/cars/detomaso/1971-1991-de-tomaso-pantera-ar448.html 1971 - 1991 De Tomaso Pantera Review \u2013 Top Speed]</ref>\n| length = {{convert|158|in|mm|0|abbr=on|disp=flip}} \u2013 1971 spec <ref name=topspeed7191/><br>{{convert|4270|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} \u2013 later spec\n| width = {{convert|67|in|mm|0|abbr=on|disp=flip}} \u2013 1971 spec <ref name=topspeed7191/><br>{{convert|71.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on|disp=flip}} \u2013 later spec\n| height = {{convert|1100|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[De Tomaso Mangusta]]\n| successor = [[De Tomaso Guar\u00e0]]<br>[[Ares Design Project1]] (spiritual)\n}}\n\nThe '''De Tomaso Pantera''' is a [[mid-engine]] [[sports car]] produced by Italian automobile manufacturer [[De Tomaso]] from 1971 to 1993.<ref name=\"detomaso.it/gb/\"/> Italian for \"Panther\", the Pantera was the automaker's most popular model, with over 7,000 manufactured over its twenty-year production run.\n\n==History==\nThe Pantera was designed by the Italian design firm Ghia's American-born designer [[Tom Tjaarda]]<ref name=Motor197107/> and replaced the [[De Tomaso Mangusta|Mangusta]]. Unlike the Mangusta, which employed a [[steel]] backbone chassis, the Pantera's chassis was of a steel [[monocoque]] design, the first instance of De Tomaso using this construction technique. The Pantera logo included a T-shaped symbol that was the brand used by De Tomaso's Argentinian cattle ranching ancestors,<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.hemmings.com/hsx/stories/2010/04/01/hmn_feature16.html |title=De Tomaso: The Italian automaker's South American heritage is in its emblem|journal=Hemmings Sports & Exotic Car|date=April 2010 |first=Craig |last=Fitzgerals|accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref> as well as a version of the Argentinean flag turned on its side, inspired by the company's founder, Alejandro De Tomaso, having been born and raised in Argentina.\n\n[[File:Detomaso Pantera Interior.JPG|thumb|left|Interior (1972 model)]]\nThe car debuted in Modena in March 1970 and was presented at the 1970 [[New York International Auto Show|New York Motor Show]] a few weeks later.<ref name=Motor197107/> Approximately a year later the first production cars were sold, and production was increased to three per day.<ref name=Motor197107/>\n\nThe slat-backed seats which had attracted criticism at the New York Auto Show were replaced by more conventional body-hugging sports seats in the production cars: leg-room was generous but the pedals were off-set and headroom was insufficient for drivers above approximately {{cvt|6|ft|m|0|abbr=on}} tall.<ref name=Motor197107/> Reflecting its makers' transatlantic ambitions, the Pantera came with an abundance of standard features which appeared exotic in Europe, such as electric windows, air conditioning and even \"doors that buzz when ... open\".<ref name=Motor197107/> By the time the Pantera reached production stage, the interior was in most respects well sorted, although resting an arm on the central console could lead to inadvertently activating the poorly located cigarette lighter.<ref name=Motor197107/>\n\nThe first 1971 Pantera models were powered by a {{convert|351|CID|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[Ford 335 engine#351 Cleveland|''Ford Cleveland'' V8 engine]] having a power output of {{convert|335|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. The high torque provided by the Ford engine reduced the need for excessive gear changing at low speeds: this made the car much less demanding to drive in urban conditions than many of the locally built offerings.<ref name=Motor197107/>\n\nThe [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] [[transaxle]] used in the Mangusta was also used for the Pantera: a passenger in an early Pantera recorded that the mechanical noises emanating from the transaxle were more intrusive than the well restrained engine noise.<ref name=Motor197107/> Another Italian car that shares the ZF transaxle is the [[Maserati Bora]], also launched in 1971 although not yet available for sale.<ref name=Motor19710710>{{cite journal| first=Paul |last=Fr\u00e8re |title=Continental Diary....Up to now only two Bora have been built| journal =The Motor| volume = | pages=30\u201331|date =10 July 1971}}</ref> Power-assisted four-wheel [[disc brake]]s and [[rack and pinion]] steering were all standard equipment on the Pantera. The 1971 Pantera could accelerate to 97&nbsp;km/h (60&nbsp;mph) in 5.5 seconds according to ''[[Car and Driver]]''.\n\nIn the summer of 1971, a visitor to the De Tomaso plant at [[Modena]] identified two different types of Pantera awaiting shipment, being respectively the European and American versions.<ref name=Motor197107>{{cite journal|first=Pete |last=Coltrin | title =Leave the Homburg at home: [Report of a visit to the de Tomaso plant]| journal=The Motor| volume = | pages=29|date=10 July 1971}}</ref> From outside, the principal differences were the larger tail lamps on the cars destined for America, along with addition of corner marker lamps.<ref name=Motor197107/> The visitor was impressed by the large number of cars awaiting shipment; in reality, spending the best part of a year under dust covers in a series of large hangars probably did nothing for the cash-flow of the business by the time they crossed the Atlantic. \n\n{{Listen\n |filename =De Tomaso Pantera (1974).ogg\n |title    =De Tomaso Pantera at Goodwood Festival of Speed 2010\n |type     =sound\n |style    =float:right;clear:none\n}}\n\n===In the United States===\n[[File:1973 DeTomaso Pantera (931878515).jpg|thumb|left|The 1973 De Tomaso Pantera L, with bigger \"safety bumpers\"]]\n[[File:1983 De Tomaso Pantera GTS (US market), front right.jpg|thumb|Pantera GTS (US model)]]\nLate in 1971, Ford began importing the Pantera for the American market to be sold through its [[Lincoln (automobile)|Lincoln]] [[Mercury (automobile)|Mercury]] dealers. The first 75 cars were simply European imports and are known for their \"push-button\" door handles and hand-built [[Carrozzeria Vignale]] bodies. A total of 1,007 cars reached the United States that year. As with most Italian cars of the day, rust-proofing was minimal and the quality of fit and finish on these early models was poor with large amounts of [[body solder]] being used to cover body panel flaws. Subsequently, Ford increased their involvement in the production of the later cars with the introduction of precision stampings for body panels which resulted in improved overall quality.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pantera International |url=http://panterainternational.org/detomaso_history/fords_pantera.html}}</ref> \n \nSeveral modifications were made to the Pantera for the 1972 model year. A new {{cvt|351|cuin|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[4 Bolt Main]] [[Cleveland Engine]], was used with lower [[compression ratio]] (from 11:1 to 8.6:1, chiefly to meet US emissions standards and run on lower octane standard fuel) but with the more aggressive \"Cobra Jet\" camshaft (featuring the same lift and duration as the [[Ford Mustang (first generation)|428 Cobra Jet]]'s factory performance cam) in an effort to reclaim some of the power lost through the reduction in compression ratio along with a dual point distributor. Many other engine changes were made, including the use of a factory [[Exhaust manifold|exhaust header]].\n\nThe \"Lusso\" (luxury) '''Pantera L''' was also introduced in August 1972 as a 1972\u00bd model. For the US market, it featured a large black single front bumper that incorporated a built-in airfoil to reduce front end lift at high speeds, rather than the separate bumperettes still used abroad, as well as the Cleveland engine now having a power output of {{cvt|266|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}. The \"L\" model featured many factory upgrades and updates that fixed most of the problems and issues the earlier cars experienced. It was so improved that the 1973 DeTomaso Pantera was Road Test Magazine's Import car of the year beating offerings from Ferrari, Maserati, Lamborghini, and Porsche. During 1973 the dashboard was changed, deviating from two separate pods for the gauges to a unified unit with the dials angled towards the driver. The U.S. version of the 1974 '''Pantera GTS''' featured optional GTS badging but not the higher compression, solid lifter engine of its European GTS \"cousin\".\n\n=== Disengagement of Ford ===\n[[File:De Tomaso Pantera GT5.jpg|thumb|right|De Tomaso Pantera GT5]]\nFord stopped importing the Pantera to the US in 1975, having sold around 5,500 cars. De Tomaso continued to build the car in ever-escalating forms of performance and luxury for almost two decades for sale in the rest of the world. A small number of cars were imported to the US by [[Grey import vehicles|gray market]] importers in the 1980s, notably Panteramerica and AmeriSport. After 1974, Ford discontinued the Cleveland 351 engine, but production continued in Australia until 1982. De Tomaso started sourcing their engines from Australia once the American supplies stopped. These engines were tuned in Switzerland and were available with a range of outputs up to {{convert|360|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"AK87\">{{cite book|title=Auto Katalog 1987|publisher=[[:de:Motor Presse Stuttgart|Vereinigte Motor-Verlage GmbH & Co. KG]]|editor-last=Heitz|editor-first=Rudolf|location=Stuttgart|page=120|volume=30|language=German|date=1 August 1986}}</ref>\n[[File:1976 DeTomaso Pantera GT5S.jpg|thumb|Pantera GT5-S having wide steel fenders]]\nAccording to De Tomaso the chassis was completely revised in 1980, beginning with chassis number 9000.<ref name=Pantparts>{{citation | title = De Tomaso Pantera: Parts & Accessories | publisher = De Tomaso Automobili SpA | location =  | date = 1986 | url = http://www.pim.net/WebPIMCatalog2009.pdf | pages = 2\u20133 }}</ref> From May 1980, the lineup included the GT5, which had bonded and riveted-on fibreglass wheelarch extensions and from November 1984 the GT5-S model which had blended arches and a distinctive wide-body look.<ref name=Pantparts/> The GT5 also incorporated better brakes, a more luxurious interior, much larger wheels and tires and the fiberglass body kit also included an air dam and side skirts. Production of the wide body GT5 (and similarly equipped narrow body GTS models) continued until 1985, when the GT5-S replaced the GT5. Although the factory has not made its records available, an analysis based on [[Vehicle Identification Number]]s by the Pantera Owners Club of America (POCA) late model (9000 series) registrar has shown that fewer than 252 GT5 Pantera models were likely to have been built. The GT5-S featured single piece flared steel fenders instead of the GT5's bolted-on fiberglass flares, and a smaller steel front air dam. The 'S' in the GT5-S name stood for \"steel\". Otherwise the GT5-S was largely identical to the GT5. The POCA 9000 series registrar's VIN analysis indicates that fewer than 183 GT5-S Panteras were built. Concurrent GTS production continued, on a custom order and very limited basis, until the late 1980s.\n\nThe car continued to use a Ford V8 engine, although in 1988, when the supply of Ford 351 Cleveland engines from Australia ran out, De Tomaso began installing [[Ford small block engine#351W|Ford 351 Windsor engines]] in the Pantera instead. In all, about 7,200 cars in total were built.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Pantera Si==\n[[File:1990 De Tomaso Pantera Si.jpg|thumb|DeTomaso Pantera Si]]\nFor 1990 the 351 engine was replaced by the Ford 302 engine {{cvt|302|cuin|L|abbr=on}} engine and the Pantera received new styling penned by [[Marcello Gandini]], suspension redesign and a partial chassis redesign. The new model was called the Pantera 90 Si and it was introduced in 1990. Only 38 90 Si models were sold before the Pantera was finally phased out in 1993 to make way for the radical [[De Tomaso Guar\u00e0|Guar\u00e0]]. Some sources state that 41 were built (with the last one not finished until 1996), of which four were targa models. The targas were converted by Pavesi directly off the production lines. In the UK, the model was sold as Pantera 90.\n\n==Specifications==\n[[File:De Tomaso Pantera Series II Front.jpg|thumb|right|A one-off second generation Pantera prototype made by [[Ghia]].<ref name=\"italiaspeed.com/2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.italiaspeed.com/2008/cars/others/de_tomaso/05/villa_deste/0205.html|date=2008-03-05 |title=Long Forgotten Pantera Prototype Resurfaces at Villa d'Este|accessdate=2008-07-18|work=italiaspeed.com/2008}}</ref>]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+[[Model year]]\n!Specification data\n!1971 L<ref name=\"1971L\">{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1971/695495/de_tomaso_pantera.html\n|title=1971 De Tomaso Pantera L\n|website=automobile-catalog.com\n|editor=Pawel Zal\n|accessdate=September 23, 2018}}</ref>\n!1988 GT5 S <ref name=\"GT5S\">{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1988/695810/de_tomaso_pantera_gt5s.html|title=1988 De Tomaso Pantera GT5 S (man. 5) specifications|website=automobile-catalog.com|language=en-us|access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Engine configuration]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\" |{{convert|351|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Naturally aspirated]] [[Ford 335 engine#351 Cleveland|Ford Cleveland V8]]\n|-\n|Fuel system\n|[[Autolite]] 4-barrel [[carburetor]]\n|[[Holley Performance Products|Holley]] 4-barrel carburetor\n|-\n|[[Curb weight]]\n|{{convert|3123|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|3250|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|[[Wheelbase]]\n|{{convert|98.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|98.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|Front track\n|{{convert|57.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|59.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|Rear track\n|{{convert|58.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|62.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|Length\n|{{convert|158.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|168.1|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|Width\n|{{convert|67.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|77.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|Height\n|{{convert|43.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{convert|43.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|[[Brake]]s\n|Front: 332 x 32 [[ventilated disc brake|ventilated discs]] and cross-drilled;<br/>Rear: 314 x 28 ventilated<br/>(1971 models had 15-inch wheels and brake rotors were smaller than {{convert|300|mm|in|1|abbr=on}})\n|Front: {{convert|284|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} ventilated;<br/>Rear: {{convert|297|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} ventilated<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.supercars.net/blog/1985-detomaso-pantera-gt5-s/\n|website=Supercars.net\n|title=1985 De Tomaso Pantera GT5-S}}</ref>\n|-\n|Power\n|{{convert|326|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 5,400 rpm\n|{{convert|350|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 6,000 rpm\n|-\n|Torque\n|{{convert|466|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on|order=flip}} at 3,500 rpm\n|{{convert|451|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on|order=flip}} at 3,800 rpm\n|-\n|Fuel economy\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\" |Highway (Extra-urban): {{convert|14.6|mpgus|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"1971L\"/><ref name=\"GT5S\"/><ref name=\"Willson2\">{{cite book|title=The Ultimate Classic Car Book|last=Willson|first=Quentin|publisher=DK Publishing, Inc.|year=1995|isbn=0-7894-0159-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ultimateclassicc00quen}}</ref>\n|-\n|Compression ratio\n|11.0:1\n|9.5:1\n|-\n|Gearbox\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\" |5-speed [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] [[manual transmission]]\n|-\n|Maximum speed\n|{{convert|159|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Willson2\" />\n|{{convert|174|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"GT5S\"/>\n|}\n\n==Motorsports==\n===Group 3===\n[[File:Paris - Bonhams 2014 - De Tomaso Pantera Group 3 - 1972 - 001.jpg|thumb|left|A De Tomaso Pantera GTS Group 3 prototype]]\n\nDe Tomaso offered a Pantera competition car built to special order according to the Group 3 class racing rules between 1972 and 1984 based on the Pantera GTS. 30 cars were built for private customer teams. Group 3 rules were very strict and allowed little modifications to the original road going production cars. Earlier Group 3 cars are infamously called \"push button\" chassis cars as they were built by hand because De Tomaso didn't have a proper assembly line when the Pantera began production. Special equipment of the Group 3 cars included Campagnolo wheels (15 x 8 inches at the front and 15 x 10 inches at the rear), adjustable Koni shocks, racing brakes and special safety equipment required at the time: plexi-glass windows with cutouts, a roll bar, fire extinguisher and racing bucket seats. The engine modifications included a reinforced camshaft, a 10-litre oil pan and a Holley racing 4 barrel carburetor. Displacement of the engine was also enlarged to 5.8-litres. The engine had a power output of {{cvt|336|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. The engine was mated to a 5-speed close ratio gearbox with a heavy duty single plate clutch and a limited slip differential. It was reported that with the long ratio gears, the Group 3 cars could achieve a top speed up to {{cvt|280|kph|mph|0|abbr=on}}. The Group 3 cars were so competitive that this prompted Porsche to speed up development of the more powerful 911 Carrera RS and Carrera RSR race cars. The use of racing brakes for the Pantera Group 3 was not allowed until 1975 and the car competed with the brakes of the road legal Pantera which proved to be its weak point. Due to an accident in 1973 at the Charade circuit, reinforced hubs developed by De Tomaso for the Group 3 car were approved in Group 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/17043/lot/136/?category=list|title=1973 DE TOMASO PANTERA GP3, 1973 De Tomaso Pantera Group 3 Coup\u00e9 Chassis no. 2006|date=2009-02-07|publisher=[[Bonhams]]|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://detomasodc.co.uk/pantera-gts|title=Pantera GTS|work=De Tomaso Driver's Club|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n===Group 4===\n[[File:De Tomaso Pantera GTS Group 4 Gen1 000 1972 frontleft 2013-03-17 U.jpg|thumb|left|A De Tomaso Pantera GTS Group 4 competition car]]\n\nAfter the Pantera had begun production, De Tomaso introduced a motorsport oriented Group 3 version of the car. This was followed by a modified Group 4 version in 1972. British engineer and driver Mike Parkes, who had previously developed racing cars for Ferrari was tasked with the development of the new car.\n\nAs per the regulations, the Group 4 car was based around the road car's steel monocoque chassis. The double wishbone suspension was substantially modified and Koni adjustable shocks were used in order to improve handling at the track and make room for wider Campagnolo wheels and tyres. Bigger ventilated brakes supplied by Girling and a quick ratio steering rack were used to refine handling and stopping power. The standard steel body shell of the Pantera also received modifications such as aluminium doors, front lid and engine cover along with flared fibre glass wheel arches in order to accommodate the wide wheels and tyres. Plexi glass windows were used throughout and holes were cut into the chassis where possible in order to reduce weight. The car had no front or rear bumpers and a front deep chin spoiler. It also didn't had any rustproofing and interior amenities. The interior was fitted with a cut-off switch instead of a radio, light weight cloth bucket racing seats, a vinyl trim, a roll-cage and drilled aluminium pedals. The final car had a weight of {{cvt|1100|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nFord, providing a good amount of financial backing in the development of the road going Pantera had little interest in the motorsport version of the car and refused to supply engines for the Group 4 Pantera. De Tomaso engaged a private US based engine builder Bud Moore to supply engines for the car.\n\nBased on the same Ford 351 Cleveland V8 engine used in the road going Pantera, the engine in the Group 4 Pantera was fitted with bespoke aluminium heads, TRW forged pistons, large capacity oil pans and titanium valves. Initially, a single Holley Racing 1150 CFM four barrel carburetor was fitted but this was replaced by four Weber carburetors and a revised intake. The engine had a higher compression ratio of 12.0:1. Displacement of the racing engine was unchanged from road going Pantera's engine. The \"spaghetti\" styled exhaust system similar to the one used in the [[Ford GT40]] was used. The engine had a claimed power output of {{cvt|507|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. Although the cars ran at a power output of {{cvt|446|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 7,000 rpm which was increased to {{cvt|477|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} when the Weber 850 CFM carburetors were used. The engine was mated to a ZF 5-speed close ratio manual transmission with a heavy duty single clutch plate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.janluehn.com/cars/1974-de-tomaso-pantera-group-4|title=De Tomaso Pantera Group 4|publisher=Jan B Leuhn|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\nThe first Group 4 Panteras were entered into the 1972 24 Hours of LeMans. The problems of the car then began to become apparent. The engine proved to be unreliable and the car was also subject to a weight penalty, increasing the weight to {{cvt|1250|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}. This was set reportedly high due to [[Porsche]]'s influence over the governing body of the race. Another problem of the car was the rigidity of its chassis. Nevertheless, the car continued to compete in Group 4 and the engine problem was addressed by sourcing replacement engines with a lower compression ratio. A total of 14 Group 4 cars were made. Some Group 3 cars were modified to Group 4 specifications by privateers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultimatecarpage.com/txt/6263/2/DeTomaso-Pantera-Group-4.html|title=De Tomaso Pantera Group 4|date=2015-06-17|first=Wouter|last=Melissen|publisher=Ultimate Car Page|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n===Group 5===\n[[File:De Tomaso Pantera Mallory Park.JPG|thumb|right|De Tomaso Pantera Group 5 competition car]]\n\nThe Group 5 Pantera race cars were converted by private racing teams from Group 4 and Group 3 cars and competed in Group 5 class racing from 1976 to 1981. The Group 5 cars only had wider body panels and no significant design, mechanical and chassis modifications.\n\nHowever, two cars were extensively modified to compete in the IMSA GTX and Group 5 class respectively. The first car having chassis number #001 was constructed from a new chassis by Italian racing team Sala and Marveti. The second car, having chassis number #1603 was a Group 4 car campaigned by Hugh Kleinpeter in the US and then underwent modification. Afterwards, the former was converted to Group C class specifications in 1983 and the latter was converted to IMSA GTP class specifications respectively. Both cars were uncompetitive in their categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gr5pantera.com/gr-5-panteras|title=Gr 5 Panteras, 1976 - 1981|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[AMC AMX#AMX/3]] - first shown a month earlier, and sometimes confused with.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|De Tomaso Pantera}}\n* (August, 1971) ''[[Car and Driver]]''\n* [http://www.poca.com Pantera Owners Club of America]\n* [http://www.DeTomasoRegistry.org The DeTomaso Registry]\n* [http://carplusautoblog.com/de-tomaso-pantera-the-top-speed-car/ Tomaso Pantera Review]\n\n{{De Tomaso}}\n\n[[Category:De Tomaso vehicles|Pantera]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Group 4 cars]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1970]]\n", "name_user": "Amagi82", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix brake sizes for 1970s era", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_Tomaso_Pantera"}
{"title_page": "John Grieve (poet)", "text_new": "'''John Grieve''' (12 September 1781 \u2013 4 April 1836), was a Scottish poet.\n\n==Early pursuits==\nJohn, son of the Rev. Walter Grieve, minister of the [[Reformed Presbyterian Church of Scotland|Reformed Presbyterian Church]], was born at [[Dunfermline]] on 12 Sept. 1781. He was educated at the parish school of [[Ettrick, Scotland|Ettrick]], where his father had settled on retiring from the ministry. After leaving school he was first a merchant's clerk in [[Alloa]], and then acted for some time as a bank clerk in [[Greenock]]; he returned to Alloa, however, to become a partner in the firm of his former employer. \nIn 1804, he began business in Edinburgh, in partnership with Mr. Chalmers Izzet, hat-maker.\n\n==He becomes a writer==\nHere he was successful, and found leisure for literary pursuits. He contributed to various periodicals, his most notable efforts being the songs which he wrote for the ''Forest Minstrel'' of [[James Hogg]]. He was on intimate terms with Hogg, who speaks of his literary advice as well as his material assistance. Hogg's ''Madoc of the Moor'' is dedicated to him, and he figures as a competing minstrel in the ''Queen's Wake''.\n \nIt was on Grieve's recommendation that the ''Queen's Wake'' was published, and in regard to the more generous support given him by Grieve and his partner, Hogg says that without this he could never have fought his way in Edinburgh: {{quote|\"I was fairly starved into it, and if it had not been for Messrs. Grieve and Scott would in a very short time have been starved out of it again.\"}}\nIn 1817, Grieve retired from business through ill-health. Until his death he was a well-known figure in Edinburgh literary society. He died unmarried on 4 April 1836, and was buried in St. Mary's, Yarrow.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/?id=gBEbAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA203&lpg=PA203&dq=John+Grieve+(poet)#v=onepage&q=John%20Grieve%20(poet)&f=false| title=The Scottish minstrel: the songs of Scotland subsequent to Burns, with memoirs of the poets| author=[[Charles Rogers (author)|Charles Rogers]]| publisher=W. P. Nimmo| year= 1885}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DNB|wstitle=Grieve, John|volume=23}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grieve, John}}\n[[Category:1781 births]]\n[[Category:1836 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish poets]]\n[[Category:Scottish poets]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Grieve''' (12 September 1781 \u2013 4 April 1836), was a Scottish poet.\n\n==Early pursuits==\nJohn, son of the Rev. Walter Grieve, minister of the [[Reformed Presbyterian Church of Scotland|Reformed Presbyterian Church]], was born at [[Dunfermline]] on 12 Sept. 1781. He was educated at the parish school of [[Ettrick, Scotland|Ettrick]], where his father had settled on retiring from the ministry. After leaving school he was first a merchant's clerk in [[Alloa]], and then acted for some time as a bank clerk in [[Greenock]]; he returned to Alloa, however, to become a partner in the firm of his former employer. \nIn 1804, he began business in Edinburgh, in partnership with Mr. Chalmers Izzet, hat-maker.\n\n==He becomes a writer==\nHere he was successful, and found leisure for literary pursuits. He contributed to various periodicals, his most notable efforts being the songs which he wrote for the ''Forest Minstrel'' of [[James Hogg]]. He was on intimate terms with Hogg, who speaks of his literary advice as well as his material assistance. Hogg's ''Madoc of the Moor'' is dedicated to him, and he figures as a competing minstrel in the ''Queen's Wake''.\n \nIt was on Grieve's recommendation that the ''Queen's Wake'' was published, and in regard to the more generous support given him by Grieve and his partner, Hogg says that without this he could never have fought his way in Edinburgh: {{quote|\"I was fairly starved into it, and if it had not been for Messrs. Grieve and Scott would in a very short time have been starved out of it again.\"}}\nIn 1817, Grieve retired from business through ill-health. Until his death he was a well-known figure in Edinburgh literary society. He died unmarried on 4 April 1836, and was buried in St. Mary's, Yarrow.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/?id=gBEbAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA203&lpg=PA203&dq=John+Grieve+(poet)#v=onepage&q=John%20Grieve%20(poet)&f=false| title=The Scottish minstrel: the songs of Scotland subsequent to Burns, with memoirs of the poets| author=Charles Rogers| publisher=W. P. Nimmo| year= 1885}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DNB|wstitle=Grieve, John}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grieve, John}}\n[[Category:1781 births]]\n[[Category:1836 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish poets]]\n[[Category:Scottish poets]]\n", "name_user": "Charles Matthews", "label": "safe", "comment": "lk", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Grieve_(poet)"}
{"title_page": "Silencer (firearms)", "text_new": "{{redirect|Suppressor|other uses|Suppressor (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Device which reduces sound intensity or muzzle flash on a firearm}}\n[[File:Cross section of a suppressor 01 noBG.jpg|thumb|Cutaway view of a silencer]]\n[[File:Suppressors.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|Several firearms with detachable silencers, from top to bottom: an [[Uzi]], a [[Short-barreled rifle]] or SBR, a [[Heckler & Koch USP]] Tactical, a [[Beretta 92|Beretta 92FS]], and a [[SIG Mosquito]]]]\n[[File:CZ 452 A silencer large.jpg|thumb|[[CZ 452]] bolt-action rimfire rifle with silencer]]\n[[File:Bundeswehr-Technik 02 (RaBoe).jpg|thumb|[[Accuracy International AWM|AWM-F]] [[sniper rifle]] with attached silencer]]\n\nA '''suppressor'''<!-- DO NOT REMOVE \"suppressor\". This term is the consensus pick. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Silencer_(firearms)#Requested_move_24_February_2018 -->, also known as a '''sound suppressor''' or '''sound moderator''', is a [[muzzle (firearms)|muzzle]] device that reduces the [[acoustic intensity]] of the muzzle report (sound of gunfire) and eliminates [[muzzle flash]] when a [[gun]] ([[firearm]] or [[air gun]]) is discharged, by modulating the speed and pressure of the gas ejection from the muzzle and hence suppressing the [[muzzle blast]].  Like a [[muzzle brake]], a silencer can be a detachable accessory mounted separately onto the muzzle, or an integral part of the [[gun barrel|barrel]].\n\nA typical silencer is a metal cylinder with internal [[sound baffle]]s that slow and cool the escaping [[propellant]] gas, dissipating its [[kinetic energy]] over a longer time and over a larger area, thus reducing the blast [[intensity (physics)|intensity]] and decreasing both the sound volume and [[recoil]] [[impulse (physics)|impulse]] generated during shooting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Firearms - Gun Control Act Definition - Silencer|url=https://www.atf.gov/firearms/firearms-guides-importation-verification-firearms-gun-control-act-definition-silencer|website=atf.gov|publisher=atf.gov|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref>  A [[flash suppressor]], on the other hand, specifically cools or disperses burning gases which typically already exited the muzzle of a [[carbine]]-length weapon to reduce the amount of [[muzzle flash|flash]], without reference to sound reduction.\n<!-- CLAIMS UNSUPPORTED IN BODY: Some jurisdictions allow, and even mandate, the sporting use of silencers, to reduce the risk of [[hearing loss]] and decrease [[noise pollution]], while other governments ban them for civilian use. -->\n\n==History==\nAmerican inventor [[Hiram Percy Maxim]], son of [[Maxim gun]] inventor [[Hiram Stevens Maxim]] and co-founder of the [[American Radio Relay League]], is usually credited with inventing and selling the first commercially successful silencer around 1902, receiving a patent for it on March 30, 1909.<ref name=\"USPTO-958935\"/><ref name=\"popular science 1923\">{{cite journal|last=Crossman|first=Edward|editor=Popular Science|number=2|volume=100|year=1923|publisher=Bonnier Corporation|page=48|title=Maxim's House of Silence|issn=0161-7370}}</ref><ref name=\"USAR1989\">{{cite book|last=USAR|first=William S. Brophy|title=Marlin Firearms: A History of the Guns and the Company That Made Them |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mdC3DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA653|date=1 May 1989|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=978-0-8117-4694-6|page=653|quote=During the early 1900s, Hiram Percy Maxim designed and patented gun silencers. His efforts were directed toward both military and sporting arms and resulted in his forming the Maxim Silencer Company, Hartford, Conn.}}</ref>  Maxim gave his device the [[generic trademark|popularly trademarked]] name \"Maxim Silencer\",<ref name=\"Freeman1997\">{{cite book|last=Freeman|first=Morton S.|title=A New Dictionary of Eponyms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dujiiVP2KJIC&pg=PA165 |date=18 December 1997|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-509354-4|page=165}}</ref> and they were regularly advertised in sporting goods magazines.<ref name=\"Gage\"/>  The [[muffler]] for [[internal combustion engine]]s was developed in parallel with the firearm silencer by Maxim in the early 20th century, using many of the same techniques to provide quieter-running engines, and in many English-speaking countries automobile mufflers are called silencers.<ref name=\"Goddard2000\"/>\n\nFormer president of the United States [[Theodore Roosevelt]] was known to purchase and use Maxim Silencers.<ref name=\"Boorman2001\"/>\n\nSilencers were regularly used by agents of the United States [[Office of Strategic Services]], who favored the newly designed [[High Standard HDM]] [[.22 LR]] pistol during [[World War II]].  OSS Director [[William Joseph Donovan|William Joseph \"Wild Bill\" Donovan]] demonstrated the pistol for President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] at the [[White House]].  According to OSS research chief Stanley Lovell,<ref name=\"Lovell\"/> Donovan, an old and trusted friend of the President, was waved into the [[Oval Office]], where Roosevelt was dictating a letter.  While Roosevelt finished his message, Donovan turned his back and fired ten shots into a sandbag he had brought with him, announced what he had done and handed the smoking gun to the astonished president.<ref name=\"Kessler1994\"/>  The British [[Special Operations Executive]] (SOE) [[Welrod]] pistol with an integral silencer was also used by the American OSS on clandestine operations in [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]]-occupied Europe.<ref name=\"Bull2004\"/>\n\n==Terminology==\nThe US [[National Firearms Act]] (NFA) of 1934 defined silencers and established regulations limiting their sale and ownership.<ref>Section 1(a), Public Law No. 474, Ch. 757, 48 Stat. 1236 (June 26, 1934).</ref> Both the [[United States Department of Justice|US Department of Justice]] and the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]] (ATF) use the term ''silencer''.<ref name=\"atf34\"/> Hiram Percy Maxim, the original inventor of the device, marketed them as \"Maxim Silencers\".<ref name=\"Greener2002\"/>\n\nThe earliest use of the technical term ''suppressor'' to refer to firearm noise reduction is in US Patent 4530417, July 23, 1985, \"A suppressor for reducing the muzzle blast of firearms or the like\".<ref>{{patent|US|4530417}}</ref>  In [[UK English]], ''silencer'' is the common term for either a motor vehicle muffler or for a gun silencer.<ref name=\"Goddard2000\"/>  ''Sound moderator'' has been used in UK English for silencers on high-powered rifles used for hunting or at ranges.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.shootinguk.co.uk/guns/sound-moderators-86396|title=Five sound moderators on test - Shooting UK|date=2016-12-21|website=Shooting UK |access-date=2018-04-11|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=The NRA Handbook Including The NRA Rules Of Shooting and the Programme of the Imperial Meeting Friday 17 June To Saturday 23 July 2016 |date=March 26, 2016 |publisher=[[National Rifle Association of the United Kingdom]] |url=http://www.chichesterrifleclub.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/2016-NRA-Handbook.pdf }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Oxford English Dictionary|Oxford]], [[The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language|American Heritage]], and other dictionaries apply the term ''suppressor'' to such contexts as [[electromagnetic shielding]] devices, [[Suppressor mutation|genetics]], and [[censorship]], but not firearms.<ref name=\"OEDsilencer\">{{Cite OED|silencer}}</ref><ref name=\"OEDsuppressor\">{{Cite OED|suppressor}}</ref><ref name=\"AHDsuppressor\">{{AHDict |suppressor}}</ref><ref name=\"DictionarySupressor\">{{Dictionary.com|suppressor |accessdate=2018-02-24}}</ref>  These dictionaries define both ''silencer'' and ''suppressor'' as essentially equivalent and interchangeable, neither applying exclusively or primarily to sound, and both being applicable as much to complete and total quiet or to partial reduction of sound.<ref name=\"OEDsilencer\" /><ref name=\"OEDsuppressor\" /><ref name=\"AHDsuppressor\" /><ref name=\"DictionarySupressor\" />\n\nIn 2011, the US [[National Rifle Association]] began a campaign to increase the civilian use of silencers for hunting and sport shooting, setting the goals of easing the restrictions in the [[National Firearms Act of 1934|Federal NFA of 1934]], and in various state laws, regulating the sale and ownership of firearm silencers.  In the same year, the American Silencer Association (ASA) was founded by US manufacturers of silencers, with the same goals of moving silencers into the mainstream.<ref name=\"LaSorte2011\" /><ref name=\"Devaney2017\">{{Citation |url=http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/335348-gun-lobby-seeks-to-calm-fears-about-silencers |title=Gun lobby seeks to calm fears about silencers |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |first=Tim |last=Devaney |date=May 5, 2017 }}</ref>  Along with state and federal legislative lobbying efforts, the NRA and ASA began public information campaigns designed to change the perception of silencers from their association with espionage, assassination, crime or military special operation use, to instead show that silencers can have health and safety benefits, primarily protecting the hearing of shooters and people in the vicinity, and to debunk the perceived myth in popular television, film and video game media that silencers are so effective that gunshot sounds can go totally unnoticed, such as by people in the next room of a building.<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/><ref name=\"LaSorte2011\">{{Citation |url=https://www.americanrifleman.org/articles/2011/12/22/suppressors-for-hearing-and-the-shooting-sports/ |title= Suppressors: For Hearing and the Shooting Sports |first=Darren |last=LaSorte |date=December 22, 2011 |magazine=[[American Rifleman]] |publisher=[[National Rifle Association]] }}</ref><ref name=\"Rosenwald2017\">{{Citation |title= Gun silencers are hard to buy. Donald Trump Jr. and silencer makers want to change that |first=Michael S. |last=Rosenwald |date=January 9, 2017 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/gun-silencers-are-hard-to-buy-donald-trump-jr-and-silencer-makers-want-to-change-that/2017/01/07/0764ab4c-d2d2-11e6-9cb0-54ab630851e8_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the ASA changed its name to American Suppressor Association \"in a continuing effort to dispel myths about suppressors\".<ref>{{Citation |url= http://www.guns.com/2014/05/09/asa-changes-its-name-to-american-suppressor-association/ |title= ASA changes its name to American Suppressor Association |date= May 9, 2014 |first=Max |last=Slowik }}</ref>  Gun control advocates have said that changing the name from \"silencer\" to \"suppressor\" is semantic propaganda similar to the efforts to avoid terms like \"[[assault rifle]]\" or \"[[assault weapon]]\" in favor of friendlier-sounding language like \"[[modern sporting rifle]]\", while gun rights advocates make essentially the opposite argument, and also that the widespread term ''silencer'' reflects technical ignorance and is poorly defined.<ref name=\"Devaney2017\" /><ref name=\"Rosenwald2017\" />\n\nGun rights advocates and gun media generally say that the word \"silencer\" is defined as meaning ''total'' silence, while \"suppressor\" is defined as only meaning reduced sound intensity.<ref name=\"Devaney2017\" /><ref name=\"Rosenwald2017\" />\n\n==Firearm noise anatomy==\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2019}}\nWhen a firearm is discharged, there are three ways sound is produced. Whilst part of it can be managed; however, some of it is beyond the ability of the operator or manufacturers to eliminate.\n\nIn order of importance, the three ways a firearm generates sound are:\n*Muzzle blast \u2014 [[shockwave]] generated by high-pressure gases escaping and expanding from the muzzle after the [[projectile]] exits the barrel and breaks the functional [[seal (mechanical)|seal]] restraining the gas inside the [[gun barrel#Bore|bore]]\n*[[Sonic boom]] \u2014 sharp [[bullwhip]]-cracking sound associated with high-frequency shockwaves caused by an object (in this case, the [[bullet]]) flying [[supersonic]]ally through the air\n*Mechanical noise generated by the internal moving parts of the [[firearm action]]\n\nA silencer can only affect the noise generated by the muzzle blast.  While using [[subsonic ammunition]]s can negate the sonic boom, mechanical noise can be mitigated but is nearly impossible to eliminate.  For these reasons, it is difficult to completely silence any firearm, or achieve an acceptable{{clarify|date=June 2018}} level of noise suppression in [[revolver]]s that function under standard operating principles due to the looser gas seal between the barrel and the [[cylinder (firearms)|cylinder]].  Some revolvers have technical features that enable suppression and include the Russian [[Nagant M1895]] and [[OTs-38]] revolvers, and the [[S&W QSPR]].\n\n[[Muzzle blast]] generated by firearm discharge is directly proportional to the amount of [[propellant]] to be combusted within the [[cartridge (firearms)|cartridge]].  Therefore, the greater the case capacity (e.g. a [[magnum cartridge]]), the louder the muzzle blast and consequently a more efficient or larger silencer system is required.  A gunshot (the combination of the sonic boom, the vacuum release, and hot gases) will almost always be louder than the sound of the action cycling of an [[semi-automatic firearm|autoloading firearm]].  Alan C. Paulson, a renowned firearms specialist, claimed to have encountered an integrally suppressed .22 LR gun that had such a quiet report {{clarify|date=August 2019}} ,<ref name=\"Paulson\"/> although this is somewhat uncommon.  Properly evaluating the sound generated by a firearm can only be done using a [[Decibel Meters|decibel meter]] in conjunction with a [[frequency spectrum]] analyzer during live tests.\n\n==Design and construction==\n[[File:ReflexSuppressor-WP-Drwg.png|thumb|Cross-section drawing of a centerfire rifle silencer, showing expansion chamber \"reflexed\" (going back around) the rifle barrel, and four sound baffles. The diffractor and baffles are carefully shaped to deflect gas.|alt=]]\n[[File:Vaime-Suppressor-22-WP-Drwg.png|thumb|Cross-section drawing of a rimfire rifle silencer, showing short expansion chamber and thirteen plastic baffles. These baffles use alternating angled flat surfaces to repeatedly deflect gas expanding through the silencer. In the actual silencer, the baffles are oriented at 90 degrees to each other about the axis of bullet travel. (The illustration cannot demonstrate this well.)]]\n[[File:Navy-HushPuppy-WP-Drwg.png|thumb|Cross-section drawing of a pistol silencer, showing expansion chamber wrapped around inner suppressor assembly, and four wipes. The bullet pushes a bullet-diameter hole through the wipes, trapping propellant gas behind it entirely until the bullet has passed through the wipe completely]]\n[[File:Patent DE1553874 07-Oct-1971 Handfeuerwaffe mit Schalldaempfer Heckler und Koch.png|thumb|Cross section drawing of an \"integral\" sound suppressor in part designed and built into the suppressed firearm.]]\n\nThe silencer is typically a hollow metal tube manufactured from [[steel]], [[aluminum]], or [[titanium]] and contains expansion chambers. This device, typically cylindrical in shape, attaches to the [[muzzle (firearm)|muzzle]] of a [[pistol]], [[submachine gun]], or [[rifle]]. Some \"can\"-type silencers (so-called as they often resemble a [[beverage can]]) may be detached by the user and attached to a different firearm. Another type is the \"integral\" suppressor, which typically consists of an expansion chamber or chambers surrounding the barrel. The barrel has openings or \"ports\" which bleed off gases into the chambers. This type of silencer is part of the firearm (thus the term \"integral\"), and maintenance of the suppressor requires that the firearm be at least partially disassembled.<ref name=\"Heard2011\"/>\n\n[[File:Huntertown Kestrel 5.56 disassembled.JPG|thumb|left|Firearm suppressor disassembled to show blast chamber, baffles, and sections of the outer tube]]\n\nBoth types of silencers reduce noise by allowing the rapidly expanding gases from the firing of the cartridge to be decelerated and cooled through a series of hollow chambers. The trapped gas exits the suppressor over a longer period of time and at a greatly reduced speed, producing less noise signature. The chambers are divided by either ''baffles'' or ''wipes''. There are typically at least four and up to perhaps fifteen chambers in a suppressor, depending on the intended use and design details. Often, a single, larger expansion chamber is located at the muzzle end of a can-type silencer, which allows the propellant gas to expand considerably and slow down before it encounters the baffles or wipes. This larger chamber may be \"reflexed\" toward the rear of the barrel to minimize the overall length of the combined firearm and silencer, especially with longer weapons such as rifles.\n\nSilencers vary greatly in size and efficiency. One disposable type developed in the 1980s by the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] for [[9\u00d719mm]] pistols was {{convert|150|mm|in|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|45|mm|in|abbr=on}} in outside diameter, and was designed for six shots with standard ammunition or up to thirty shots with [[speed of sound|subsonic]] (slower than the speed of sound) [[ammunition]]. In contrast, one suppressor designed for rifles firing the powerful [[.50 BMG|.50 caliber (BMG)]] cartridge is {{convert|509|mm|in|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|76|mm|in|abbr=on}} in diameter.<ref name=\"Barrett\"/>\n\nTwo ancillary advantages to the silencer are recoil reduction and flash suppression. Muzzle flash is reduced by both being contained in the suppressor and through the arresting of unburned powder that would normally burn in the air, adding to the flash. Recoil reduction results from the slowing of propellant gasses, which can contribute 30\u201350% of recoil velocity. However, some suppressors can increase the backpressure produced by the propellant gasses. This can cause them to function somewhat like a [[muzzle booster]] and thus increase the felt recoil. The weight of the silencer and the location of that additional weight at the muzzle reduce recoil through basic mass as well as muzzle flip due to the location of this mass.\n\n===Components===\n\n===Baffles and spacers===\nBaffles are usually circular metal dividers which separate the expansion chambers. Each baffle has a hole in its center to permit the passage of the bullet through the silencer and toward the target. The hole is typically at least 1&nbsp;mm larger than the bullet caliber to minimize the risk of the bullet hitting the baffle in what is known as a \"baffle strike\". Baffles are typically made of stainless steel, aluminum, titanium, or alloys such as [[Inconel]], and are either [[machining|machined]] out of solid metal or [[stamping (metalworking)|stamped]] out of sheet metal. A few silencers for low-powered cartridges such as the [[.22 Long Rifle]] have successfully used plastic baffles (certain models by Vaime and others).<ref name=\"Paulson\"/>{{rp|186\u2013187}}\n\nThere are several unique baffle designs. M, K, Z, monolithic core<ref name=\"Sparrow\"/> and \u03a9 (Omega) are the most prevalent. M-type is the crudest and comprises an inverted [[cone (geometry)|cone]]. K forms slanted obstructions diverging from the sidewalls, creating [[turbulence]] across the [[gauge (bore diameter)|bore]]line. Z is expensive to machine and includes \"pockets\" of dead airspace along the sidewalls which trap expanded gases and hold them thereby lengthening the time that the gases cool before exiting. Omega-type baffles form a series of spaced cones drawing gas away from the boreline and incorporate a scalloped mouth creating cross-bore turbulence, which is in turn directed to a \"mouse-hole\" opening between the baffle stack and sidewall.\n\nPropellant gas heats and erodes the baffles, causing wear, which is worsened by high rates of fire. Aluminum baffles are seldom used with fully [[automatic firearm|automatic weapon]]s, because service life is unacceptably short. Some modern suppressors using steel or high-temperature alloy baffles can endure extended periods of fully automatic fire without damage. The highest-quality rifle suppressors available today have a claimed service life of greater than 30,000 rounds.<ref name=\"Paulson\"/>{{rp|363\u2013364}} Baffles have not been given any specific angles, a specific size, or weight to meet any standards; they are created on a trial and error basis.<ref name=\"Walker\"/>\n\nSpacers separate baffles and keep them aligned at a specified distance from each other inside the silencer. Many baffles and spacers are manufactured as a single assembly and several suppressor designs have all the baffles attached together with spacers as a one-piece helical baffle stack. Modern baffles are usually carefully shaped to divert the propellant gases effectively into the chambers. This shaping can be a slanted flat surface, canted at an angle to the bore, or a conical or otherwise curved surface. One popular technique is to have alternating angled surfaces through the stack of baffles.<ref name=\"Walker\"/>\n\n===Wipes and packing material===\nWipes are inner dividers intended to touch the bullet as it passes through the silencer, and are typically made of [[rubber]], [[plastic]], or [[foam]]. Each wipe may either have a hole drilled in it before use, a pattern stamped into its surface at the point where the bullet will strike it, or it may simply be punched through by the bullet. Wipes typically last for a small number of firings (perhaps no more than five) before their performance is significantly degraded. While many suppressors used wipes in the [[Vietnam War]] era, most modern suppressors do not use them as anything that touches the projectile has significant accuracy implications. All \"wipes\" deteriorate quickly and require disassembly and spare parts replacement.<ref name=\"Dockery2007\"/>\n\n\"Wet\" silencers or \"wet cans\" use a small quantity of water, [[oil]], [[petroleum|grease]], or [[gel]] in the expansion chambers to cool the propellant gases and reduce their volume (see [[ideal gas law]]). The coolant lasts only a few shots before it must be replenished, but can greatly increase the effectiveness of the suppressor. Water is most effective, due to its high [[heat of vaporization]], but it can run or evaporate out of the silencer. Grease, while messier and less effective than water, can be left in the suppressor indefinitely without losing effectiveness. Oil is the least effective and least preferable, as it runs while being as messy as grease, and leaves behind a fine mist of [[aerosol]]ized oil after each shot. Water-based gels, such as wire-pulling lubricant gel, are a good compromise; they offer the efficacy of water with less mess, as they do not run or drip. However, they take longer to apply, as they must be cleared from the bore of the suppressor to ensure a clear path for the bullet (grease requires this step as well). Generally, only pistol silencers are shot wet, as rifle silencers handle such high pressure and heat that the liquid is gone within 1\u20133 shots. Many manufacturers will not warranty their rifle suppressors for \"wet\" fire, as some feel this may even result in a dangerous over-pressurization of the silencer.<ref name=\"Walker\"/>\n\nPacking materials such as metal [[mesh]], [[steel wool]], or [[washer (hardware)|metal washers]] may be used to fill the chambers and further dissipate and cool the gases. These are somewhat more effective than empty chambers, but less effective than wet designs.<ref name=\"Paulson\"/>{{rp|130}} Metal mesh, if properly used, may last for hundreds or thousands of shots of spaced semi-automatic fire; however, steel wool usually degrades within ten shots, with stainless steel wool lasting longer than regular steel wool. Like wipes, packing materials are rarely found in modern silencers.<ref name=\"Walker\"/>\n\nWipes, packing materials and purpose-designed wet cans have been generally abandoned in 21st-century suppressor design because they decrease overall accuracy and require excessive cleaning and maintenance.<ref name=\"Dockery2007\"/> The instructions from several manufacturers state that their suppressors need not be cleaned at all.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018|reason=Which manufacturers? Where is this stated?}} Furthermore, legal changes in the United States during the 1980s and 1990s made it much more difficult for end-users to legally replace internal silencer parts, and the newer designs reflect this reality.<ref name=\"Explosives\"/>\n\n===Attachment===\n[[File:AOW and SBR suppressed.jpg|thumb|Silenced 12 gauge shotgun and 7.62\u00d739&nbsp;mm rifle]]\nApart from integral silencers which are integrated as a part of the firearm's barrel, most suppressors have a \"female\" threaded end, which attaches to \"male\" threads cut into the exterior of the barrel. These types of silencers are mostly used on handguns and rifles chambered in .22LR. More powerful rifles may use this type of attachment, but harsh recoil may cause the suppressor to over-tighten to the barrel and the suppressor can become difficult to remove.<ref name=\"Walker\"/> [[SilencerCo]]'s Salvo silencer for shotguns attaches via internal barrel threading normally used to mount removable [[Choke (firearms)|chokes]].<ref>Waldron, Len. \"SilencerCo Salvo 12 Gauge Suppressor Review.\" ''Guns &''\n Ammo''. March 7, 2016. [http://www.gunsandammo.com/gear-accessories/suppressors/silencerco-salvo-12-suppressor-review/]''</ref>\n\nMilitary rifles such as the [[M16 rifle|M16]] or [[M14 rifle|M14]] often use \"quick-detach\" suppressors which use coarser than normal threads and are installed over an existing muzzle device such as a flash suppressor and may include a secondary locking mechanism to allow the shooter to quickly and safely add or remove a sound suppressor based on individual needs.<ref name=\"Walker\"/>\n\n===Advanced types===\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2019|reason=mostly essay}}\n[[File:SilencerCo Osprey .45.JPG|thumb|[[SilencerCo]] Osprey .45 silencer on a Springfield pistol]]\n\nIn addition to containing and slowly releasing the gas pressure associated with muzzle blast or reducing pressure through the use of coolant mediums, advanced silencer designs attempt to modify the properties of the sound waves generated by the muzzle blast. In these designs, effects known as [[frequency shifting]] and [[interference (wave propagation)|phase cancellation]] (or destructive interference) are used in an attempt to make the suppressor quieter. These effects are achieved by separating the flow of gases and causing them to collide with each other or by venting them through precision-made holes. The intended effect of frequency shifting is to shift audible sound waves frequencies into [[ultrasound]] (above 20 [[Hertz|kHz]]), beyond the range of human hearing. The Russian [[AN-94]] assault rifle has a muzzle attachment that claims apparent noise reduction by venting some gases through a \"dog-whistle\" type channel. Phase cancellation occurs when similar sound waves encounter each other 180\u00b0 out of phase, cancelling the amplitude of the wave and eliminating the pressure variations perceived as sound.\n\nAn alternate method under development is called the anti-phase destructive interference generator.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} The process involves duplication of the sound waves generated by the muzzle blast, which are then used to create an anti-phase auditory signal. Currently, this is a muzzle attached device, and is only being tested to cancel out the gunshot sound of the firearm. The devices tested incorporate multiple microphones, speakers and an auditory processor. The first shot fired is recorded, and then played back precisely out of sync(180 degrees out of phase) with each subsequent shot. This has proven successful with small caliber(.17-.22) rifles, but the amplitude has not been matched efficiently with larger cartridges. With the use of subsonic ammunition, the resultant sound waves effectively cancel each other out, and with the exception of the sound of the action cycling, completely eliminate any gunshot sound. In the current development stage, this has worked only in close proximity to the shooter, and the pressure wave(p-wave) can still be felt. Each time a different type of ammunition or firearm is used, the device needs recalibration.\n\nTaking advantage of either property requires that the silencer be designed within the specification of the muzzle blast in mind. For example, the velocity of the sound waves is a major factor. This figure can change significantly between different cartridges and barrel lengths.\n\nHowever, these concepts are controversial because a muzzle blast creates [[white noise|broadband noise]] rather than [[pure tone]]s, and phase cancellation in particular is therefore extremely difficult (if not impossible) to achieve. Some suppressor manufacturers claim to use phase cancellation in their designs.<ref name=\"WebbDoherty2010\"/>\n\nFrom a physics standpoint, supersonic cartridge loads are impractical to suppress past the levels that are merely hearing-safe for the shooter due to the sonic boom emitted by the bullet, and cartridges such as [[.22 LR]] and [[.45 ACP]] have long been recognized as the easiest to suppress even if using technology dating back to the 1940s.<ref name=\"assassin\"/><ref name=\"Supersonic\"/>\n\n===Captive-piston silencer===\nAnother silencer technology uses a captive piston cartridge; examples are the Smith & Wesson [[Quiet Special Purpose Revolver]] (QSPR) and the Soviet and Russian [[PSS silent pistol]],<ref name=sadj>{{cite web |url=http://www.sadefensejournal.com/wp/beyond-quiet-the-russian-pss-captive-piston-pistol/ |title=Beyond Quiet: The Russian PSS Captive Piston Pistol (2 Web pages)|website=Small Arms Defense Journa|date=16 August 2011|author= |accessdate= 14 June 2019}}</ref> [[OTs-38 Stechkin silent revolver]] and the MTs-116M suppressed sniper rifle, a 12.7mm silenced development of the 7.62mm MTs-116M.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/weapons/a22862616/russia-silent-sniper-rifle/ |title=The Science of Russia's New Silent Sniper Rifle |website=Popular Mechanics|date=25 August 2018 |author=David Hambling |accessdate= 14 June 2019}}</ref> The large calibre allows the bullet to be fired at subsonic speed, eliminating a major source of noise, while retaining accuracy, range, and effectiveness. All these weapons use special, very expensive, captive-piston ammunition; the QSPR used ammunition which resembled metal-cased .410-bore shotgun shells. The cartridge case internally works as a piston to trap the gases; the piston pushes the bullet, but the gases are retained in the cartridge case instead of being expelled noisily; in tests of the PSS the sound pressure level was 124.6&nbsp;[[Decibel|dB]], similar to a suppressed .22 rimfire pistol.<ref name=sadj/> The ammunition itself, rather than the weapon, is silent; in the US each individual round is considered to be a silencer, subject to regulations on silencers.<ref name=sadj/>\n\n===Improvised silencers===\nImprovised silencers have been made from a variety of materials. In 2015, [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department|Los Angeles County Sheriff deputies]] recovered a [[ZB vz. 26]] [[light machine gun]] with an automobile [[oil filter]] attached.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weingarten|first1=Dean|title=Homeless Man's Black Market Submachine Guns and Improvised Silencer|url=http://www.thetruthaboutguns.com/2015/11/dean-weingarten/homeless-mans-black-market-submachine-guns-improvised-silencer/|accessdate=12 October 2016|work=thetruthaboutguns.com|date=November 27, 2015}}</ref> [[Polyvinyl chloride#Pipes|PVC pipes]], plastic water bottles, and foam-filled pillows are also used.<ref name=\"Hollenbach\"/><ref name=\"Emerson\">{{cite book|last1=Emerson|first1=Clint|title=100 Deadly Skills: The SEAL Operative's Guide to Eluding Pursuers, Evading Capture, and Surviving Any Dangerous Situation|date=Oct 13, 2015|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1476796055|page=70|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xi-rCgAAQBAJ|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|chapter=Injuries Due to Firearms and Other Missile-Launching Devices|title=Forensic Neuropathology: A Practical Review of the Fundamentals|first1=Hideo H. |last1=Itabashi|page=223|publisher=Academic Press|date=2011|isbn=978-0080549842}}</ref> In the United States, improvised silencers are governed by the same laws as manufactured ones.<ref name=\"Hollenbach\">{{cite book|last1=Hollenbach|first1=George M.|title=Workbench Silencers: The Art Of Improvised Designs|date=1996|publisher=Paladin Press|isbn=1610046773|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fX_KAwAAQBAJ|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Nielsen device area of YHM Cobra .45 suppressor.jpg|thumb|Rear of a silencer with the [[Muzzle booster|Nielsen device]] protruding (completely assembled)]]\n[[File:Nielsen device of YHM Cobra .45 suppressor partially removed.jpg|thumb|Retaining ring unscrewed and Nielsen device partially removed]]\n[[File:Nielsen device of YHM Cobra .45 suppressor completely disassembled.jpg|thumb|Nielsen device completely removed and disassembled]]\n[[File:Rotational indexing system of YHM Cobra .45 suppressor Nielsen device.jpg|thumb|Rear of silencer showing the rotational indexing system incorporated into some Nielsen devices]]\n\nFunctionally, a suppressor is meant to diminish the report of a discharged round, or make its sound unrecognizable. Other sounds emanating from the weapon remain unchanged. Even subsonic bullets make distinct sounds by their passage through the air and striking targets, and supersonic bullets produce a small sonic boom, resulting in a \"ballistic crack\". Semi-automatic and fully automatic firearms also make distinct noises as their actions cycle, ejecting the fired cartridge case and loading a new round.\n\nAside from reductions in volume, suppressors tend to alter the sound to something that is not identifiable as a gunshot.<ref name=\"Dougherty2012\"/> This reduces or eliminates attention drawn to the shooter. A Finnish expression dating from the [[Winter War]] says that \"A silencer does not make a soldier silent, but it does make him invisible.\"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Guns & Weapons for Law Enforcement|year= 2004|issue=8|title=Finland's Silenced .338 Long-Range Sniper:Sako TRG42 Rifle and BR-Tuote T8M Reflex Suppressor|first= Al |last=Paulson|publisher=Harris Publications|location=New York|volume=1|url=http://www.canadiantactical.ca/PaulsonArticle2.html}}</ref> Silencers are particularly useful in enclosed spaces where the sound, flash and pressure effects of a weapon being fired are amplified. Such effects may disorient the shooter, affecting [[situational awareness]], concentration and accuracy, and can permanently damage hearing very quickly.<ref name=\"Dater2007\"/>\n\nAs the suppressed sound of firing is overshadowed by ballistic crack, observers can be deceived as to the location of the shooter, often from 90 to 180 degrees from his actual location. However, [[counter-sniper tactics]] can include [[gunfire locator]]s, such as the U.S. [[Boomerang (mobile shooter detection system)|Boomerang]] system, where sensitive microphones are coupled to computers running algorithms, and use the ballistic crack to detect and localize the origin of the shot.\n\nThere are many advantages in using a silencer that are not related to the sound.\n\nHunters using [[Centerfire ammunition|centerfire rifles]] find silencers bring various important benefits that outweigh the extra weight and resulting change in the firearm's center of gravity. The most important advantage of a suppressor is the hearing protection for the shooter as well as their companions. Many hunters have suffered permanent hearing damage due to someone else firing a high-caliber gun too closely without warning.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=National Hearing Conservation Association|year= 2017|title=NHCA Position Statement, Recreational Firearm Noise |first=Michael |last=Stewart |first2=Deanna K. |last2=Meinke |first3=Gregory A. |last3=Flamme |first4=William J. |last4=Murphy |first5=Donald S. |last5=Finan |first6=James E. |last6=Lankford |first7=Stephen M. |last7= Tasko |url=https://www.hearingconservation.org/assets/docs/NHCA_position_paper_on_firea.pdf}}</ref> By reducing noise, recoil and muzzle-blast, it also enables the firer to follow through calmly on their first shot and fire a further carefully aimed shot without delay if necessary. [[Wildlife]] of all kinds are often confused as to the direction of the source of a well-suppressed shot. In the field, however, the comparatively large size of a centerfire rifle suppressor can cause unwanted noise if it bumps or rubs against vegetation or rocks, so many users cover them with [[neoprene]] sleeves.<ref name=\"Mann2014\"/>\n\nSilencers reduce firing [[recoil]] significantly, primarily by diverting and trapping the propellant gas. The gas generally has much less mass than the projectile, but it exits the muzzle at multiples of the projectile velocity, so reducing the speed and quantity of the gas expelled can significantly reduce the total [[momentum]] of the matter (gas and projectile) leaving the barrel, the negation of which, because momentum is [[Conservation of momentum|conserved]], is transferred to the gun as recoil. Paulson ''et al.'', discussing low-velocity pistol calibers, suggest the recoil reduction is around 15%.<ref name=\"Paulson\"/>{{rp|38\u201340}} With high-velocity calibers, recoil reduction runs in the range of 20\u201330%.<ref name=\"MarkWhite\"/> The added mass of the suppressor\u2014normally 300 to 500&nbsp;grams\u2014also helps to manage the recoil.\n\nA suppressor also cools the hot gases coming out of the barrel enough that most of the [[lead]]-laced [[vapor]] that leaves the barrel [[condensation|condenses]] inside the silencer, reducing the amount of lead that might be inhaled by the shooter and others around them. However, in auto-loading actions this might be offset by increased [[back pressure]], which results in propellant gas blowing back into a shooter's face through the chamber during case ejection.<ref name=\"Emptormaven\"/>\n\n===Subsonic ammunition===\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2019}}\nIn weapons firing [[supersonic]] ammunition, the bullet itself produces a loud and very sharp sound as it leaves the muzzle in excess of the speed of sound and gradually reducing speed as it travels downrange. This is a small sonic boom, and is referred to in the firearm field as \"ballistic crack\" or \"sonic signature\". Subsonic ammunition eliminates this sound, but at the cost of lower velocity, resulting in decreased range and much decreased [[muzzle energy]] unless the bullet weight is increased, thus lessening effectiveness on the target. For example, if the muzzle velocity is reduced from {{cvt|820|m/s|order=flip}} (common for the [[.308 Winchester]], for example) to a subsonic {{cvt|290|m/s|order=flip}}, the muzzle energy is reduced by a factor of 8. Military marksmen and police units may use subsonic ammunition in suppressed rifles, when minimal noise is more important than range and energy.<ref name=\"sniper\"/>\n\nHowever, the numeric effectiveness of subsonic rounds is, again, misrepresented by media.<ref name=\"Dockery2007\"/> Independent testing of commercially available firearm suppressors with commercially available subsonic rounds has found that .308 subsonic rounds decreased the volume at the muzzle by 10 to 12&nbsp;dB when compared to the same caliber of suppressed supersonic ammunition.<ref name=\"results\" /> When combined with silencers, the subsonic .308 rounds metered between 121 and 137&nbsp;dB.\n\nThe ballistic crack depends on the speed of sound, which in turn depends mainly on air temperature. At sea level, an ambient temperature of {{convert|70|F}}, and under normal atmospheric conditions, the speed of sound is approximately {{convert|1140|ft/s}}. Bullets that travel near the speed of sound are considered [[transonic]], which means that the airflow over the surface of the bullet, which at points travels faster than the bullet itself, can break the speed of sound. [[Bullet#Pointed bullets|Pointed bullets]], which gradually displace air, can get closer to the speed of sound than round- or snub-nosed bullets before becoming transonic.\n\nSpecial cartridges have been developed for use with a silencer. These cartridges use very heavy bullets to make up for the energy lost by keeping the bullet subsonic. A good example of this is the [[.300 Whisper]] cartridge, which is formed from a necked-up [[.221 Remington Fireball]] cartridge case. The subsonic .300 Whisper fires up to a {{convert|250|gr}}, .30 caliber bullet at about {{convert|980|ft/s}}, generating about {{convert|533|ftlbf}} of energy at the muzzle. While this is similar to the energy available from the .45 ACP pistol cartridge, the reduced diameter and streamlined shape of the heavy .30 caliber bullet provides far better [[external ballistics|external ballistic]] performance, improving range substantially.\n\n[[9\u00d719mm Parabellum|9\u00d719&nbsp;mm Parabellum]], a very popular caliber for suppressed shooting, can use almost any factory-loaded {{convert|147|gr}} weight round to achieve subsonic performance. These 147&nbsp;gr weight bullets typically have a velocity of {{convert|900|-|980|ft/s}}, which is less than the {{convert|1140|ft/s}} speed of sound.<ref name=\"Ayoob2011\"/>\n[[File:AS Val & VSS Vintorez - RaceofHeroes-part2-34 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Integral silencer on [[VSS Vintorez]] sniper rifle and [[AS Val]] assault rifle]]\nThe [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]/Russian [[Armor-piercing shot and shell#Small arms|armor-piercing]] [[9\u00d739mm]] ammunition used in rifles such as the [[AS Val]] has a high subsonic [[ballistic coefficient]], high retained downrange energy, high [[sectional density]], and moderate recoil.<ref name=\"Tilstra2014\"/>\n\nWithout using subsonic ammunition, the [[muzzle velocity]] of a supersonic bullet can be lowered by other means, before it leaves the barrel. Some silencer designs, referred to as \"integrals\", do this by allowing gas to bleed off along the length of the barrel before the projectile exits. The [[MP5SD]] is an example of this, with holes right after the chamber of the barrel used to reduce a regular 115 or 124&nbsp;gr ammunition to subsonic velocities.<ref name=\"Heard2011\"/>\n\n==Effectiveness==\n[[File:Silencerco Osprey 9, SWR Octane 45, and Silencerco Saker 5.56.JPG|thumb|Firearm silencers including the SilencerCo Osprey 9, SWR Octane 45, and SilencerCo Saker 5.56]]\n\nLive tests by independent reviewers of numerous commercially available suppressors find that even low-power, unsuppressed .22&nbsp;LR handguns produce gunshots over 160&nbsp;[[decibels]].<ref name=\"results\"/> A recent study of various suppressors reported peak sound pressure level reductions between 17 dB and 24 dB.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Murphy|first=William J.|last2=Flamme|first2=Gregory A.|last3=Campbell|first3=Adam R.|last4=Zechmann|first4=Edward L.|last5=Tasko|first5=Stephen M.|last6=Lankford|first6=James E.|last7=Meinke|first7=Deanna K.|last8=Finan|first8=Donald S.|last9=Stewart|first9=Michael|date=2018-01-26|title=The reduction of gunshot noise and auditory risk through the use of firearm suppressors and low-velocity ammunition|journal=International Journal of Audiology|volume=57|issue=sup1|pages=S28\u2013S41|doi=10.1080/14992027.2017.1407459|issn=1499-2027|pmid=29299940}}</ref> Another study evaluated two calibers of rifle and nine suppressors, .223 caliber [[AR-15 style rifle|AR-15]] (five suppressors) and .300 caliber AAC Blackout (four suppressors), and reported noise reduction of the peak sound level pressure between 7 dB and 32 dB.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lobarinas|first=Edward|last2=Scott|first2=Ryan|last3=Spankovich|first3=Christopher|last4=Prell|first4=Colleen G. Le|date=2016-02-12|title=Differential effects of suppressors on hazardous sound pressure levels generated by AR-15 rifles: Considerations for recreational shooters, law enforcement, and the military|journal=International Journal of Audiology|volume=55|issue=sup1|pages=S59\u2013S71|doi=10.3109/14992027.2015.1122241|issn=1499-2027|pmid=26821935}}</ref> The [[De Lisle carbine]], a British World War II suppressed rifle used in small numbers by Special Forces, was recorded at 85.5&nbsp;dB in official firing tests.<ref name=\"Rome\"/>\n\nComparatively, ear protection commonly used while shooting provides 18 to 32&nbsp;dB of sound reduction at the ear.<ref name=\"Hearing\"/> Further, chainsaws, rock concerts, rocket engines, pneumatic drills, small firecrackers, and ambulance sirens are rated at 100 to 140&nbsp;dB.<ref name=\"Murray\"/>\n\nWhile some consider the noise reduction of a suppressor significant enough to permit safe shooting without hearing protection (\"hearing safe\"), [[noise-induced hearing loss]] may occur at 85 time-weighted-average decibels or above if exposed for a prolonged period,<ref name=\"NIHL\"/> and suppressed gunshots regularly meter above 130&nbsp;dB. However, the U.S. [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration]] uses 140&nbsp;dB as the \"safety cutoff\" for [[impulse noise (audio)|impulsive noise]], which has led most U.S. manufacturers to advertise sub-140&nbsp;dB silencers as \"hearing safe\". Current OSHA standards would allow no more than sub-single-second exposure to impact noise over 130&nbsp;dB per 24 hours. That would equate to a single .308 round fired through a very efficient suppressor. This result effectively requires all users of silencers to wear additional ear protection.\n\nDecibel testing measures only the peak sound \"pressure\" noise, not duration or frequency. Limitations of dB testing become apparent in a comparison of sound between a [[.308 Winchester|.308 caliber]] rifle and a [[.300 Winchester Magnum]] rifle. The dB meter will show that both rifles produce the same decibel level of noise. Upon firing these rifles, however, it is clear that the .300 Winchester Magnum sounds much louder. What a dB meter does not show is that, although both rifles produce the same peak [[sound pressure level]] (SPL), the .300 Winchester Magnum holds its peak duration longer\u2014meaning that the .300 Winchester Magnum sound remains at full value longer, while the .308 peaks and falls off more quickly. Decibel meters fail in this and other regards when being used as the principal means to determine silencer capability. In a physical sense, dB meters essentially take a short-time average ([[Root mean square|RMS]] intensity of a sonic signal or impulse) over a specified period of time (sampling rate), and do not take into account the rate of increase of the sound wave packet (first derivative of packet envelope), which would in practice provide a better sense of the human [[Sound perception|perception of sound]].<ref name=\"AWC\"/>\n\nAlan C. Paulson, of [[Paladin Press]], writes that suppressors are considered a great help, along with hearing protection, to preserve the hearing of the user and any onlookers.<ref name=\"Paulson2\"/>\n\n==Regulation==\nLegal regulation of silencers varies widely around the world. In some nations, such as Finland, France, and New Zealand some or all types of suppressor are essentially unregulated and are sold through retail stores or by mail-order.<ref name=\"Dockery2007\"/> In other countries their possession or use is more restricted.\n\n===Europe===\n*In Norway, silencers are not regulated and can be purchased by anyone for any firearm. No licence or permit is necessary.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://lovdata.no/dokument/SF/forskrift/2009-06-25-904 |title = Forskrift om skytev\u00e5pen, v\u00e5pendeler og ammunisjon mv. (V\u00e5penforskriften) - Lovdata}}</ref>\n*In Denmark, the [[Danish Weapons And Explosives Law]] makes the unlicensed possession of a silencer illegal. {{asof|2014|05|07}} it is legal to own and use silencers for hunting.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.retsinformation.dk/Forms/R0710.aspx?id=162966 | title=Bekendtg\u00f8relse om v\u00e5ben og ammunition der m\u00e5 anvendes til jagt m.v. |work= retsinformation.dk |publisher=[[Milj\u00f8ministeriet]]|accessdate=2015-03-15|date= 2014-05-07|trans-title= Hunting weapons and ammunition act|language=Danish}}</ref>\n*In Finland, a firearm silencer is classified as a firearm part by law. Purchasing a suppressor requires a firearm ownership permit, which must be shown to the vendor at the moment of purchase.<ref name=\"Baum2013\"/>\n*Silencers for [[Rimfire (firearms)|rimfire]] pistols are sold without government oversight in France.<ref name=\"Dockery2007\"/>\n*Poland: In 2020 new amendment to Arms and Ammunition Act allowed police to issue permits for firearms with a sound suppressors for hunting permits. Hunters are allowed to use them only for sanitary shooting of animals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prezydent.pl/aktualnosci/wydarzenia/art,1658,dwie-ustawy-z-podpisem-prezydenta.html|title=Dwie ustawy z podpisem Prezydenta|date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n*In the Russian Federation, using firearm silencers (legally defined as \"devices for noiseless shooting\") by civilians is prohibited, and dealers are prohibited from selling them, but there is no penalty for purchasing or possession of such devices.<ref name=\"Carter2002\"/> \n*In Sweden, silencers for specified calibers are legal for hunting purposes; a license is required.<ref name=\"Paulson\"/>{{rp|9}}\n*In the UK, the owner's [[firearm certificate]] (FAC) will need to show permission for the purchase of a \"sound moderator\" and also the firearm for which it is intended. All firearms certificates have the firearm and caliber approved by the police and annotated to the document before a silencer may be purchased. Applicants must show a \"good reason\" for needing the accessory.<ref name=\"Durham\">{{cite web|title=Sound Moderators|url=https://www.durham.police.uk/Information-and-advice/firearms-and-firearms-licensing/Pages/Sound-Moderators.aspx|website=Durham Constabulary|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n*In Germany, a silencer is treated the same in the eyes of the law as the weapon it is designed for. Accordingly, suppressors for [[BB gun|air guns]], which can be purchased by anyone over 18 years of age, can as well be purchased by anyone over 18. Since, amongst other things, \"good cause\" must be shown to be issued a license to own a firearm in Germany, the same \"good cause\" requirement exists for suppressors for these firearms. This requirement is handled very varyingly across the States of Germany. The State of [[Bavaria]] accepts the possession of a valid hunter's license as \"good cause\" to own an unlimited number of suppressors, while [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] does not accept hunting as a \"good cause\" at all. [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] accepts \"active exercise of hunting\" as \"good cause\", but only allows the purchase of one silencer.<ref name=\"Suppressor use while Hunting in Germany\">{{cite web|title=Jagdrecht in Bayern|url=http://www.wildtierportal.bayern.de/jagd/094822/index.php|website=Bavarian Ministry of Agriculture|accessdate=20 January 2017|language=German |trans-title=Hunting Laws in Bavaria}}</ref>\n*In Italy, a silencer is considered a prohibited firearms accessory, allowed only to the armed forces, police and government agency.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n*In the Czech Republic, a silencer is considered a prohibited firearms accessory, and as such can only be obtained with an extremely uncommon exception for weapon collectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvcr.cz/clanek/zbrane-podlehajici-zakonu-o-zbranich-a-podminky-jejich-nabyvani-a-drzeni.aspx?q=Y2hudW09NA%3d%3d|title=Ministry of Interior of the Czech Republic|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=Czech|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\n[[File:Legality of firearm suppressors by US jurisdiction.svg|thumb|Legality of firearm silencers by US jurisdiction{{legend|#008000|Silencers legal to own and hunt with}}\n{{legend|#FFA500|Silencers legal but illegal to hunt with}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|Silencers illegal}}\n|250x250px]]\n*In Canada, a device to muffle or stop the sound of a firearm is a \"prohibited device\" under the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code]].<ref name=\"LOIS\"/> A prohibited device is not inherently illegal in Canada but it does require an uncommon and very specific prohibited device license for its possession, use, and transport. Silencers cannot be imported into the country by civilians.<ref name=\"CBSA\"/> ''See [[Gun politics in Canada]]''\n*In the United States, taxes and strict regulations affect the manufacture and sale of silencers under the [[National Firearms Act]]. They are legal for individuals to possess and use for lawful purposes in 42 of the 50 states. However, a prospective owner must go through an application process administered by the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]] (ATF), which requires a federal tax payment of $200 and a thorough criminal [[background check]]. The tax payment buys a [[revenue stamp]], which is the legal document allowing possession of a suppressor. The eight states that have explicitly banned any civilian from possessing a suppressor are: [[California]], [[Delaware]], [[Hawaii]], [[Illinois]], [[Massachusetts]], [[New Jersey]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Rhode Island]],<ref name=\"VSA\"/> and the [[District of Columbia]]. The states of [[Connecticut]] and [[Vermont]] allow suppressor ownership, but prohibit using silencers while hunting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americansuppressorassociation.com/education/|title=Education|website=americansuppressorassociation.com|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref> The federal legal requirements to manufacture a suppressor in the United States are enumerated in [[Internal Revenue Code|Title 26]], Chapter 53 of the [[United States Code]].<ref name=\"Cornell-53\"/> Individual states and several municipalities also have their specific requirements. Federal law provides severe penalties for crimes of violence committed using firearms equipped with silencers, with a minimum prison sentence of 30 years.<ref name=\"Cornell-924\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westerncriminology.org/documents/WCR/v08n2/clark.pdf |title=Criminal Use of Firearm Silencers |last=Clark |first=Paul A. |website= |publisher=Western Criminology Review |accessdate=15 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\n=== Oceania ===\n* In Australia, use and ownership of silencers is generally limited to government, security and law enforcement use only and thus prohibited for civilians. \n* In New Zealand, following firearm law changes in April 2019, suppressors could still be fitted to a standard firearm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.police.govt.nz/advice/firearms-and-safety/changes-firearms-law-prohibited-firearms/firearms-changes-faqs |title=Firearms changes FAQs |website=New Zealand Police|author= |date= 15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* Notable suppressed firearms: [[De Lisle carbine]], [[Welrod]], [[PBS-1 Suppressor]], [[MSP Groza silent pistol]], [[OTs-38 Stechkin silent revolver]], [[VSS Vintorez]], [[Sten submachine gun|STEN mk II]]\n* [[Title II weapons]]\n* {{Section link|Piston effect|Tunnel boom}}, for a similar device but far bigger, on ends of railway tunnels\n* [[Sound blimp]], a device to reduce the noise made by a camera's shutter\n\n=== Other muzzle devices ===\n* [[Muzzle brake]]\n* [[Flash suppressor]]\n* [[Muzzle booster]]\n* [[Muzzle shroud]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"assassin\">[http://www.assassinstradecraft.com/Silencers.html .22 and .45 as easy to suppress ammunition]</ref>\n<ref name=atf34>{{ cite web |url = http://www.atf.gov/firearms/faq/firearms-technology.html |title = Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives, Silencer FAQ |accessdate = 2011-03-22 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"AWC\">dB in Principle and Practice, AWC Systems Technology April 2010</ref>\n<ref name=\"Ayoob2011\">{{ cite book |last = Ayoob |first = Massad |authorlink = Massad Ayoob |title = Gun Digest Book of Beretta Pistols |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=AD5Kg35n9PkC&pg=PA223 |date = 28 February 2011 |publisher = Gun Digest Books |location = Iola, Wisconsin |isbn = 978-1-4402-2424-9 |page = 223 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Barrett\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.guns.connect.fi/rs/btxgraaf.html |title = Reflex Suppressor for Barrett M82A1 - BR Reflex Suppressors (Finland) |publisher = Guns.connect.fi |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Baum2013\">{{ cite book |last = Baum |first = Dan |title = Gun Guys: A Road Trip |url = https://archive.org/details/gunguysroadtrip0000baum |url-access = registration |year = 2013 |publisher = Knopf |isbn = 978-0-307-59541-6 |pages = [https://archive.org/details/gunguysroadtrip0000baum/page/45 45]\u201346 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Boorman2001\">{{ cite book |last = Boorman |first = Dean K. |title = The History of Winchester Firearms |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dZmlpZivhU8C&pg=PA74 |year = 2001 |publisher = Globe Pequot Press |isbn = 978-1-58574-307-0 |page = 74 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Bull2004\">{{ cite book |last = Bull |first = Stephen |title = Encyclopedia of Military Technology and Innovation |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HN3AUx_3Mn4C&pg=PA237 |date = 1 January 2004 |publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn = 978-1-57356-557-8 |page = 237 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Carter2002\">{{ cite book |last = Carter |first = Gregg Lee |title = Guns in American Society: An Encyclopedia of History, Politics, Culture, and the Law |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=H_RrLyV9rDUC&pg=PA752 |date = 1 January 2002 |publisher = ABC-CLIO |isbn = 978-1-57607-268-4 |page = 512 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CBSA\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.cbsa-asfc.gc.ca/publications/pub/bsf5044-eng.html |title = Importing a Firearm or Weapon Into Canada |publisher = [[Canada Border Services Agency]] |accessdate = 2008-06-11 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Cornell-53\">{{ cite web |url = https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/html/uscode26/usc_sup_01_26_10_E_20_53.html |title = Title 26, United States Code, Chapter 53 - Legal Information Institute, Cornell University Law School |publisher = Law.cornell.edu |date = 2008-09-24 |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Cornell-924\">{{ cite web |url = https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/924 |title = Title 18, United States Code, Section 924(c)(1)(B)(ii) - Legal Information Institute, Cornell University Law School |publisher = Law.cornell.edu |date = 2013-02-13 |accessdate = 2013-03-17 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Dater2007\">{{ cite book |last1 = Dater |first1 = Philip |last2 = Dockery |first2 = Kevin |title = Stalkers and Shooters: A History of Snipers |chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_2zqCm-QRHoC&pg=PA234 |date = July 2007 |publisher = BERKLEY Publishing Group |isbn = 978-0-425-21542-5 |pages = 228\u2013235 |chapter = 28 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Dockery2007\">{{ cite book |last = Dockery |first = Kevin |authorlink = Kevin Dockery (author) |title = Stalkers and Shooters: A History of Snipers |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nYWZFOKFQ2gC&pg=PT218 |accessdate = 8 August 2013 |year = 2007 |publisher = Penguin Group US |location = New York |isbn = 978-1-4406-2890-0 |pages = 218\u2013235 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Dougherty2012\">{{ cite book |last = Dougherty |first = Martin J. |title = SAS and Elite Forces Guide Sniper: Sniping Skills from the World's Elite Forces |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nXNBdeseO1AC&pg=PT43 |date = 2012 |publisher = Lyons Press |isbn = 978-0-7627-8876-7 |pages = 43\u201344 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Emptormaven\">{{ cite web |last = Emptormaven |title = Rethinking Direct Impingement |url = http://emptormaven.com/2013/08/rethinking-direct-impingement-with-the-noveske-300-blk-upper/ |accessdate = 4 March 2014 |date = 2013-08-26 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Explosives\">{{ cite book |author=United States, Tobacco Bureau of Alcohol, and Firearms, Firearms Programs Division, Tobacco Bureau of Alcohol, Firearms and Explosives |title = Federal Firearms Regulations Reference Guide |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9encMNU8mwsC&pg=PA176 |accessdate = 8 August 2013 |publisher = DIANE Publishing |isbn = 978-1-4289-5186-0 |page = 176 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Gage\">{{ cite book |last = Gage |title = Electrical Record and Buyer's Reference |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6382AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA53 |year = 1913 |publisher = Buyers' Reference Company |location = New York |page = 53 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Goddard2000\">{{ cite book |last = Goddard |first = Stephen B. |title = Colonel Albert Pope and His American Dream Machines: The Life and Times of a Bicycle Tycoon Turned Automotive Pioneer |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6RVbAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA227 |date = 11 November 2000 |publisher = McFarland |isbn = 978-1-4766-1334-5 |page = 227 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Greener2002\">{{ cite book |last = Greener |first = W. W. |title = The Gun and Its Development |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=obxNmpITIPkC&pg=PR9 |date = 1 October 2002 |publisher = Lyons Press |isbn = 978-1-58574-734-4 |page = 9 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Heard2011\">{{ cite book |author=Brian J. Heard |title = Handbook of Firearms and Ballistics: Examining and Interpreting Forensic Evidence |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qd8TkbuC_bAC&pg=PT32 |accessdate = 6 January 2012 |date = 17 August 2011 |publisher = John Wiley and Sons |isbn = 978-1-119-96477-3 |page = 32 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hearing\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.hearingreview.com/issues/articles/2007-03_06.asp |title = Firearms and Hearing Protection &#124; March 2007 &#124; The Hearing Industry Resource |publisher = Hearingreview.com |date = 2007-02-12 |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kessler1994\">{{ cite book |last = Kessler |first = Ronald |title = Inside the CIA |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=l_EvNUJHTSoC&pg=PA187 |year = 1994 |publisher = Simon and Schuster |location = New York |isbn = 978-0-671-73458-9 |page = 187 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"LOIS\">{{ cite web |url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-46/FullText.html#h-38 |title = Criminal Code of Canada, Part III Firearms and other Weapons |accessdate = 2012-11-20 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Lovell\">Stanley Lovell (1963), ''Of Spies and Stratagems'', Englewood Cliffs, NJ: Prentice-Hall. Lovell claimed that a weapon so quiet would be more efficient than any death ray.</ref>\n<ref name=\"Mann2014\">{{ cite book |last = Mann |first = Richard A. |title = Gun Digest Shooter's Guide to the AR-15 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MQw5AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA232 |date = 30 April 2014 |publisher = Krause Publications |location = Iola, Wisconsin |isbn = 978-1-4402-3847-5 |pages = 232\u2013233 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MarkWhite\">{{ cite web |last = White |first = Mark |url = http://guns.connect.fi/gow/highpow.html |title = The Use of Sound Suppressors on High-Powered Rifles |publisher = Small Arms Review Vol. 1 No 7-9 |year = 1998 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Murray\">{{ cite web |url = http://campus.murraystate.edu/tsm/tsm118/Ch2/Ch2_7/Ch2_7.htm |title = 2.7: Decibels |publisher = Campus.murraystate.edu |accessdate = 2009-03-09}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418035925/http://campus.murraystate.edu/tsm/tsm118/Ch2/Ch2_7/Ch2_7.htm |date=April 18, 2009 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"NIHL\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.hearinglossweb.com/Medical/Causes/nihl/nihlfs.htm |title = nihl |publisher = Hearinglossweb.com |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Paulson2\">{{ cite book |last1 = Kokalis |first1 = Peter G.|author2 = Paulson, Alan C, and Parker, N.R. |title = Silencer History and Performance, Vol 2: CQB, Assault Rifle, and Sniper Technology |year = 2002 |publisher = Paladin Press |isbn = 1581603231 |page=49}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Paulson\">''Silencer: History and Performance, Volume 1'' by Alan C. Paulson</ref>\n<ref name=\"results\">{{ cite web |url = http://silencertalk.com/results.htm |title = Results |first = Robert |last = Silvers |publisher = |year = 2005 |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Rome\">{{ cite journal |last = Rome |first = Robert |date = June 1984 |title = WWII Silent Killer Still Lives |journal=Gung Ho |volume= |issue= |pages = 29 |doi= |url = http://www.valkyriearms.com/images/delisle.pdf |accessdate = }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"sniper\">{{ cite web |url = http://world.guns.ru/sniper/sn00-e.htm |title = Modern sniper rifles |publisher = world.guns.ru |date = 2001-01-26 |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Sparrow\">{{cite web|url=http://www.silencerco.com/?section=Products&page=Sparrow|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110108045602/http://www.silencerco.com/?section=Products&page=Sparrow|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-01-08|title=Suppressors - Silencers - SilencerCo|work=SilencerCo}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Supersonic\">{{cite web|url=http://guns.connect.fi/gow/highpow.html|title=Sound Suppressors on High-Powered Rifles|work=connect.fi}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Tilstra2014\">{{ cite book |last = Tilstra |first = Russell C. |title = The Battle Rifle: Development and Use Since World War II |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_a0zAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA165 |date = 21 March 2014 |publisher = McFarland |isbn = 978-1-4766-1564-6 |page = 165 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"USPTO-958935\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.google.com/patents?id=dWJ-AAAAEBAJ&pg=PA1&source=gbs_selected_pages&cad=2#v=onepage&q&f=false |title = US Patent 958935 - Google Patents }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"VSA\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.leg.state.vt.us/statutes/fullsection.cfm?title=13&chapter=085&Section=04010 |title = 13 V.S.A. \u00a7 4010. Gun silencers |accessdate = March 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Walker\">{{ cite book |last = Walker |first = Robert E. |title = Cartridges and Firearm Identification |publisher = CRC Press |location = Fort Myers, Florida |isbn = 978-1-4665-8881-3 |pages = 210\u2013214, 295 |date = 2013-03-21 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"WebbDoherty2010\">{{ cite book |last1 = Webb |first1 = Brandon |last2 = Doherty |first2 = Glen |title = 21st Century Sniper: The Complete Guide |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ClPffwtcYGMC&pg=PT71 |date = 15 September 2010 |publisher = Skyhorse Publishing Inc. |isbn = 978-1-61608-001-3 |pages = 71\u201372 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hollywood\">Examples of blaming Hollywood exaggeration of silencer effectiveness:\n*{{Citation |last=Sweeney |first=Patrick |title=Ruger silent-SR: One of the great names in firearms takes the plunge into a once-taboo market |magazine=[[Firearms News]] |date=February 10, 2017 |pages=32+ |publisher=[[Outdoor Sportsman Group]] {{subscription required|via=[[General OneFile]] }} |quote= With subsonic ammunition, the Silent-SR provided the Hollywood 'phuut-phuut' noise that all movie suppressors are supposed to deliver }}\n*{{Citation |postscript= [Joshua Waldron, co-founder of SilencerCo] \"So I see a big part of my job as educating the public about silencers and trying to undo so much of that stupid Hollywood idea about silencers being an assassin's tool. |last=McCombie |first=Brian |title= Joshua Waldron: how two guys in a rock band redesigned silencers and became the biggest suppressor maker in the nation |magazine=[[Gun Digest]] |date=August 28, 2014 |pages=48+ |publisher=Gun Digest Books {{subscription required|via=[[General OneFile]] }} }}\n*{{Citation |quote=Despite their Hollywood image, suppressors are not 'silencers.' They won't completely muffle rifle or handgun noise, and they won't stop the sonic crack of a bullet that comes from traveling beyond the speed of sound. |last= McCombie |first=Brian |title= Hush-up: how sound suppressors work and why you should own one |magazine=[[Outdoor Life]] |date=June\u2013July 2012 |page=82 |publisher=[[Bonnier Corporation]] {{subscription required|via=[[General OneFile]] }}  }}\n*{{Citation |quote=In the real world, 'silencers' are actually 'suppressors,' and they don't eliminate the sound of a gunshot so much as slightly reduce it-- |title=Hollywood has a lot to answer for. |magazine=[[National Review]] |date=February 6, 2017 |page= 10 |publisher=E. Garrett Bewkes IV {{subscription required|via=[[General OneFile]] }} }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Firearm silencers}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n*{{hsw|question112|How does a gun silencer work?||people}}\n\n[[Category:Firearm muzzle devices]]\n[[Category:Noise reduction]]\n[[Category:American inventions]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Suppressor|other uses|Suppressor (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Device which reduces sound intensity or muzzle flash on a firearm}}\n[[File:Cross section of a suppressor 01 noBG.jpg|thumb|Cutaway view of a silencer]]\n[[File:Suppressors.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|Several firearms with detachable silencers, from top to bottom: an [[Uzi]], a [[Short-barreled rifle]] or SBR, a [[Heckler & Koch USP]] Tactical, a [[Beretta 92|Beretta 92FS]], and a [[SIG Mosquito]]]]\n[[File:CZ 452 A silencer large.jpg|thumb|[[CZ 452]] bolt-action rimfire rifle with silencer]]\n[[File:Bundeswehr-Technik 02 (RaBoe).jpg|thumb|[[Accuracy International AWM|AWM-F]] [[sniper rifle]] with attached silencer]]\n\nA '''suppressor'''<!-- DO NOT REMOVE \"suppressor\". This term is the consensus pick. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Silencer_(firearms)#Requested_move_24_February_2018 -->, also known as a '''sound suppressor''' or '''sound moderator''', is a [[muzzle (firearms)|muzzle]] device that reduces the [[acoustic intensity]] of the muzzle report (sound of gunfire) and eliminates [[muzzle flash]] when a [[gun]] ([[firearm]] or [[air gun]]) is discharged, by modulating the speed and pressure of the gas ejection from the muzzle and hence suppressing the [[muzzle blast]].  Like a [[muzzle brake]], a silencer can be a detachable accessory mounted separately onto the muzzle, or an integral part of the [[gun barrel|barrel]].\n\nA typical silencer is a metal cylinder with internal [[sound baffle]]s that slow and cool the escaping [[propellant]] gas, dissipating its [[kinetic energy]] over a longer time and over a larger area, thus reducing the blast [[intensity (physics)|intensity]] and decreasing both the sound volume and [[recoil]] [[impulse (physics)|impulse]] generated during shooting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Firearms - Gun Control Act Definition - Silencer|url=https://www.atf.gov/firearms/firearms-guides-importation-verification-firearms-gun-control-act-definition-silencer|website=atf.gov|publisher=atf.gov|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref>  A [[flash suppressor]], on the other hand, specifically cools or disperses burning gases which typically already exited the muzzle of a [[carbine]]-length weapon to reduce the amount of [[muzzle flash|flash]], without reference to sound reduction.\n<!-- CLAIMS UNSUPPORTED IN BODY: Some jurisdictions allow, and even mandate, the sporting use of silencers, to reduce the risk of [[hearing loss]] and decrease [[noise pollution]], while other governments ban them for civilian use. -->\n\n==History==\nAmerican inventor [[Hiram Percy Maxim]], son of [[Maxim gun]] inventor [[Hiram Stevens Maxim]] and co-founder of the [[American Radio Relay League]], is usually credited with inventing and selling the first commercially successful silencer around 1902, receiving a patent for it on March 30, 1909.<ref name=\"USPTO-958935\"/><ref name=\"popular science 1923\">{{cite journal|last=Crossman|first=Edward|editor=Popular Science|number=2|volume=100|year=1923|publisher=Bonnier Corporation|page=48|title=Maxim's House of Silence|issn=0161-7370}}</ref><ref name=\"USAR1989\">{{cite book|last=USAR|first=William S. Brophy|title=Marlin Firearms: A History of the Guns and the Company That Made Them |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mdC3DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA653|date=1 May 1989|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=978-0-8117-4694-6|page=653|quote=During the early 1900s, Hiram Percy Maxim designed and patented gun silencers. His efforts were directed toward both military and sporting arms and resulted in his forming the Maxim Silencer Company, Hartford, Conn.}}</ref>  Maxim gave his device the [[generic trademark|popularly trademarked]] name \"Maxim Silencer\",<ref name=\"Freeman1997\">{{cite book|last=Freeman|first=Morton S.|title=A New Dictionary of Eponyms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dujiiVP2KJIC&pg=PA165 |date=18 December 1997|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-509354-4|page=165}}</ref> and they were regularly advertised in sporting goods magazines.<ref name=\"Gage\"/>  The [[muffler]] for [[internal combustion engine]]s was developed in parallel with the firearm silencer by Maxim in the early 20th century, using many of the same techniques to provide quieter-running engines, and in many English-speaking countries automobile mufflers are called silencers.<ref name=\"Goddard2000\"/>\n\nFormer president of the United States [[Theodore Roosevelt]] was known to purchase and use Maxim Silencers.<ref name=\"Boorman2001\"/>\n\nSilencers were regularly used by agents of the United States [[Office of Strategic Services]], who favored the newly designed [[High Standard HDM]] [[.22 LR]] pistol during [[World War II]].  OSS Director [[William Joseph Donovan|William Joseph \"Wild Bill\" Donovan]] demonstrated the pistol for President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] at the [[White House]].  According to OSS research chief Stanley Lovell,<ref name=\"Lovell\"/> Donovan, an old and trusted friend of the President, was waved into the [[Oval Office]], where Roosevelt was dictating a letter.  While Roosevelt finished his message, Donovan turned his back and fired ten shots into a sandbag he had brought with him, announced what he had done and handed the smoking gun to the astonished president.<ref name=\"Kessler1994\"/>  The British [[Special Operations Executive]] (SOE) [[Welrod]] pistol with an integral silencer was also used by the American OSS on clandestine operations in [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]]-occupied Europe.<ref name=\"Bull2004\"/>\n\n==Terminology==\nThe US [[National Firearms Act]] (NFA) of 1934 defined silencers and established regulations limiting their sale and ownership.<ref>Section 1(a), Public Law No. 474, Ch. 757, 48 Stat. 1236 (June 26, 1934).</ref> Both the [[United States Department of Justice|US Department of Justice]] and the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]] (ATF) use the term ''silencer''.<ref name=\"atf34\"/> Hiram Percy Maxim, the original inventor of the device, marketed them as \"Maxim Silencers\".<ref name=\"Greener2002\"/>\n\nThe earliest use of the technical term ''suppressor'' to refer to firearm noise reduction is in US Patent 4530417, July 23, 1985, \"A suppressor for reducing the muzzle blast of firearms or the like\".<ref>{{patent|US|4530417}}</ref>  In [[UK English]], ''silencer'' is the common term for either a motor vehicle muffler or for a gun silencer.<ref name=\"Goddard2000\"/>  ''Sound moderator'' has been used in UK English for silencers on high-powered rifles used for hunting or at ranges.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.shootinguk.co.uk/guns/sound-moderators-86396|title=Five sound moderators on test - Shooting UK|date=2016-12-21|website=Shooting UK |access-date=2018-04-11|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=The NRA Handbook Including The NRA Rules Of Shooting and the Programme of the Imperial Meeting Friday 17 June To Saturday 23 July 2016 |date=March 26, 2016 |publisher=[[National Rifle Association of the United Kingdom]] |url=http://www.chichesterrifleclub.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/2016-NRA-Handbook.pdf }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Oxford English Dictionary|Oxford]], [[The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language|American Heritage]], and other dictionaries apply the term ''suppressor'' to such contexts as [[electromagnetic shielding]] devices, [[Suppressor mutation|genetics]], and [[censorship]], but not firearms.<ref name=\"OEDsilencer\">{{Cite OED|silencer}}</ref><ref name=\"OEDsuppressor\">{{Cite OED|suppressor}}</ref><ref name=\"AHDsuppressor\">{{AHDict |suppressor}}</ref><ref name=\"DictionarySupressor\">{{Dictionary.com|suppressor |accessdate=2018-02-24}}</ref>  These dictionaries define both ''silencer'' and ''suppressor'' as essentially equivalent and interchangeable, neither applying exclusively or primarily to sound, and both being applicable as much to complete and total quiet or to partial reduction of sound.<ref name=\"OEDsilencer\" /><ref name=\"OEDsuppressor\" /><ref name=\"AHDsuppressor\" /><ref name=\"DictionarySupressor\" />\n\nIn 2011, the US [[National Rifle Association]] began a campaign to increase the civilian use of silencers for hunting and sport shooting, setting the goals of easing the restrictions in the [[National Firearms Act of 1934|Federal NFA of 1934]], and in various state laws, regulating the sale and ownership of firearm silencers.  In the same year, the American Silencer Association (ASA) was founded by US manufacturers of silencers, with the same goals of moving silencers into the mainstream.<ref name=\"LaSorte2011\" /><ref name=\"Devaney2017\">{{Citation |url=http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/335348-gun-lobby-seeks-to-calm-fears-about-silencers |title=Gun lobby seeks to calm fears about silencers |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |first=Tim |last=Devaney |date=May 5, 2017 }}</ref>  Along with state and federal legislative lobbying efforts, the NRA and ASA began public information campaigns designed to change the perception of silencers from their association with espionage, assassination, crime or military special operation use, to instead show that silencers can have health and safety benefits, primarily protecting the hearing of shooters and people in the vicinity, and to debunk the perceived myth in popular television, film and video game media that silencers are so effective that gunshot sounds can go totally unnoticed, such as by people in the next room of a building.<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/><ref name=\"LaSorte2011\">{{Citation |url=https://www.americanrifleman.org/articles/2011/12/22/suppressors-for-hearing-and-the-shooting-sports/ |title= Suppressors: For Hearing and the Shooting Sports |first=Darren |last=LaSorte |date=December 22, 2011 |magazine=[[American Rifleman]] |publisher=[[National Rifle Association]] }}</ref><ref name=\"Rosenwald2017\">{{Citation |title= Gun silencers are hard to buy. Donald Trump Jr. and silencer makers want to change that |first=Michael S. |last=Rosenwald |date=January 9, 2017 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/gun-silencers-are-hard-to-buy-donald-trump-jr-and-silencer-makers-want-to-change-that/2017/01/07/0764ab4c-d2d2-11e6-9cb0-54ab630851e8_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the ASA changed its name to American Suppressor Association \"in a continuing effort to dispel myths about suppressors\".<ref>{{Citation |url= http://www.guns.com/2014/05/09/asa-changes-its-name-to-american-suppressor-association/ |title= ASA changes its name to American Suppressor Association |date= May 9, 2014 |first=Max |last=Slowik }}</ref>  Gun control advocates have said that changing the name from \"silencer\" to \"suppressor\" is semantic propaganda similar to the efforts to avoid terms like \"[[assault rifle]]\" or \"[[assault weapon]]\" in favor of friendlier-sounding language like \"[[modern sporting rifle]]\", while gun rights advocates make essentially the opposite argument, and also that the widespread term ''silencer'' reflects technical ignorance and is poorly defined.<ref name=\"Devaney2017\" /><ref name=\"Rosenwald2017\" />\n\nGun rights advocates and gun media generally say that the word \"silencer\" is defined as meaning ''total'' silence, while \"suppressor\" is defined as only meaning reduced sound intensity.<ref name=\"Devaney2017\" /><ref name=\"Rosenwald2017\" />\n\n==Firearm noise anatomy==\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2019}}\nWhen a firearm is discharged, there are three ways sound is produced.  Part of it can be managed; however, some of it is beyond the ability of the operator or manufacturers to eliminate.\n\nIn order of importance, the three ways a firearm generates sound are:\n*Muzzle blast \u2014 [[shockwave]] generated by high-pressure gases escaping and expanding from the muzzle after the [[projectile]] exits the barrel and breaks the functional [[seal (mechanical)|seal]] restraining the gas inside the [[gun barrel#Bore|bore]]\n*[[Sonic boom]] \u2014 sharp [[bullwhip]]-cracking sound associated with high-frequency shockwaves caused by an object (in this case, the [[bullet]]) flying [[supersonic]]ally through the air\n*Mechanical noise generated by the internal moving parts of the [[firearm action]]\n\nA silencer can only affect the noise generated by the muzzle blast.  While using [[subsonic ammunition]]s can negate the sonic boom, mechanical noise can be mitigated but is nearly impossible to eliminate.  For these reasons, it is difficult to completely silence any firearm, or achieve an acceptable{{clarify|date=June 2018}} level of noise suppression in [[revolver]]s that function under standard operating principles due to the looser gas seal between the barrel and the [[cylinder (firearms)|cylinder]].  Some revolvers have technical features that enable suppression and include the Russian [[Nagant M1895]] and [[OTs-38]] revolvers, and the [[S&W QSPR]].\n\n[[Muzzle blast]] generated by firearm discharge is directly proportional to the amount of [[propellant]] to be combusted within the [[cartridge (firearms)|cartridge]].  Therefore, the greater the case capacity (e.g. a [[magnum cartridge]]), the louder the muzzle blast and consequently a more efficient or larger silencer system is required.  A gunshot (the combination of the sonic boom, the vacuum release, and hot gases) will almost always be louder than the sound of the action cycling of an [[semi-automatic firearm|autoloading firearm]].  Alan C. Paulson, a renowned firearms specialist, claimed to have encountered an integrally suppressed .22 LR gun that had such a quiet report {{clarify|date=August 2019}} ,<ref name=\"Paulson\"/> although this is somewhat uncommon.  Properly evaluating the sound generated by a firearm can only be done using a [[Decibel Meters|decibel meter]] in conjunction with a [[frequency spectrum]] analyzer during live tests.\n\n==Design and construction==\n[[File:ReflexSuppressor-WP-Drwg.png|thumb|Cross-section drawing of a centerfire rifle silencer, showing expansion chamber \"reflexed\" (going back around) the rifle barrel, and four sound baffles. The diffractor and baffles are carefully shaped to deflect gas.|alt=]]\n[[File:Vaime-Suppressor-22-WP-Drwg.png|thumb|Cross-section drawing of a rimfire rifle silencer, showing short expansion chamber and thirteen plastic baffles. These baffles use alternating angled flat surfaces to repeatedly deflect gas expanding through the silencer. In the actual silencer, the baffles are oriented at 90 degrees to each other about the axis of bullet travel. (The illustration cannot demonstrate this well.)]]\n[[File:Navy-HushPuppy-WP-Drwg.png|thumb|Cross-section drawing of a pistol silencer, showing expansion chamber wrapped around inner suppressor assembly, and four wipes. The bullet pushes a bullet-diameter hole through the wipes, trapping propellant gas behind it entirely until the bullet has passed through the wipe completely]]\n[[File:Patent DE1553874 07-Oct-1971 Handfeuerwaffe mit Schalldaempfer Heckler und Koch.png|thumb|Cross section drawing of an \"integral\" sound suppressor in part designed and built into the suppressed firearm.]]\n\nThe silencer is typically a hollow metal tube manufactured from [[steel]], [[aluminum]], or [[titanium]] and contains expansion chambers. This device, typically cylindrical in shape, attaches to the [[muzzle (firearm)|muzzle]] of a [[pistol]], [[submachine gun]], or [[rifle]]. Some \"can\"-type silencers (so-called as they often resemble a [[beverage can]]) may be detached by the user and attached to a different firearm. Another type is the \"integral\" suppressor, which typically consists of an expansion chamber or chambers surrounding the barrel. The barrel has openings or \"ports\" which bleed off gases into the chambers. This type of silencer is part of the firearm (thus the term \"integral\"), and maintenance of the suppressor requires that the firearm be at least partially disassembled.<ref name=\"Heard2011\"/>\n\n[[File:Huntertown Kestrel 5.56 disassembled.JPG|thumb|left|Firearm suppressor disassembled to show blast chamber, baffles, and sections of the outer tube]]\n\nBoth types of silencers reduce noise by allowing the rapidly expanding gases from the firing of the cartridge to be decelerated and cooled through a series of hollow chambers. The trapped gas exits the suppressor over a longer period of time and at a greatly reduced speed, producing less noise signature. The chambers are divided by either ''baffles'' or ''wipes''. There are typically at least four and up to perhaps fifteen chambers in a suppressor, depending on the intended use and design details. Often, a single, larger expansion chamber is located at the muzzle end of a can-type silencer, which allows the propellant gas to expand considerably and slow down before it encounters the baffles or wipes. This larger chamber may be \"reflexed\" toward the rear of the barrel to minimize the overall length of the combined firearm and silencer, especially with longer weapons such as rifles.\n\nSilencers vary greatly in size and efficiency. One disposable type developed in the 1980s by the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] for [[9\u00d719mm]] pistols was {{convert|150|mm|in|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|45|mm|in|abbr=on}} in outside diameter, and was designed for six shots with standard ammunition or up to thirty shots with [[speed of sound|subsonic]] (slower than the speed of sound) [[ammunition]]. In contrast, one suppressor designed for rifles firing the powerful [[.50 BMG|.50 caliber (BMG)]] cartridge is {{convert|509|mm|in|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|76|mm|in|abbr=on}} in diameter.<ref name=\"Barrett\"/>\n\nTwo ancillary advantages to the silencer are recoil reduction and flash suppression. Muzzle flash is reduced by both being contained in the suppressor and through the arresting of unburned powder that would normally burn in the air, adding to the flash. Recoil reduction results from the slowing of propellant gasses, which can contribute 30\u201350% of recoil velocity. However, some suppressors can increase the backpressure produced by the propellant gasses. This can cause them to function somewhat like a [[muzzle booster]] and thus increase the felt recoil. The weight of the silencer and the location of that additional weight at the muzzle reduce recoil through basic mass as well as muzzle flip due to the location of this mass.\n\n===Components===\n\n===Baffles and spacers===\nBaffles are usually circular metal dividers which separate the expansion chambers. Each baffle has a hole in its center to permit the passage of the bullet through the silencer and toward the target. The hole is typically at least 1&nbsp;mm larger than the bullet caliber to minimize the risk of the bullet hitting the baffle in what is known as a \"baffle strike\". Baffles are typically made of stainless steel, aluminum, titanium, or alloys such as [[Inconel]], and are either [[machining|machined]] out of solid metal or [[stamping (metalworking)|stamped]] out of sheet metal. A few silencers for low-powered cartridges such as the [[.22 Long Rifle]] have successfully used plastic baffles (certain models by Vaime and others).<ref name=\"Paulson\"/>{{rp|186\u2013187}}\n\nThere are several unique baffle designs. M, K, Z, monolithic core<ref name=\"Sparrow\"/> and \u03a9 (Omega) are the most prevalent. M-type is the crudest and comprises an inverted [[cone (geometry)|cone]]. K forms slanted obstructions diverging from the sidewalls, creating [[turbulence]] across the [[gauge (bore diameter)|bore]]line. Z is expensive to machine and includes \"pockets\" of dead airspace along the sidewalls which trap expanded gases and hold them thereby lengthening the time that the gases cool before exiting. Omega-type baffles form a series of spaced cones drawing gas away from the boreline and incorporate a scalloped mouth creating cross-bore turbulence, which is in turn directed to a \"mouse-hole\" opening between the baffle stack and sidewall.\n\nPropellant gas heats and erodes the baffles, causing wear, which is worsened by high rates of fire. Aluminum baffles are seldom used with fully [[automatic firearm|automatic weapon]]s, because service life is unacceptably short. Some modern suppressors using steel or high-temperature alloy baffles can endure extended periods of fully automatic fire without damage. The highest-quality rifle suppressors available today have a claimed service life of greater than 30,000 rounds.<ref name=\"Paulson\"/>{{rp|363\u2013364}} Baffles have not been given any specific angles, a specific size, or weight to meet any standards; they are created on a trial and error basis.<ref name=\"Walker\"/>\n\nSpacers separate baffles and keep them aligned at a specified distance from each other inside the silencer. Many baffles and spacers are manufactured as a single assembly and several suppressor designs have all the baffles attached together with spacers as a one-piece helical baffle stack. Modern baffles are usually carefully shaped to divert the propellant gases effectively into the chambers. This shaping can be a slanted flat surface, canted at an angle to the bore, or a conical or otherwise curved surface. One popular technique is to have alternating angled surfaces through the stack of baffles.<ref name=\"Walker\"/>\n\n===Wipes and packing material===\nWipes are inner dividers intended to touch the bullet as it passes through the silencer, and are typically made of [[rubber]], [[plastic]], or [[foam]]. Each wipe may either have a hole drilled in it before use, a pattern stamped into its surface at the point where the bullet will strike it, or it may simply be punched through by the bullet. Wipes typically last for a small number of firings (perhaps no more than five) before their performance is significantly degraded. While many suppressors used wipes in the [[Vietnam War]] era, most modern suppressors do not use them as anything that touches the projectile has significant accuracy implications. All \"wipes\" deteriorate quickly and require disassembly and spare parts replacement.<ref name=\"Dockery2007\"/>\n\n\"Wet\" silencers or \"wet cans\" use a small quantity of water, [[oil]], [[petroleum|grease]], or [[gel]] in the expansion chambers to cool the propellant gases and reduce their volume (see [[ideal gas law]]). The coolant lasts only a few shots before it must be replenished, but can greatly increase the effectiveness of the suppressor. Water is most effective, due to its high [[heat of vaporization]], but it can run or evaporate out of the silencer. Grease, while messier and less effective than water, can be left in the suppressor indefinitely without losing effectiveness. Oil is the least effective and least preferable, as it runs while being as messy as grease, and leaves behind a fine mist of [[aerosol]]ized oil after each shot. Water-based gels, such as wire-pulling lubricant gel, are a good compromise; they offer the efficacy of water with less mess, as they do not run or drip. However, they take longer to apply, as they must be cleared from the bore of the suppressor to ensure a clear path for the bullet (grease requires this step as well). Generally, only pistol silencers are shot wet, as rifle silencers handle such high pressure and heat that the liquid is gone within 1\u20133 shots. Many manufacturers will not warranty their rifle suppressors for \"wet\" fire, as some feel this may even result in a dangerous over-pressurization of the silencer.<ref name=\"Walker\"/>\n\nPacking materials such as metal [[mesh]], [[steel wool]], or [[washer (hardware)|metal washers]] may be used to fill the chambers and further dissipate and cool the gases. These are somewhat more effective than empty chambers, but less effective than wet designs.<ref name=\"Paulson\"/>{{rp|130}} Metal mesh, if properly used, may last for hundreds or thousands of shots of spaced semi-automatic fire; however, steel wool usually degrades within ten shots, with stainless steel wool lasting longer than regular steel wool. Like wipes, packing materials are rarely found in modern silencers.<ref name=\"Walker\"/>\n\nWipes, packing materials and purpose-designed wet cans have been generally abandoned in 21st-century suppressor design because they decrease overall accuracy and require excessive cleaning and maintenance.<ref name=\"Dockery2007\"/> The instructions from several manufacturers state that their suppressors need not be cleaned at all.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018|reason=Which manufacturers? Where is this stated?}} Furthermore, legal changes in the United States during the 1980s and 1990s made it much more difficult for end-users to legally replace internal silencer parts, and the newer designs reflect this reality.<ref name=\"Explosives\"/>\n\n===Attachment===\n[[File:AOW and SBR suppressed.jpg|thumb|Silenced 12 gauge shotgun and 7.62\u00d739&nbsp;mm rifle]]\nApart from integral silencers which are integrated as a part of the firearm's barrel, most suppressors have a \"female\" threaded end, which attaches to \"male\" threads cut into the exterior of the barrel. These types of silencers are mostly used on handguns and rifles chambered in .22LR. More powerful rifles may use this type of attachment, but harsh recoil may cause the suppressor to over-tighten to the barrel and the suppressor can become difficult to remove.<ref name=\"Walker\"/> [[SilencerCo]]'s Salvo silencer for shotguns attaches via internal barrel threading normally used to mount removable [[Choke (firearms)|chokes]].<ref>Waldron, Len. \"SilencerCo Salvo 12 Gauge Suppressor Review.\" ''Guns &''\n Ammo''. March 7, 2016. [http://www.gunsandammo.com/gear-accessories/suppressors/silencerco-salvo-12-suppressor-review/]''</ref>\n\nMilitary rifles such as the [[M16 rifle|M16]] or [[M14 rifle|M14]] often use \"quick-detach\" suppressors which use coarser than normal threads and are installed over an existing muzzle device such as a flash suppressor and may include a secondary locking mechanism to allow the shooter to quickly and safely add or remove a sound suppressor based on individual needs.<ref name=\"Walker\"/>\n\n===Advanced types===\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2019|reason=mostly essay}}\n[[File:SilencerCo Osprey .45.JPG|thumb|[[SilencerCo]] Osprey .45 silencer on a Springfield pistol]]\n\nIn addition to containing and slowly releasing the gas pressure associated with muzzle blast or reducing pressure through the use of coolant mediums, advanced silencer designs attempt to modify the properties of the sound waves generated by the muzzle blast. In these designs, effects known as [[frequency shifting]] and [[interference (wave propagation)|phase cancellation]] (or destructive interference) are used in an attempt to make the suppressor quieter. These effects are achieved by separating the flow of gases and causing them to collide with each other or by venting them through precision-made holes. The intended effect of frequency shifting is to shift audible sound waves frequencies into [[ultrasound]] (above 20 [[Hertz|kHz]]), beyond the range of human hearing. The Russian [[AN-94]] assault rifle has a muzzle attachment that claims apparent noise reduction by venting some gases through a \"dog-whistle\" type channel. Phase cancellation occurs when similar sound waves encounter each other 180\u00b0 out of phase, cancelling the amplitude of the wave and eliminating the pressure variations perceived as sound.\n\nAn alternate method under development is called the anti-phase destructive interference generator.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} The process involves duplication of the sound waves generated by the muzzle blast, which are then used to create an anti-phase auditory signal. Currently, this is a muzzle attached device, and is only being tested to cancel out the gunshot sound of the firearm. The devices tested incorporate multiple microphones, speakers and an auditory processor. The first shot fired is recorded, and then played back precisely out of sync(180 degrees out of phase) with each subsequent shot. This has proven successful with small caliber(.17-.22) rifles, but the amplitude has not been matched efficiently with larger cartridges. With the use of subsonic ammunition, the resultant sound waves effectively cancel each other out, and with the exception of the sound of the action cycling, completely eliminate any gunshot sound. In the current development stage, this has worked only in close proximity to the shooter, and the pressure wave(p-wave) can still be felt. Each time a different type of ammunition or firearm is used, the device needs recalibration.\n\nTaking advantage of either property requires that the silencer be designed within the specification of the muzzle blast in mind. For example, the velocity of the sound waves is a major factor. This figure can change significantly between different cartridges and barrel lengths.\n\nHowever, these concepts are controversial because a muzzle blast creates [[white noise|broadband noise]] rather than [[pure tone]]s, and phase cancellation in particular is therefore extremely difficult (if not impossible) to achieve. Some suppressor manufacturers claim to use phase cancellation in their designs.<ref name=\"WebbDoherty2010\"/>\n\nFrom a physics standpoint, supersonic cartridge loads are impractical to suppress past the levels that are merely hearing-safe for the shooter due to the sonic boom emitted by the bullet, and cartridges such as [[.22 LR]] and [[.45 ACP]] have long been recognized as the easiest to suppress even if using technology dating back to the 1940s.<ref name=\"assassin\"/><ref name=\"Supersonic\"/>\n\n===Captive-piston silencer===\nAnother silencer technology uses a captive piston cartridge; examples are the Smith & Wesson [[Quiet Special Purpose Revolver]] (QSPR) and the Soviet and Russian [[PSS silent pistol]],<ref name=sadj>{{cite web |url=http://www.sadefensejournal.com/wp/beyond-quiet-the-russian-pss-captive-piston-pistol/ |title=Beyond Quiet: The Russian PSS Captive Piston Pistol (2 Web pages)|website=Small Arms Defense Journa|date=16 August 2011|author= |accessdate= 14 June 2019}}</ref> [[OTs-38 Stechkin silent revolver]] and the MTs-116M suppressed sniper rifle, a 12.7mm silenced development of the 7.62mm MTs-116M.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/weapons/a22862616/russia-silent-sniper-rifle/ |title=The Science of Russia's New Silent Sniper Rifle |website=Popular Mechanics|date=25 August 2018 |author=David Hambling |accessdate= 14 June 2019}}</ref> The large calibre allows the bullet to be fired at subsonic speed, eliminating a major source of noise, while retaining accuracy, range, and effectiveness. All these weapons use special, very expensive, captive-piston ammunition; the QSPR used ammunition which resembled metal-cased .410-bore shotgun shells. The cartridge case internally works as a piston to trap the gases; the piston pushes the bullet, but the gases are retained in the cartridge case instead of being expelled noisily; in tests of the PSS the sound pressure level was 124.6&nbsp;[[Decibel|dB]], similar to a suppressed .22 rimfire pistol.<ref name=sadj/> The ammunition itself, rather than the weapon, is silent; in the US each individual round is considered to be a silencer, subject to regulations on silencers.<ref name=sadj/>\n\n===Improvised silencers===\nImprovised silencers have been made from a variety of materials. In 2015, [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department|Los Angeles County Sheriff deputies]] recovered a [[ZB vz. 26]] [[light machine gun]] with an automobile [[oil filter]] attached.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weingarten|first1=Dean|title=Homeless Man's Black Market Submachine Guns and Improvised Silencer|url=http://www.thetruthaboutguns.com/2015/11/dean-weingarten/homeless-mans-black-market-submachine-guns-improvised-silencer/|accessdate=12 October 2016|work=thetruthaboutguns.com|date=November 27, 2015}}</ref> [[Polyvinyl chloride#Pipes|PVC pipes]], plastic water bottles, and foam-filled pillows are also used.<ref name=\"Hollenbach\"/><ref name=\"Emerson\">{{cite book|last1=Emerson|first1=Clint|title=100 Deadly Skills: The SEAL Operative's Guide to Eluding Pursuers, Evading Capture, and Surviving Any Dangerous Situation|date=Oct 13, 2015|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1476796055|page=70|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xi-rCgAAQBAJ|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|chapter=Injuries Due to Firearms and Other Missile-Launching Devices|title=Forensic Neuropathology: A Practical Review of the Fundamentals|first1=Hideo H. |last1=Itabashi|page=223|publisher=Academic Press|date=2011|isbn=978-0080549842}}</ref> In the United States, improvised silencers are governed by the same laws as manufactured ones.<ref name=\"Hollenbach\">{{cite book|last1=Hollenbach|first1=George M.|title=Workbench Silencers: The Art Of Improvised Designs|date=1996|publisher=Paladin Press|isbn=1610046773|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fX_KAwAAQBAJ|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Nielsen device area of YHM Cobra .45 suppressor.jpg|thumb|Rear of a silencer with the [[Muzzle booster|Nielsen device]] protruding (completely assembled)]]\n[[File:Nielsen device of YHM Cobra .45 suppressor partially removed.jpg|thumb|Retaining ring unscrewed and Nielsen device partially removed]]\n[[File:Nielsen device of YHM Cobra .45 suppressor completely disassembled.jpg|thumb|Nielsen device completely removed and disassembled]]\n[[File:Rotational indexing system of YHM Cobra .45 suppressor Nielsen device.jpg|thumb|Rear of silencer showing the rotational indexing system incorporated into some Nielsen devices]]\n\nFunctionally, a suppressor is meant to diminish the report of a discharged round, or make its sound unrecognizable. Other sounds emanating from the weapon remain unchanged. Even subsonic bullets make distinct sounds by their passage through the air and striking targets, and supersonic bullets produce a small sonic boom, resulting in a \"ballistic crack\". Semi-automatic and fully automatic firearms also make distinct noises as their actions cycle, ejecting the fired cartridge case and loading a new round.\n\nAside from reductions in volume, suppressors tend to alter the sound to something that is not identifiable as a gunshot.<ref name=\"Dougherty2012\"/> This reduces or eliminates attention drawn to the shooter. A Finnish expression dating from the [[Winter War]] says that \"A silencer does not make a soldier silent, but it does make him invisible.\"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Guns & Weapons for Law Enforcement|year= 2004|issue=8|title=Finland's Silenced .338 Long-Range Sniper:Sako TRG42 Rifle and BR-Tuote T8M Reflex Suppressor|first= Al |last=Paulson|publisher=Harris Publications|location=New York|volume=1|url=http://www.canadiantactical.ca/PaulsonArticle2.html}}</ref> Silencers are particularly useful in enclosed spaces where the sound, flash and pressure effects of a weapon being fired are amplified. Such effects may disorient the shooter, affecting [[situational awareness]], concentration and accuracy, and can permanently damage hearing very quickly.<ref name=\"Dater2007\"/>\n\nAs the suppressed sound of firing is overshadowed by ballistic crack, observers can be deceived as to the location of the shooter, often from 90 to 180 degrees from his actual location. However, [[counter-sniper tactics]] can include [[gunfire locator]]s, such as the U.S. [[Boomerang (mobile shooter detection system)|Boomerang]] system, where sensitive microphones are coupled to computers running algorithms, and use the ballistic crack to detect and localize the origin of the shot.\n\nThere are many advantages in using a silencer that are not related to the sound.\n\nHunters using [[Centerfire ammunition|centerfire rifles]] find silencers bring various important benefits that outweigh the extra weight and resulting change in the firearm's center of gravity. The most important advantage of a suppressor is the hearing protection for the shooter as well as their companions. Many hunters have suffered permanent hearing damage due to someone else firing a high-caliber gun too closely without warning.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=National Hearing Conservation Association|year= 2017|title=NHCA Position Statement, Recreational Firearm Noise |first=Michael |last=Stewart |first2=Deanna K. |last2=Meinke |first3=Gregory A. |last3=Flamme |first4=William J. |last4=Murphy |first5=Donald S. |last5=Finan |first6=James E. |last6=Lankford |first7=Stephen M. |last7= Tasko |url=https://www.hearingconservation.org/assets/docs/NHCA_position_paper_on_firea.pdf}}</ref> By reducing noise, recoil and muzzle-blast, it also enables the firer to follow through calmly on their first shot and fire a further carefully aimed shot without delay if necessary. [[Wildlife]] of all kinds are often confused as to the direction of the source of a well-suppressed shot. In the field, however, the comparatively large size of a centerfire rifle suppressor can cause unwanted noise if it bumps or rubs against vegetation or rocks, so many users cover them with [[neoprene]] sleeves.<ref name=\"Mann2014\"/>\n\nSilencers reduce firing [[recoil]] significantly, primarily by diverting and trapping the propellant gas. The gas generally has much less mass than the projectile, but it exits the muzzle at multiples of the projectile velocity, so reducing the speed and quantity of the gas expelled can significantly reduce the total [[momentum]] of the matter (gas and projectile) leaving the barrel, the negation of which, because momentum is [[Conservation of momentum|conserved]], is transferred to the gun as recoil. Paulson ''et al.'', discussing low-velocity pistol calibers, suggest the recoil reduction is around 15%.<ref name=\"Paulson\"/>{{rp|38\u201340}} With high-velocity calibers, recoil reduction runs in the range of 20\u201330%.<ref name=\"MarkWhite\"/> The added mass of the suppressor\u2014normally 300 to 500&nbsp;grams\u2014also helps to manage the recoil.\n\nA suppressor also cools the hot gases coming out of the barrel enough that most of the [[lead]]-laced [[vapor]] that leaves the barrel [[condensation|condenses]] inside the silencer, reducing the amount of lead that might be inhaled by the shooter and others around them. However, in auto-loading actions this might be offset by increased [[back pressure]], which results in propellant gas blowing back into a shooter's face through the chamber during case ejection.<ref name=\"Emptormaven\"/>\n\n===Subsonic ammunition===\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2019}}\nIn weapons firing [[supersonic]] ammunition, the bullet itself produces a loud and very sharp sound as it leaves the muzzle in excess of the speed of sound and gradually reducing speed as it travels downrange. This is a small sonic boom, and is referred to in the firearm field as \"ballistic crack\" or \"sonic signature\". Subsonic ammunition eliminates this sound, but at the cost of lower velocity, resulting in decreased range and much decreased [[muzzle energy]] unless the bullet weight is increased, thus lessening effectiveness on the target. For example, if the muzzle velocity is reduced from {{cvt|820|m/s|order=flip}} (common for the [[.308 Winchester]], for example) to a subsonic {{cvt|290|m/s|order=flip}}, the muzzle energy is reduced by a factor of 8. Military marksmen and police units may use subsonic ammunition in suppressed rifles, when minimal noise is more important than range and energy.<ref name=\"sniper\"/>\n\nHowever, the numeric effectiveness of subsonic rounds is, again, misrepresented by media.<ref name=\"Dockery2007\"/> Independent testing of commercially available firearm suppressors with commercially available subsonic rounds has found that .308 subsonic rounds decreased the volume at the muzzle by 10 to 12&nbsp;dB when compared to the same caliber of suppressed supersonic ammunition.<ref name=\"results\" /> When combined with silencers, the subsonic .308 rounds metered between 121 and 137&nbsp;dB.\n\nThe ballistic crack depends on the speed of sound, which in turn depends mainly on air temperature. At sea level, an ambient temperature of {{convert|70|F}}, and under normal atmospheric conditions, the speed of sound is approximately {{convert|1140|ft/s}}. Bullets that travel near the speed of sound are considered [[transonic]], which means that the airflow over the surface of the bullet, which at points travels faster than the bullet itself, can break the speed of sound. [[Bullet#Pointed bullets|Pointed bullets]], which gradually displace air, can get closer to the speed of sound than round- or snub-nosed bullets before becoming transonic.\n\nSpecial cartridges have been developed for use with a silencer. These cartridges use very heavy bullets to make up for the energy lost by keeping the bullet subsonic. A good example of this is the [[.300 Whisper]] cartridge, which is formed from a necked-up [[.221 Remington Fireball]] cartridge case. The subsonic .300 Whisper fires up to a {{convert|250|gr}}, .30 caliber bullet at about {{convert|980|ft/s}}, generating about {{convert|533|ftlbf}} of energy at the muzzle. While this is similar to the energy available from the .45 ACP pistol cartridge, the reduced diameter and streamlined shape of the heavy .30 caliber bullet provides far better [[external ballistics|external ballistic]] performance, improving range substantially.\n\n[[9\u00d719mm Parabellum|9\u00d719&nbsp;mm Parabellum]], a very popular caliber for suppressed shooting, can use almost any factory-loaded {{convert|147|gr}} weight round to achieve subsonic performance. These 147&nbsp;gr weight bullets typically have a velocity of {{convert|900|-|980|ft/s}}, which is less than the {{convert|1140|ft/s}} speed of sound.<ref name=\"Ayoob2011\"/>\n[[File:AS Val & VSS Vintorez - RaceofHeroes-part2-34 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Integral silencer on [[VSS Vintorez]] sniper rifle and [[AS Val]] assault rifle]]\nThe [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]/Russian [[Armor-piercing shot and shell#Small arms|armor-piercing]] [[9\u00d739mm]] ammunition used in rifles such as the [[AS Val]] has a high subsonic [[ballistic coefficient]], high retained downrange energy, high [[sectional density]], and moderate recoil.<ref name=\"Tilstra2014\"/>\n\nWithout using subsonic ammunition, the [[muzzle velocity]] of a supersonic bullet can be lowered by other means, before it leaves the barrel. Some silencer designs, referred to as \"integrals\", do this by allowing gas to bleed off along the length of the barrel before the projectile exits. The [[MP5SD]] is an example of this, with holes right after the chamber of the barrel used to reduce a regular 115 or 124&nbsp;gr ammunition to subsonic velocities.<ref name=\"Heard2011\"/>\n\n==Effectiveness==\n[[File:Silencerco Osprey 9, SWR Octane 45, and Silencerco Saker 5.56.JPG|thumb|Firearm silencers including the SilencerCo Osprey 9, SWR Octane 45, and SilencerCo Saker 5.56]]\n\nLive tests by independent reviewers of numerous commercially available suppressors find that even low-power, unsuppressed .22&nbsp;LR handguns produce gunshots over 160&nbsp;[[decibels]].<ref name=\"results\"/> A recent study of various suppressors reported peak sound pressure level reductions between 17 dB and 24 dB.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Murphy|first=William J.|last2=Flamme|first2=Gregory A.|last3=Campbell|first3=Adam R.|last4=Zechmann|first4=Edward L.|last5=Tasko|first5=Stephen M.|last6=Lankford|first6=James E.|last7=Meinke|first7=Deanna K.|last8=Finan|first8=Donald S.|last9=Stewart|first9=Michael|date=2018-01-26|title=The reduction of gunshot noise and auditory risk through the use of firearm suppressors and low-velocity ammunition|journal=International Journal of Audiology|volume=57|issue=sup1|pages=S28\u2013S41|doi=10.1080/14992027.2017.1407459|issn=1499-2027|pmid=29299940}}</ref> Another study evaluated two calibers of rifle and nine suppressors, .223 caliber [[AR-15 style rifle|AR-15]] (five suppressors) and .300 caliber AAC Blackout (four suppressors), and reported noise reduction of the peak sound level pressure between 7 dB and 32 dB.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lobarinas|first=Edward|last2=Scott|first2=Ryan|last3=Spankovich|first3=Christopher|last4=Prell|first4=Colleen G. Le|date=2016-02-12|title=Differential effects of suppressors on hazardous sound pressure levels generated by AR-15 rifles: Considerations for recreational shooters, law enforcement, and the military|journal=International Journal of Audiology|volume=55|issue=sup1|pages=S59\u2013S71|doi=10.3109/14992027.2015.1122241|issn=1499-2027|pmid=26821935}}</ref> The [[De Lisle carbine]], a British World War II suppressed rifle used in small numbers by Special Forces, was recorded at 85.5&nbsp;dB in official firing tests.<ref name=\"Rome\"/>\n\nComparatively, ear protection commonly used while shooting provides 18 to 32&nbsp;dB of sound reduction at the ear.<ref name=\"Hearing\"/> Further, chainsaws, rock concerts, rocket engines, pneumatic drills, small firecrackers, and ambulance sirens are rated at 100 to 140&nbsp;dB.<ref name=\"Murray\"/>\n\nWhile some consider the noise reduction of a suppressor significant enough to permit safe shooting without hearing protection (\"hearing safe\"), [[noise-induced hearing loss]] may occur at 85 time-weighted-average decibels or above if exposed for a prolonged period,<ref name=\"NIHL\"/> and suppressed gunshots regularly meter above 130&nbsp;dB. However, the U.S. [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration]] uses 140&nbsp;dB as the \"safety cutoff\" for [[impulse noise (audio)|impulsive noise]], which has led most U.S. manufacturers to advertise sub-140&nbsp;dB silencers as \"hearing safe\". Current OSHA standards would allow no more than sub-single-second exposure to impact noise over 130&nbsp;dB per 24 hours. That would equate to a single .308 round fired through a very efficient suppressor. This result effectively requires all users of silencers to wear additional ear protection.\n\nDecibel testing measures only the peak sound \"pressure\" noise, not duration or frequency. Limitations of dB testing become apparent in a comparison of sound between a [[.308 Winchester|.308 caliber]] rifle and a [[.300 Winchester Magnum]] rifle. The dB meter will show that both rifles produce the same decibel level of noise. Upon firing these rifles, however, it is clear that the .300 Winchester Magnum sounds much louder. What a dB meter does not show is that, although both rifles produce the same peak [[sound pressure level]] (SPL), the .300 Winchester Magnum holds its peak duration longer\u2014meaning that the .300 Winchester Magnum sound remains at full value longer, while the .308 peaks and falls off more quickly. Decibel meters fail in this and other regards when being used as the principal means to determine silencer capability. In a physical sense, dB meters essentially take a short-time average ([[Root mean square|RMS]] intensity of a sonic signal or impulse) over a specified period of time (sampling rate), and do not take into account the rate of increase of the sound wave packet (first derivative of packet envelope), which would in practice provide a better sense of the human [[Sound perception|perception of sound]].<ref name=\"AWC\"/>\n\nAlan C. Paulson, of [[Paladin Press]], writes that suppressors are considered a great help, along with hearing protection, to preserve the hearing of the user and any onlookers.<ref name=\"Paulson2\"/>\n\n==Regulation==\nLegal regulation of silencers varies widely around the world. In some nations, such as Finland, France, and New Zealand some or all types of suppressor are essentially unregulated and are sold through retail stores or by mail-order.<ref name=\"Dockery2007\"/> In other countries their possession or use is more restricted.\n\n===Europe===\n*In Norway, silencers are not regulated and can be purchased by anyone for any firearm. No licence or permit is necessary.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://lovdata.no/dokument/SF/forskrift/2009-06-25-904 |title = Forskrift om skytev\u00e5pen, v\u00e5pendeler og ammunisjon mv. (V\u00e5penforskriften) - Lovdata}}</ref>\n*In Denmark, the [[Danish Weapons And Explosives Law]] makes the unlicensed possession of a silencer illegal. {{asof|2014|05|07}} it is legal to own and use silencers for hunting.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.retsinformation.dk/Forms/R0710.aspx?id=162966 | title=Bekendtg\u00f8relse om v\u00e5ben og ammunition der m\u00e5 anvendes til jagt m.v. |work= retsinformation.dk |publisher=[[Milj\u00f8ministeriet]]|accessdate=2015-03-15|date= 2014-05-07|trans-title= Hunting weapons and ammunition act|language=Danish}}</ref>\n*In Finland, a firearm silencer is classified as a firearm part by law. Purchasing a suppressor requires a firearm ownership permit, which must be shown to the vendor at the moment of purchase.<ref name=\"Baum2013\"/>\n*Silencers for [[Rimfire (firearms)|rimfire]] pistols are sold without government oversight in France.<ref name=\"Dockery2007\"/>\n*Poland: In 2020 new amendment to Arms and Ammunition Act allowed police to issue permits for firearms with a sound suppressors for hunting permits. Hunters are allowed to use them only for sanitary shooting of animals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prezydent.pl/aktualnosci/wydarzenia/art,1658,dwie-ustawy-z-podpisem-prezydenta.html|title=Dwie ustawy z podpisem Prezydenta|date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n*In the Russian Federation, using firearm silencers (legally defined as \"devices for noiseless shooting\") by civilians is prohibited, and dealers are prohibited from selling them, but there is no penalty for purchasing or possession of such devices.<ref name=\"Carter2002\"/> \n*In Sweden, silencers for specified calibers are legal for hunting purposes; a license is required.<ref name=\"Paulson\"/>{{rp|9}}\n*In the UK, the owner's [[firearm certificate]] (FAC) will need to show permission for the purchase of a \"sound moderator\" and also the firearm for which it is intended. All firearms certificates have the firearm and caliber approved by the police and annotated to the document before a silencer may be purchased. Applicants must show a \"good reason\" for needing the accessory.<ref name=\"Durham\">{{cite web|title=Sound Moderators|url=https://www.durham.police.uk/Information-and-advice/firearms-and-firearms-licensing/Pages/Sound-Moderators.aspx|website=Durham Constabulary|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n*In Germany, a silencer is treated the same in the eyes of the law as the weapon it is designed for. Accordingly, suppressors for [[BB gun|air guns]], which can be purchased by anyone over 18 years of age, can as well be purchased by anyone over 18. Since, amongst other things, \"good cause\" must be shown to be issued a license to own a firearm in Germany, the same \"good cause\" requirement exists for suppressors for these firearms. This requirement is handled very varyingly across the States of Germany. The State of [[Bavaria]] accepts the possession of a valid hunter's license as \"good cause\" to own an unlimited number of suppressors, while [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] does not accept hunting as a \"good cause\" at all. [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] accepts \"active exercise of hunting\" as \"good cause\", but only allows the purchase of one silencer.<ref name=\"Suppressor use while Hunting in Germany\">{{cite web|title=Jagdrecht in Bayern|url=http://www.wildtierportal.bayern.de/jagd/094822/index.php|website=Bavarian Ministry of Agriculture|accessdate=20 January 2017|language=German |trans-title=Hunting Laws in Bavaria}}</ref>\n*In Italy, a silencer is considered a prohibited firearms accessory, allowed only to the armed forces, police and government agency.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n*In the Czech Republic, a silencer is considered a prohibited firearms accessory, and as such can only be obtained with an extremely uncommon exception for weapon collectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvcr.cz/clanek/zbrane-podlehajici-zakonu-o-zbranich-a-podminky-jejich-nabyvani-a-drzeni.aspx?q=Y2hudW09NA%3d%3d|title=Ministry of Interior of the Czech Republic|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=Czech|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\n[[File:Legality of firearm suppressors by US jurisdiction.svg|thumb|Legality of firearm silencers by US jurisdiction{{legend|#008000|Silencers legal to own and hunt with}}\n{{legend|#FFA500|Silencers legal but illegal to hunt with}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|Silencers illegal}}\n|250x250px]]\n*In Canada, a device to muffle or stop the sound of a firearm is a \"prohibited device\" under the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code]].<ref name=\"LOIS\"/> A prohibited device is not inherently illegal in Canada but it does require an uncommon and very specific prohibited device license for its possession, use, and transport. Silencers cannot be imported into the country by civilians.<ref name=\"CBSA\"/> ''See [[Gun politics in Canada]]''\n*In the United States, taxes and strict regulations affect the manufacture and sale of silencers under the [[National Firearms Act]]. They are legal for individuals to possess and use for lawful purposes in 42 of the 50 states. However, a prospective owner must go through an application process administered by the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]] (ATF), which requires a federal tax payment of $200 and a thorough criminal [[background check]]. The tax payment buys a [[revenue stamp]], which is the legal document allowing possession of a suppressor. The eight states that have explicitly banned any civilian from possessing a suppressor are: [[California]], [[Delaware]], [[Hawaii]], [[Illinois]], [[Massachusetts]], [[New Jersey]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Rhode Island]],<ref name=\"VSA\"/> and the [[District of Columbia]]. The states of [[Connecticut]] and [[Vermont]] allow suppressor ownership, but prohibit using silencers while hunting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americansuppressorassociation.com/education/|title=Education|website=americansuppressorassociation.com|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref> The federal legal requirements to manufacture a suppressor in the United States are enumerated in [[Internal Revenue Code|Title 26]], Chapter 53 of the [[United States Code]].<ref name=\"Cornell-53\"/> Individual states and several municipalities also have their specific requirements. Federal law provides severe penalties for crimes of violence committed using firearms equipped with silencers, with a minimum prison sentence of 30 years.<ref name=\"Cornell-924\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westerncriminology.org/documents/WCR/v08n2/clark.pdf |title=Criminal Use of Firearm Silencers |last=Clark |first=Paul A. |website= |publisher=Western Criminology Review |accessdate=15 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\n=== Oceania ===\n* In Australia, use and ownership of silencers is generally limited to government, security and law enforcement use only and thus prohibited for civilians. \n* In New Zealand, following firearm law changes in April 2019, suppressors could still be fitted to a standard firearm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.police.govt.nz/advice/firearms-and-safety/changes-firearms-law-prohibited-firearms/firearms-changes-faqs |title=Firearms changes FAQs |website=New Zealand Police|author= |date= 15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* Notable suppressed firearms: [[De Lisle carbine]], [[Welrod]], [[PBS-1 Suppressor]], [[MSP Groza silent pistol]], [[OTs-38 Stechkin silent revolver]], [[VSS Vintorez]], [[Sten submachine gun|STEN mk II]]\n* [[Title II weapons]]\n* {{Section link|Piston effect|Tunnel boom}}, for a similar device but far bigger, on ends of railway tunnels\n* [[Sound blimp]], a device to reduce the noise made by a camera's shutter\n\n=== Other muzzle devices ===\n* [[Muzzle brake]]\n* [[Flash suppressor]]\n* [[Muzzle booster]]\n* [[Muzzle shroud]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"assassin\">[http://www.assassinstradecraft.com/Silencers.html .22 and .45 as easy to suppress ammunition]</ref>\n<ref name=atf34>{{ cite web |url = http://www.atf.gov/firearms/faq/firearms-technology.html |title = Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives, Silencer FAQ |accessdate = 2011-03-22 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"AWC\">dB in Principle and Practice, AWC Systems Technology April 2010</ref>\n<ref name=\"Ayoob2011\">{{ cite book |last = Ayoob |first = Massad |authorlink = Massad Ayoob |title = Gun Digest Book of Beretta Pistols |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=AD5Kg35n9PkC&pg=PA223 |date = 28 February 2011 |publisher = Gun Digest Books |location = Iola, Wisconsin |isbn = 978-1-4402-2424-9 |page = 223 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Barrett\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.guns.connect.fi/rs/btxgraaf.html |title = Reflex Suppressor for Barrett M82A1 - BR Reflex Suppressors (Finland) |publisher = Guns.connect.fi |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Baum2013\">{{ cite book |last = Baum |first = Dan |title = Gun Guys: A Road Trip |url = https://archive.org/details/gunguysroadtrip0000baum |url-access = registration |year = 2013 |publisher = Knopf |isbn = 978-0-307-59541-6 |pages = [https://archive.org/details/gunguysroadtrip0000baum/page/45 45]\u201346 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Boorman2001\">{{ cite book |last = Boorman |first = Dean K. |title = The History of Winchester Firearms |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dZmlpZivhU8C&pg=PA74 |year = 2001 |publisher = Globe Pequot Press |isbn = 978-1-58574-307-0 |page = 74 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Bull2004\">{{ cite book |last = Bull |first = Stephen |title = Encyclopedia of Military Technology and Innovation |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HN3AUx_3Mn4C&pg=PA237 |date = 1 January 2004 |publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn = 978-1-57356-557-8 |page = 237 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Carter2002\">{{ cite book |last = Carter |first = Gregg Lee |title = Guns in American Society: An Encyclopedia of History, Politics, Culture, and the Law |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=H_RrLyV9rDUC&pg=PA752 |date = 1 January 2002 |publisher = ABC-CLIO |isbn = 978-1-57607-268-4 |page = 512 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CBSA\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.cbsa-asfc.gc.ca/publications/pub/bsf5044-eng.html |title = Importing a Firearm or Weapon Into Canada |publisher = [[Canada Border Services Agency]] |accessdate = 2008-06-11 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Cornell-53\">{{ cite web |url = https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/html/uscode26/usc_sup_01_26_10_E_20_53.html |title = Title 26, United States Code, Chapter 53 - Legal Information Institute, Cornell University Law School |publisher = Law.cornell.edu |date = 2008-09-24 |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Cornell-924\">{{ cite web |url = https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/924 |title = Title 18, United States Code, Section 924(c)(1)(B)(ii) - Legal Information Institute, Cornell University Law School |publisher = Law.cornell.edu |date = 2013-02-13 |accessdate = 2013-03-17 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Dater2007\">{{ cite book |last1 = Dater |first1 = Philip |last2 = Dockery |first2 = Kevin |title = Stalkers and Shooters: A History of Snipers |chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_2zqCm-QRHoC&pg=PA234 |date = July 2007 |publisher = BERKLEY Publishing Group |isbn = 978-0-425-21542-5 |pages = 228\u2013235 |chapter = 28 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Dockery2007\">{{ cite book |last = Dockery |first = Kevin |authorlink = Kevin Dockery (author) |title = Stalkers and Shooters: A History of Snipers |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nYWZFOKFQ2gC&pg=PT218 |accessdate = 8 August 2013 |year = 2007 |publisher = Penguin Group US |location = New York |isbn = 978-1-4406-2890-0 |pages = 218\u2013235 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Dougherty2012\">{{ cite book |last = Dougherty |first = Martin J. |title = SAS and Elite Forces Guide Sniper: Sniping Skills from the World's Elite Forces |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nXNBdeseO1AC&pg=PT43 |date = 2012 |publisher = Lyons Press |isbn = 978-0-7627-8876-7 |pages = 43\u201344 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Emptormaven\">{{ cite web |last = Emptormaven |title = Rethinking Direct Impingement |url = http://emptormaven.com/2013/08/rethinking-direct-impingement-with-the-noveske-300-blk-upper/ |accessdate = 4 March 2014 |date = 2013-08-26 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Explosives\">{{ cite book |author=United States, Tobacco Bureau of Alcohol, and Firearms, Firearms Programs Division, Tobacco Bureau of Alcohol, Firearms and Explosives |title = Federal Firearms Regulations Reference Guide |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9encMNU8mwsC&pg=PA176 |accessdate = 8 August 2013 |publisher = DIANE Publishing |isbn = 978-1-4289-5186-0 |page = 176 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Gage\">{{ cite book |last = Gage |title = Electrical Record and Buyer's Reference |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6382AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA53 |year = 1913 |publisher = Buyers' Reference Company |location = New York |page = 53 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Goddard2000\">{{ cite book |last = Goddard |first = Stephen B. |title = Colonel Albert Pope and His American Dream Machines: The Life and Times of a Bicycle Tycoon Turned Automotive Pioneer |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6RVbAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA227 |date = 11 November 2000 |publisher = McFarland |isbn = 978-1-4766-1334-5 |page = 227 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Greener2002\">{{ cite book |last = Greener |first = W. W. |title = The Gun and Its Development |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=obxNmpITIPkC&pg=PR9 |date = 1 October 2002 |publisher = Lyons Press |isbn = 978-1-58574-734-4 |page = 9 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Heard2011\">{{ cite book |author=Brian J. Heard |title = Handbook of Firearms and Ballistics: Examining and Interpreting Forensic Evidence |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qd8TkbuC_bAC&pg=PT32 |accessdate = 6 January 2012 |date = 17 August 2011 |publisher = John Wiley and Sons |isbn = 978-1-119-96477-3 |page = 32 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hearing\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.hearingreview.com/issues/articles/2007-03_06.asp |title = Firearms and Hearing Protection &#124; March 2007 &#124; The Hearing Industry Resource |publisher = Hearingreview.com |date = 2007-02-12 |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kessler1994\">{{ cite book |last = Kessler |first = Ronald |title = Inside the CIA |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=l_EvNUJHTSoC&pg=PA187 |year = 1994 |publisher = Simon and Schuster |location = New York |isbn = 978-0-671-73458-9 |page = 187 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"LOIS\">{{ cite web |url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-46/FullText.html#h-38 |title = Criminal Code of Canada, Part III Firearms and other Weapons |accessdate = 2012-11-20 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Lovell\">Stanley Lovell (1963), ''Of Spies and Stratagems'', Englewood Cliffs, NJ: Prentice-Hall. Lovell claimed that a weapon so quiet would be more efficient than any death ray.</ref>\n<ref name=\"Mann2014\">{{ cite book |last = Mann |first = Richard A. |title = Gun Digest Shooter's Guide to the AR-15 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MQw5AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA232 |date = 30 April 2014 |publisher = Krause Publications |location = Iola, Wisconsin |isbn = 978-1-4402-3847-5 |pages = 232\u2013233 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MarkWhite\">{{ cite web |last = White |first = Mark |url = http://guns.connect.fi/gow/highpow.html |title = The Use of Sound Suppressors on High-Powered Rifles |publisher = Small Arms Review Vol. 1 No 7-9 |year = 1998 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Murray\">{{ cite web |url = http://campus.murraystate.edu/tsm/tsm118/Ch2/Ch2_7/Ch2_7.htm |title = 2.7: Decibels |publisher = Campus.murraystate.edu |accessdate = 2009-03-09}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418035925/http://campus.murraystate.edu/tsm/tsm118/Ch2/Ch2_7/Ch2_7.htm |date=April 18, 2009 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"NIHL\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.hearinglossweb.com/Medical/Causes/nihl/nihlfs.htm |title = nihl |publisher = Hearinglossweb.com |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Paulson2\">{{ cite book |last1 = Kokalis |first1 = Peter G.|author2 = Paulson, Alan C, and Parker, N.R. |title = Silencer History and Performance, Vol 2: CQB, Assault Rifle, and Sniper Technology |year = 2002 |publisher = Paladin Press |isbn = 1581603231 |page=49}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Paulson\">''Silencer: History and Performance, Volume 1'' by Alan C. Paulson</ref>\n<ref name=\"results\">{{ cite web |url = http://silencertalk.com/results.htm |title = Results |first = Robert |last = Silvers |publisher = |year = 2005 |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Rome\">{{ cite journal |last = Rome |first = Robert |date = June 1984 |title = WWII Silent Killer Still Lives |journal=Gung Ho |volume= |issue= |pages = 29 |doi= |url = http://www.valkyriearms.com/images/delisle.pdf |accessdate = }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"sniper\">{{ cite web |url = http://world.guns.ru/sniper/sn00-e.htm |title = Modern sniper rifles |publisher = world.guns.ru |date = 2001-01-26 |accessdate = 2009-03-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Sparrow\">{{cite web|url=http://www.silencerco.com/?section=Products&page=Sparrow|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110108045602/http://www.silencerco.com/?section=Products&page=Sparrow|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-01-08|title=Suppressors - Silencers - SilencerCo|work=SilencerCo}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Supersonic\">{{cite web|url=http://guns.connect.fi/gow/highpow.html|title=Sound Suppressors on High-Powered Rifles|work=connect.fi}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Tilstra2014\">{{ cite book |last = Tilstra |first = Russell C. |title = The Battle Rifle: Development and Use Since World War II |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_a0zAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA165 |date = 21 March 2014 |publisher = McFarland |isbn = 978-1-4766-1564-6 |page = 165 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"USPTO-958935\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.google.com/patents?id=dWJ-AAAAEBAJ&pg=PA1&source=gbs_selected_pages&cad=2#v=onepage&q&f=false |title = US Patent 958935 - Google Patents }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"VSA\">{{ cite web |url = http://www.leg.state.vt.us/statutes/fullsection.cfm?title=13&chapter=085&Section=04010 |title = 13 V.S.A. \u00a7 4010. Gun silencers |accessdate = March 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Walker\">{{ cite book |last = Walker |first = Robert E. |title = Cartridges and Firearm Identification |publisher = CRC Press |location = Fort Myers, Florida |isbn = 978-1-4665-8881-3 |pages = 210\u2013214, 295 |date = 2013-03-21 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"WebbDoherty2010\">{{ cite book |last1 = Webb |first1 = Brandon |last2 = Doherty |first2 = Glen |title = 21st Century Sniper: The Complete Guide |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ClPffwtcYGMC&pg=PT71 |date = 15 September 2010 |publisher = Skyhorse Publishing Inc. |isbn = 978-1-61608-001-3 |pages = 71\u201372 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hollywood\">Examples of blaming Hollywood exaggeration of silencer effectiveness:\n*{{Citation |last=Sweeney |first=Patrick |title=Ruger silent-SR: One of the great names in firearms takes the plunge into a once-taboo market |magazine=[[Firearms News]] |date=February 10, 2017 |pages=32+ |publisher=[[Outdoor Sportsman Group]] {{subscription required|via=[[General OneFile]] }} |quote= With subsonic ammunition, the Silent-SR provided the Hollywood 'phuut-phuut' noise that all movie suppressors are supposed to deliver }}\n*{{Citation |postscript= [Joshua Waldron, co-founder of SilencerCo] \"So I see a big part of my job as educating the public about silencers and trying to undo so much of that stupid Hollywood idea about silencers being an assassin's tool. |last=McCombie |first=Brian |title= Joshua Waldron: how two guys in a rock band redesigned silencers and became the biggest suppressor maker in the nation |magazine=[[Gun Digest]] |date=August 28, 2014 |pages=48+ |publisher=Gun Digest Books {{subscription required|via=[[General OneFile]] }} }}\n*{{Citation |quote=Despite their Hollywood image, suppressors are not 'silencers.' They won't completely muffle rifle or handgun noise, and they won't stop the sonic crack of a bullet that comes from traveling beyond the speed of sound. |last= McCombie |first=Brian |title= Hush-up: how sound suppressors work and why you should own one |magazine=[[Outdoor Life]] |date=June\u2013July 2012 |page=82 |publisher=[[Bonnier Corporation]] {{subscription required|via=[[General OneFile]] }}  }}\n*{{Citation |quote=In the real world, 'silencers' are actually 'suppressors,' and they don't eliminate the sound of a gunshot so much as slightly reduce it-- |title=Hollywood has a lot to answer for. |magazine=[[National Review]] |date=February 6, 2017 |page= 10 |publisher=E. Garrett Bewkes IV {{subscription required|via=[[General OneFile]] }} }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Firearm silencers}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n*{{hsw|question112|How does a gun silencer work?||people}}\n\n[[Category:Firearm muzzle devices]]\n[[Category:Noise reduction]]\n[[Category:American inventions]]\n", "name_user": "OrangeBanana11", "label": "safe", "comment": "I changed some words so it made more sense", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silencer_(firearms)"}
{"title_page": "College of Natural Resources (Bhutan)", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name                     = College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/about-us|title=About CNR|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rub.edu.bt/index.php/en/teaching-learning/colleges/constituent-colleges/95-college-of-natural-resources|title=College of Natural Resources|first=Super|last=User|website=www.rub.edu.bt}}</ref>\n|native_name              = CNR RUB\n|image_name               = College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan.jpeg\n|image                    = \n|image_size               = 300 pixels\n|caption                  = \n|latin_name               = \n|motto                    = 'Higher learning infused with GNH values'\n|established              = 1992 as Natural Resources Training Institute (NRTI) and renamed as the College of Natural Resources in 2003\n|staff                    = 44\n|faculty                  = 59\n|type                     = University College\n|president                = Dr. Phub Dorji<ref>{{cite web |title=Management staff |url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/about-us/staff-directory/management-staff |website=www.cnr.edu.bt |accessdate=26 September 2019 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n|principal                = \n|dean = Dr. Tulsi Gurung (Academic Affairs)<br/> Dr. Om Katel (Research and Industrial Linkages)<br/>\nDr. Penjor (Student Affairs)\n|students                = 972 as of September 30, 2019\n|bachelors               = \n|postgrad                = \n|city                    = Punakha, Dzongkhag\n|state                   = \n|country                 = [[Bhutan]]\n|campus                  = \n|former_names            = Natural Resources Training Institute (NRTI)\n|colors                  = \n|colours                 = \n|footnotes               = \n|website                 = {{url|http://www.cnr.edu.bt}}\n|address                 = Lobesa, Punakha, East West highway\n|logo                    = \n}}\n\nThe '''College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan<ref>https://www.bhutanstudies.org.bt/publicationFiles/ConferenceProceedings/RethinkingDevelopment/15.Re-thinkingdev.pdf</ref>''' ('''CNR RUB''')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sfJ8AzQFfdE|title=College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.bt/biodiv/content/documents/document-7b11a336-6a28-43de-a933-bbd888db62b4/397.pdf |title=New records of snakes and lizards from Bhutan |last=Wangyal |first=Jigme |date=2010 |website=biodiversity.bt |access-date=2019-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271518682 |title=Improving the Research Output of Academics at the Royal University of Bhutan: A Reconnaissance and early initiatives |publisher=Researchgate.net |date= |accessdate=2019-09-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Managing Water Resources under Climate Uncertainty|editor-first1=Sangam|editor-last1=Shrestha|editor-first2=Anil K.|editor-last2=Anal|editor-first3=P. Abdul|editor-last3=Salam|editor-first4=Michael|editor-last4=van der Valk|date=September 23, 2015|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-10467-6|isbn = 978-3-319-10466-9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://repository.kulib.kyoto-u.ac.jp/dspace/handle/2433/200304|title=Transition of Agriculture towards Organic Farming in Bhutan|volume=16|first1=Katsue|last1=Fukamachi|first2=Rekha|last2=Chhetri|first3=Mai|last3=Kobayashi|date=March 28, 2015|via=repository.kulib.kyoto-u.ac.jp|doi=10.14989/HSM.16.66}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.bt/group/college_of_natural_resources/userGroup/show|title=College of Natural Resources|website=College of Natural Resources - Bhutan Biodiversity Portal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indembthimphu.gov.in/pages.php?id=410|title=Welcome to Embassy of India Thimphu, Bhutan|website=www.indembthimphu.gov.in}}</ref> is a college offering courses on natural resources management, that include agriculture, animal science, environment and climate, food science and technology, forest science, organic agriculture and sustainable development.<ref name=cnr>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |title=College of Natural Resources |accessdate=2019-09-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The college is located in Lobesa, [[Punakha District]], in central west [[Bhutan]]. The college campus is spread over {{cvt|98|acre}} on the eastern slope of Lobesa and is about {{cvt|140|km}} away from the [[Paro Airport|Paro International Airport]].\n[[File:College of Natural Resources, RUB.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==History==\nFounded in 1992 as '''Natural Resources Training Institute''' ('''NRTI''')<ref name=\"rcbajo.gov.bt\">http://rcbajo.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IRRI_Bhutan_2001-Joyce-report.pdf</ref> by the Ministry of Agriculture and Forests to train extension agents. The training was based on the Bhutanese farming systems. Crops, livestock and forests are the integral parts of the rural livelihood system in Bhutan. The main reason to establish the NRTI was that the then-National Agriculture Training Institute located at Paro, the Royal Veterinary Institute at Serbithang and the Bhutan Forestry Institute at Taba was brought under one umbrella named as the Natural Resources Training Institute (NRTI) at Lobesa with funding support from Swiss Development Corporation (SDC), Helvetas and the Royal Government of Bhutan.\n\nCollege of Natural Resources,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unipage.net/en/universities?country_id%5B0%5D=34&per-page=5|title=University Rankings 2019 &#124; Top institutes abroad &#124; Best colleges overseas|website=www.unipage.net}}</ref> Royal University of Bhutan, was born as the Natural Resources Training Institute (NRTI)<ref name=\"rcbajo.gov.bt\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbc.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/Biodiversity-Action-Plan-1997.pdf |title=BIODIVERSITY ACTION PLAN FOR BHUTAN |website=nbc.gov.bt|date=December 1997 |accessdate=2019-09-26}}</ref> in 1992 under the Ministry of Agriculture. The NRTI<ref>http://www.nssc.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/pub7eb6382ru.pdf</ref> joined the [[Royal University of Bhutan]] (RUB)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rub.edu.bt/index.php/en/|title=Home|website=www.rub.edu.bt}}</ref> in 2003 as a founding member college, and was named thereafter as the College of Natural Resources (CNR). As NRTI,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acauthorities.org/sites/aca/files/countrydoc/Bhutan%20National%20Action%20Program%20to%20Combat%20Land%20Degradation.pdf |title=National Action Program to Combat Land Degradation |date= |accessdate=2019-09-23}}</ref> the institute awarded Diploma courses in the field of Agriculture, Animal Husbandry, and Forestry for the mid-level extension workers of the Ministry of Agriculture until 2002. As a College of Natural Resources, CNR continued to offer Diploma courses as nested programmes in its Bachelor programmes. Since 2010, the college started to provide Bachelor programmes in the field of [[Agriculture]], [[Animal Science]], and [[Forest Science]]. By 2012 the college started to offer Bachelor of Science in Sustainable Development and in 2015, Bachelor of Science programme in Environment and Climate Science was introduced. The college has also started to offer post graduate programme such as Master in Development Practices in 2015, which is a global multidisciplinary programme. Similarly, Master of Science in Natural Resources Management by research was introduced in the year 2015. Further, a Bachelor of science programmes namely BSc in Food Science and Technology was introduced in the year 2017 and BSc in Organic Agriculture was 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Visiting scholars from the Palacky University Olomouc, Czech Republic (Europe)|website=www.cnr.edu.bt|access-date=2014-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=2011-07-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> The college is gearing to launch PhD program on Climate Studies by 2020 and, similarly, a Masters program on water resources management and conservation science is also planned.\n[[File:P1040109-min.jpg|thumb|Student Accommodation, College of Natural Resources]]\n\n==Accreditation==\nIn 2016, the College was accredited by the Bhutan Accreditation Council (BAC), and awarded it the grade of A.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kuenselonline.com/bac-accredits-three-colleges/|title=BAC accredits three colleges}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe college of Natural Resources is located in Lobesa [[Punakha District]], [[Bhutan]], in central west [[Bhutan]]. The college campus is spread over {{cvt|98|acre}} on the eastern slope of Lobesa and is about {{cvt|140|km}} away from the [[Paro Airport|Paro]] international airport. Besides laboratories and academic buildings, the main campus includes housing, and sports a conference center, and a library with over 100,000 volumes of books and other periodicals.\n[[File:College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan-min.jpg|thumb|College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan]]\n\n==Structure==\nCNR RUB comprises<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rub.edu.bt/index.php/en/teaching-learning/colleges/109-constituent-colleges/95-college-of-natural-resources|title=College of Natural Resources|first=Super|last=User|website=www.rub.edu.bt}}</ref> of six departments and eleven programs:\n*Department of Agriculture<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Agriculture)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Animal Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Animal Science)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Environment and Climate Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Environment and Climate Science)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Food Science and Technology<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Food Science and Technology)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Forest Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Forest Science)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Sustainable Development<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Sustainable Development)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Academic programs==\nThe College of Natural Resources offers Master's, Bachelor's, Diploma and Certificate courses.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Among the programs<ref>programs offered at CNR RUB http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/</ref> offered include regular Master of Science in Developmental Practice,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mdpglobal.org/global-mdp-association/partner-mdp-institutions/royal-university-of-bhutan/|title=Royal University of Bhutan - GlobalMDP}}</ref> Master of Science in Natural Resources Management by Research, Bachelor of Science in Agriculture,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/agriculture|title=Agriculture|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref> Bachelor of Science in Animal Science,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/animal-science|title=Animal Science|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref> Bachelor of Science in Environment and Climate Science,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/climate-studies|title=Environment & Climate Studies|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref> Bachelor of Science Food Science and Technology,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/food-science|title=Food Science & Technology|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref> Bachelor of Science in Forest Science,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/forestry|title=Forestry|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref> Bachelor of Science in Organic Agriculture,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php|title=Visiting scholars from the Palacky University Olomouc, Czech Republic (Europe)}}</ref> and Bachelor of Science in Sustainable Development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/sustainable-development|title=Sustainable Development|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref>\n\n==Collaboration==\nThe College has several collaboration such as: Bremen University, Germany, (Erasmus+ - SUNRAISE project),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunraise.sfu-kras.ru/results/management|title=SUNRAISE management and Quality Assurance &#124; SUNRAISE|website=sunraise.sfu-kras.ru}}</ref> G\u00f6ttingen University, Germany (Erasmus+), Palacky University, Czech Rep (Erasmus+), Pardova University, Italy (Erasmus+), Khonkaen University, Thailand (TICA),<ref>http://www.tica.thaigov.net/main/contents/ebook/ebook-20130607-164007/files/assets/basic-html/page12.html</ref> Nagoya University, Japan (JSPS), Norwegian University of Biological Science, Norway (NORHED),<ref>https://www.nmbu.no/download/file/fid/32406</ref> Research Institute of Humanity and Nature, Kyoto, Japan (FEAST),<ref>http://www.chikyu.ac.jp/rihn_e/project/2016-01.html</ref> Bangladesh Academy of Rural Development,<ref>http://www.rub.edu.bt/images/rub/Key-Documents/Annual-Reports/annual_report_2016.pdf</ref> Bangladesh, International Centre for Integrated Mountain Development (ICIMOD), Kathmandu, Nepal (TROSA),<ref>https://www.huc-hkh.org/news/detail/trosa-huc-water-research-grants-2018-2019-were-selected</ref> The Naturalis in Leiden, The Netherlands on Biodiversity and Nature<ref>http://www.moaf.gov.bt/pollination-workshop-underway-at-college-of-natural-resources/</ref><ref>https://www.naturalis.nl/en</ref> and Wageningen Centre for Development Innovation among others (CDI).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wur.nl/en/project/Enhancing-the-capacity-of-CNR-staff.htm|title=Enhancing the capacity of CNR staff|first=Contact drs NGRozemeijer Contact form + Show|last=more|date=November 5, 2015|website=WUR}}</ref>\nIn addition to the collaboration with international the college has active collaboration with national agencies, NGOs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://himalayanstudies.edu.bt/bhutan-institute-of-himalayan-studies-bihs-signed-memorandum-of-understanding-with-college-of-natural-resources/|title=Bhutan Institute of Himalayan Studies (BIHS) signed Memorandum of Understanding with College of Natural Resources &#124; Bhutan Institute of Himalayan Studies|first=Phunstho|last=Namgay}}</ref> and various civil society organizations.\n\n==Research and research centers==\nThe college has its own online journal for publication called '''Bhutan Journal of Natural Resources and Development''' (BJNRD).<ref>http://www.bjnrd.org/</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isbsbhutan.org/bhutan-and-international-links/|title=BHUTAN AND INTERNATIONAL LINKS &#124; International Society for Bhutan Studies}}</ref> The BJNRD publishes quality research articles both online and print.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnrd.org/index.php?bjnrd=8&page=1|title=BJNRD &#124; Bhutan Journal of Natural Resources and Development|website=www.bjnrd.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Visiting scholars from the Palacky University Olomouc, Czech Republic (Europe)|website=www.cnr.edu.bt|access-date=2014-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=2011-07-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBesides offering academic programmes, the college has research centres namely; \n*Centre for Environment and Climate Research (CECR),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |title=Centre for Environment and Climate Research |date= |accessdate=2019-09-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n*Centre for Rural Development Studies (CRDS),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |title=Centre for Rural Development Studies |date= |accessdate=2019-09-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and\n*Centre for Sustainable Mountain Agriculture (CSMA).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |title=Centre for Sustainable Mountain Agriculture |date= |accessdate=2019-09-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe college also provides professional education, short-course training, and consultancy services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Research Centres|publisher=|accessdate=2019-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=2011-07-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Directors and presidents ==\nThe present incumbent President, Dr. Phub Dorji assumed office on 1 September 2016<ref>http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/about-us|publisher=|accessdate= 23 September 2019}}</ref> succeeding Director General, Mr. Dorji Wangchuk. Dr. Phub Dorji is the fourth Director (renamed as President) in the history of the college. Until Phub Dorji assumed office, the position title was the Director or Director General based on the seniority; however, in 2015, the Royal University of Bhutan, changed the position structure, and renamed as the President. The college's first Director was Dasho<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kuenselonline.com/what-is-in-a-name-3/|title=What is in a Name?}}</ref> Sherab Tenzin (1992 to 1996, and in 1997 succeeded by Director, Mr. Jambay Dorji until 1999. By 2000, Mr. Dorji Wangchuk became the third director of the college until 2015. Wangchuk was promoted to director general in 2014. In 2016, Dr. Phub Dorji became the fourth director or the first President of the college.\n[[File:P1040092-min.jpg|thumb|CNR Village, College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ College of Natural Resources website]\n\n[[Category:Universities in Bhutan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1992]]\n[[Category:1992 in Bhutan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name                     = College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/about-us|title=About CNR|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rub.edu.bt/index.php/en/teaching-learning/colleges/constituent-colleges/95-college-of-natural-resources|title=College of Natural Resources|first=Super|last=User|website=www.rub.edu.bt}}</ref>\n|native_name              = CNR RUB\n|image_name               = College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan.jpeg\n|image                    = \n|image_size               = 300 pixels\n|caption                  = \n|latin_name               = \n|motto                    = 'Higher learning infused with GNH values'\n|established              = 1992 as Natural Resources Training Institute (NRTI) and renamed as the College of Natural Resources in 2003\n|staff                    = 44\n|faculty                  = 59\n|type                     = University College\n|president                = Dr. Phub Dorji<ref>{{cite web |title=Management staff |url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/about-us/staff-directory/management-staff |website=www.cnr.edu.bt |accessdate=26 September 2019 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n|principal                = \n|dean = Dr. Tulsi Gurung (Academic Affairs)<br/> Dr. Om Katel (Research and Industrial Linkages)<br/>\nDr. Penjor (Student Affairs)\n|students                = 972 as of September 30, 2019\n|bachelors               = \n|postgrad                = \n|city                    = Punakha, Dzongkhag\n|state                   = \n|country                 = [[Bhutan]]\n|campus                  = \n|former_names            = Natural Resources Training Institute (NRTI)\n|colors                  = \n|colours                 = \n|footnotes               = \n|website                 = {{url|http://www.cnr.edu.bt}}\n|address                 = Lobesa, Punakha, East West highway\n|logo                    = \n}}\n\nThe '''College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan<ref>https://www.bhutanstudies.org.bt/publicationFiles/ConferenceProceedings/RethinkingDevelopment/15.Re-thinkingdev.pdf</ref>''' ('''CNR RUB''')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sfJ8AzQFfdE|title=College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.bt/biodiv/content/documents/document-7b11a336-6a28-43de-a933-bbd888db62b4/397.pdf |title=New records of snakes and lizards from Bhutan |last=Wangyal |first=Jigme |date=2010 |website=biodiversity.bt |access-date=2019-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271518682 |title=Improving the Research Output of Academics at the Royal University of Bhutan: A Reconnaissance and early initiatives |publisher=Researchgate.net |date= |accessdate=2019-09-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Managing Water Resources under Climate Uncertainty|editor-first1=Sangam|editor-last1=Shrestha|editor-first2=Anil K.|editor-last2=Anal|editor-first3=P. Abdul|editor-last3=Salam|editor-first4=Michael|editor-last4=van der Valk|date=September 23, 2015|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-10467-6|isbn = 978-3-319-10466-9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://repository.kulib.kyoto-u.ac.jp/dspace/handle/2433/200304|title=Transition of Agriculture towards Organic Farming in Bhutan|volume=16|first1=Katsue|last1=Fukamachi|first2=Rekha|last2=Chhetri|first3=Mai|last3=Kobayashi|date=March 28, 2015|via=repository.kulib.kyoto-u.ac.jp|doi=10.14989/HSM.16.66}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.bt/group/college_of_natural_resources/userGroup/show|title=College of Natural Resources|website=College of Natural Resources - Bhutan Biodiversity Portal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indembthimphu.gov.in/pages.php?id=410|title=Welcome to Embassy of India Thimphu, Bhutan|website=www.indembthimphu.gov.in}}</ref> is a college offering courses on natural resources management, that include agriculture, animal science, environment and climate, food science and technology, forest science, organic agriculture and sustainable development.<ref name=cnr>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |title=College of Natural Resources |accessdate=2019-09-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The college is located in Lobesa, [[Punakha District]], in central west [[Bhutan]]. The college campus is spread over {{cvt|98|acre}} on the eastern slope of Lobesa and is about {{cvt|140|km}} away from the [[Paro Airport|Paro International Airport]].\n[[File:College of Natural Resources, RUB.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==History==\nFounded in 1992 as '''Natural Resources Training Institute''' ('''NRTI''')<ref name=\"rcbajo.gov.bt\">http://rcbajo.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IRRI_Bhutan_2001-Joyce-report.pdf</ref> by the Ministry of Agriculture and Forests to train extension agents. The training was based on the Bhutanese farming systems. Crops, livestock and forests are the integral parts of the rural livelihood system in Bhutan. The main reason to establish the NRTI was that the then-National Agriculture Training Institute located at Paro, the Royal Veterinary Institute at Serbithang and the Bhutan Forestry Institute at Taba was brought under one umbrella named as the Natural Resources Training Institute (NRTI) at Lobesa with funding support from Swiss Development Corporation (SDC), Helvetas and the Royal Government of Bhutan.\n\nCollege of Natural Resources,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unipage.net/en/universities?country_id%5B0%5D=34&per-page=5|title=University Rankings 2019 &#124; Top institutes abroad &#124; Best colleges overseas|website=www.unipage.net}}</ref> Royal University of Bhutan, was born as the Natural Resources Training Institute (NRTI)<ref name=\"rcbajo.gov.bt\"/><ref>http://nbc.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/Biodiversity-Action-Plan-1997.pdf|date= |accessdate=2019-09-26}}</ref> in 1992 under the Ministry of Agriculture. The NRTI<ref>http://www.nssc.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/pub7eb6382ru.pdf</ref> joined the [[Royal University of Bhutan]] (RUB)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rub.edu.bt/index.php/en/|title=Home|website=www.rub.edu.bt}}</ref> in 2003 as a founding member college, and was named thereafter as the College of Natural Resources (CNR). As NRTI,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acauthorities.org/sites/aca/files/countrydoc/Bhutan%20National%20Action%20Program%20to%20Combat%20Land%20Degradation.pdf |title=National Action Program to Combat Land Degradation |date= |accessdate=2019-09-23}}</ref> the institute awarded Diploma courses in the field of Agriculture, Animal Husbandry, and Forestry for the mid-level extension workers of the Ministry of Agriculture until 2002. As a College of Natural Resources, CNR continued to offer Diploma courses as nested programmes in its Bachelor programmes. Since 2010, the college started to provide Bachelor programmes in the field of [[Agriculture]], [[Animal Science]], and [[Forest Science]]. By 2012 the college started to offer Bachelor of Science in Sustainable Development and in 2015, Bachelor of Science programme in Environment and Climate Science was introduced. The college has also started to offer post graduate programme such as Master in Development Practices in 2015, which is a global multidisciplinary programme. Similarly, Master of Science in Natural Resources Management by research was introduced in the year 2015. Further, a Bachelor of science programmes namely BSc in Food Science and Technology was introduced in the year 2017 and BSc in Organic Agriculture was 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Visiting scholars from the Palacky University Olomouc, Czech Republic (Europe)|website=www.cnr.edu.bt|access-date=2014-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=2011-07-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> The college is gearing to launch PhD program on Climate Studies by 2020 and, similarly, a Masters program on water resources management and conservation science is also planned.\n[[File:P1040109-min.jpg|thumb|Student Accommodation, College of Natural Resources]]\n\n==Accreditation==\nIn 2016, the College was accredited by the Bhutan Accreditation Council (BAC), and awarded it the grade of A.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kuenselonline.com/bac-accredits-three-colleges/|title=BAC accredits three colleges}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe college of Natural Resources is located in Lobesa [[Punakha District]], [[Bhutan]], in central west [[Bhutan]]. The college campus is spread over {{cvt|98|acre}} on the eastern slope of Lobesa and is about {{cvt|140|km}} away from the [[Paro Airport|Paro]] international airport. Besides laboratories and academic buildings, the main campus includes housing, and sports a conference center, and a library with over 100,000 volumes of books and other periodicals.\n[[File:College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan-min.jpg|thumb|College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan]]\n\n==Structure==\nCNR RUB comprises<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rub.edu.bt/index.php/en/teaching-learning/colleges/109-constituent-colleges/95-college-of-natural-resources|title=College of Natural Resources|first=Super|last=User|website=www.rub.edu.bt}}</ref> of six departments and eleven programs:\n*Department of Agriculture<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Agriculture)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Animal Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Animal Science)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Environment and Climate Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Environment and Climate Science)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Food Science and Technology<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Food Science and Technology)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Forest Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Forest Science)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Sustainable Development<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Department of Sustainable Development)|publisher=|accessdate=23 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Academic programs==\nThe College of Natural Resources offers Master's, Bachelor's, Diploma and Certificate courses.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Among the programs<ref>programs offered at CNR RUB http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/</ref> offered include regular Master of Science in Developmental Practice,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mdpglobal.org/global-mdp-association/partner-mdp-institutions/royal-university-of-bhutan/|title=Royal University of Bhutan - GlobalMDP}}</ref> Master of Science in Natural Resources Management by Research, Bachelor of Science in Agriculture,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/agriculture|title=Agriculture|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref> Bachelor of Science in Animal Science,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/animal-science|title=Animal Science|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref> Bachelor of Science in Environment and Climate Science,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/climate-studies|title=Environment & Climate Studies|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref> Bachelor of Science Food Science and Technology,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/food-science|title=Food Science & Technology|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref> Bachelor of Science in Forest Science,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/forestry|title=Forestry|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref> Bachelor of Science in Organic Agriculture,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php|title=Visiting scholars from the Palacky University Olomouc, Czech Republic (Europe)}}</ref> and Bachelor of Science in Sustainable Development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/academic-programme/undergraduate-programs/sustainable-development|title=Sustainable Development|website=www.cnr.edu.bt}}</ref>\n\n==Collaboration==\nThe College has several collaboration such as: Bremen University, Germany, (Erasmus+ - SUNRAISE project),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunraise.sfu-kras.ru/results/management|title=SUNRAISE management and Quality Assurance &#124; SUNRAISE|website=sunraise.sfu-kras.ru}}</ref> G\u00f6ttingen University, Germany (Erasmus+), Palacky University, Czech Rep (Erasmus+), Pardova University, Italy (Erasmus+), Khonkaen University, Thailand (TICA),<ref>http://www.tica.thaigov.net/main/contents/ebook/ebook-20130607-164007/files/assets/basic-html/page12.html</ref> Nagoya University, Japan (JSPS), Norwegian University of Biological Science, Norway (NORHED),<ref>https://www.nmbu.no/download/file/fid/32406</ref> Research Institute of Humanity and Nature, Kyoto, Japan (FEAST),<ref>http://www.chikyu.ac.jp/rihn_e/project/2016-01.html</ref> Bangladesh Academy of Rural Development,<ref>http://www.rub.edu.bt/images/rub/Key-Documents/Annual-Reports/annual_report_2016.pdf</ref> Bangladesh, International Centre for Integrated Mountain Development (ICIMOD), Kathmandu, Nepal (TROSA),<ref>https://www.huc-hkh.org/news/detail/trosa-huc-water-research-grants-2018-2019-were-selected</ref> The Naturalis in Leiden, The Netherlands on Biodiversity and Nature<ref>http://www.moaf.gov.bt/pollination-workshop-underway-at-college-of-natural-resources/</ref><ref>https://www.naturalis.nl/en</ref> and Wageningen Centre for Development Innovation among others (CDI)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wur.nl/en/project/Enhancing-the-capacity-of-CNR-staff.htm|title=Enhancing the capacity of CNR staff|first=Contact drs NGRozemeijer Contact form + Show|last=more|date=November 5, 2015|website=WUR}}</ref>.\nIn addition to the collaboration with international the college has active collaboration with national agencies, NGOs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://himalayanstudies.edu.bt/bhutan-institute-of-himalayan-studies-bihs-signed-memorandum-of-understanding-with-college-of-natural-resources/|title=Bhutan Institute of Himalayan Studies (BIHS) signed Memorandum of Understanding with College of Natural Resources &#124; Bhutan Institute of Himalayan Studies|first=Phunstho|last=Namgay}}</ref> and various civil society organizations.\n\n==Research and research centers==\nThe college has its own online journal for publication called '''Bhutan Journal of Natural Resources and Development''' (BJNRD).<ref>http://www.bjnrd.org/</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isbsbhutan.org/bhutan-and-international-links/|title=BHUTAN AND INTERNATIONAL LINKS &#124; International Society for Bhutan Studies}}</ref> The BJNRD publishes quality research articles both online and print.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnrd.org/index.php?bjnrd=8&page=1|title=BJNRD &#124; Bhutan Journal of Natural Resources and Development|website=www.bjnrd.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Visiting scholars from the Palacky University Olomouc, Czech Republic (Europe)|website=www.cnr.edu.bt|access-date=2014-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=2011-07-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBesides offering academic programmes, the college has research centres namely; \n*Centre for Environment and Climate Research (CECR),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |title=Centre for Environment and Climate Research |date= |accessdate=2019-09-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n*Centre for Rural Development Studies (CRDS),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |title=Centre for Rural Development Studies |date= |accessdate=2019-09-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and\n*Centre for Sustainable Mountain Agriculture (CSMA).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |title=Centre for Sustainable Mountain Agriculture |date= |accessdate=2019-09-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe college also provides professional education, short-course training, and consultancy services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|title=Research Centres|publisher=|accessdate=2019-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/|archive-date=2011-07-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Directors and presidents ==\nThe present incumbent President, Dr. Phub Dorji assumed office on 1 September 2016<ref>http://www.cnr.edu.bt/index.php/about-us|publisher=|accessdate= 23 September 2019}}</ref> succeeding Director General, Mr. Dorji Wangchuk. Dr. Phub Dorji is the fourth Director (renamed as President) in the history of the college. Until Phub Dorji assumed office, the position title was the Director or Director General based on the seniority; however, in 2015, the Royal University of Bhutan, changed the position structure, and renamed as the President. The college's first Director was Dasho<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kuenselonline.com/what-is-in-a-name-3/|title=What is in a Name?}}</ref> Sherab Tenzin (1992 to 1996, and in 1997 succeeded by Director, Mr. Jambay Dorji until 1999. By 2000, Mr. Dorji Wangchuk became the third director of the college until 2015. Wangchuk was promoted to director general in 2014. In 2016, Dr. Phub Dorji became the fourth director or the first President of the college.\n[[File:P1040092-min.jpg|thumb|CNR Village, College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162641/http://www.cnr.edu.bt/ College of Natural Resources website]\n\n[[Category:Universities in Bhutan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1992]]\n[[Category:1992 in Bhutan]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "template fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/College_of_Natural_Resources_(Bhutan)"}
{"title_page": "Percy Fawcett", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n| name               = Percy Harrison Fawcett\n| honorific_suffix   = {{Post-nominals|GBR|DSO|size=100}}\n| image              = PercyFawcett.jpg\n| caption            = Fawcett in 1911\n| birth_name         = Percy Harrison Fawcett\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1867|8|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Torquay]], [[Devon]], United Kingdom\n| disappeared_date   = {{Disappeared date and age|df=yes|1925|5|29|1867|8|18}}\n| disappeared_place  = [[Mato Grosso]], Brazil\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Nina Agnes Paterson|January 1901}}\n| children           = 3\n| occupation         = Artillery officer, archaeologist, geologist, explorer\n| module             = {{Infobox military person | embed=yes\n| allegiance = United Kingdom\n| branch = British Army\n| serviceyears = 1886\u20131910<br/>{{Circa}}1914\u20131919\n| rank = [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant Colonel]]\n| unit = [[Royal Artillery]]\n| commands =\n| battles = [[World War I]]\n| awards = [[Distinguished Service Order]]<br/>3 \u00d7 [[Mentioned in despatches]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Percy Harrison Fawcett''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|DSO}} (18 August 1867{{spaced ndash}}[[Declared death in absentia|during or after]] 1925) was a British [[geography|geographer]], [[Royal Artillery|artillery officer]], [[cartography|cartographer]], [[archaeology|archaeologist]], and [[exploration|explorer]] of South America. Fawcett disappeared in 1925 (along with his eldest son, Jack, and one of Jack's friends, Raleigh Rimell) during an expedition to find \"[[Lost City of Z|Z]]\"\u2014his name for an ancient [[lost city]] which he and others believed existed in the [[Amazon rainforest|jungles of Brazil]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Heckenberger |first=Michael J. |date=2009 |title=Lost Cities of the Amazon |journal=[[Scientific American]] |volume=301 |issue=4 |pages=64\u201371|doi=10.1038/scientificamerican1009-64 |pmid=19780454 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nPercy Fawcett was born on 18 August 1867 in [[Torquay]], [[Devon]], England, to [[Edward Fawcett|Edward Boyd Fawcett]] and Myra Elizabeth (n\u00e9e MacDougall).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keverelchess.com/e-douglas-fawcett-1866-1960/ |work=Keverel Chess |title=E. Douglas Fawcett (1866\u20131960) |date=10 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403012650/http://www.keverelchess.com/e-douglas-fawcett-1866-1960/ |archivedate=3 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Fawcett received his early education at [[Newton Abbot]] Proprietary College, alongside the sportsman and journalist [[Bertram Fletcher Robinson]]. Fawcett's father, who had been born in India, was a Fellow of the [[Royal Geographical Society]] (RGS), while his elder brother, [[Edward Douglas Fawcett]] (1866\u20131960), was a mountain climber, an Eastern [[occultist]], and the author of philosophical books and popular [[Adventure fiction|adventure novels]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/fawcett_e_douglas |title=Fawcett, E Douglas |date=18 January 2017 |encyclopedia=[[The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction]]}}</ref>\n\nFawcett attended the [[Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]], as a cadet, and was commissioned as a lieutenant of the [[Royal Artillery]] on 24 July 1886.<ref>{{London Gazette |date=10 August 1886 |issue=25615 |page=3855 }}</ref> On 13 January 1896, he was appointed [[adjutant]]<ref>{{London Gazette |date=24 January 1896 |issue=26703 |page=424 |nolink=yes}}</ref> of the [[1st Cornwall (Duke of Cornwall's) Artillery Volunteers]],<ref>{{London Gazette |date=31 January 1896 |issue=26705 |page=589 |nolink=yes}}</ref> and was promoted to captain on 15 June 1897.<ref>{{London Gazette |date=2 July 1897 |issue=26869 |page=3635 |nolink=yes}}</ref> He later served in [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]], [[Crown Colony of Malta|Malta]], and [[Trincomalee]], [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Percy |title=Exploration Fawcett: Journey to the Lost City of Z |publisher=The Overlook Press |isbn=978-1590208366 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vHsjCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT27|date=2010-05-04 }}</ref> where he met his future wife Nina Agnes Paterson, whom he married in January 1901 after having previously ended their engagement. They had two sons, Jack (1903-?1925), and Brian (1906\u20131984), and one daughter, Joan (1910\u20132005).\n\nFawcett joined the [[Royal Geographical Society|RGS]] in 1901, in order to study [[surveying]] and [[mapmaking]]. Later, he worked for the [[Secret Intelligence Service|British Secret Service]] in [[North Africa]] while pursuing the surveyor's craft. He served for the [[War Office]] on [[Spike Island, County Cork|Spike Island]] in [[County Cork]] from 1903 to 1906, where he was promoted to major on 11 January 1905.<ref>{{London Gazette |date=12 May 1905 |issue=27792 |page=3426 |nolink=yes}}</ref> He became friends with authors [[Sir Henry Rider Haggard]] and [[Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]]; the latter used Fawcett's [[Amazon basin|Amazonian]] field reports as an inspiration for his novel ''[[The Lost World (Conan Doyle novel)|The Lost World]]''.\n\n===Early expeditions===\nFawcett's first expedition to South America was in 1906 (he was seconded for service there on 2 May<ref>{{London Gazette |date=25 May 1906 |issue=27916 |page=3657 |nolink=yes}}</ref>) when at the age of 39 he travelled to Brazil to map a jungle area at the border of Brazil and Bolivia at the behest of the Royal Geographical Society. The Society had been commissioned to map the area as a third party unbiased by local [[Nationalism|national interests]]. He arrived in [[La Paz]], [[Bolivia]], in June. While on the expedition in 1907, Fawcett claimed to have seen and shot a {{convert|62|ft|m|adj=mid}} long giant anaconda, a claim for which he was ridiculed by scientists. He reported other mysterious animals unknown to zoology, such as a small cat-like dog about the size of a [[foxhound]], which he claimed to have seen twice, and the giant Apazauca spider which was said to have poisoned a number of locals.<ref>Fawcett, P. H. and Fawcett, B. ''Exploration Fawcett'' (1953)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phfawcettsweb.org/apazauca.htm |title=Apazauca spider |work=The Great Web of Percy Harrison Fawcett}}</ref>\n\nFawcett made seven expeditions between 1906 and 1924. He was mostly amicable with the locals through gifts, patience, and courteous behaviour. In 1908, he traced the source of the [[Verde River (Guapor\u00e9 River)|Rio Verde]] (Brazil) and in 1910 made a journey to [[Heath River]] (on the border between [[Peru]] and Bolivia) to find its source, having retired from the British army on 19 January.<ref>{{London Gazette |date=18 January 1910 |issue=28330 |page=434 |nolink=yes}}</ref>\n\nAfter a 1913 expedition, he supposedly claimed to have seen dogs with double noses. These may have been [[double-nosed Andean tiger hound]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/6940289.stm |title=Double-nosed dog not to be sniffed at |work=BBC News |date=10 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nBased on documentary research, Fawcett had by 1914 formulated ideas about a \"lost city\" he named \"Z\" (''Zed'') somewhere in the [[Mato Grosso]] region of Brazil. He theorized that a complex civilization once existed in the Amazon region and that isolated ruins may have survived.<ref name=\"Yorker\">{{cite journal |last=Grann |first=David |title=The Lost City of Z |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |date=19 September 2005 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2005/09/19/the-lost-city-of-z |accessdate=23 December 2016}}</ref> Fawcett also found a document known as \"Manuscript 512\", written after explorations made in the ''[[sert\u00e3o]]'' of the state of [[Bahia]], and housed at the National Library of [[Rio de Janeiro]]. It is believed to be by Portuguese [[bandeirante]] {{ill|Jo\u00e3o da Silva Guimar\u00e3es|pt}}, who wrote that in 1753 he'd discovered the ruins of an ancient city that contained arches, a statue, and a temple with [[hieroglyphics]]; the city is described in great detail without providing a specific location. This city became a secondary destination for Fawcett, after \"Z\". (See Fawcett's own book ''Exploration Fawcett''.)\n\nAt the beginning of the [[First World War]] Fawcett returned to Britain to serve with the Army as a Reserve Officer in the Royal Artillery, volunteering for duty in [[Flanders]], and commanding an [[artillery brigade]] despite being nearly 50 years old. He was promoted from major to lieutenant-colonel on 1 March 1918,<ref>{{London Gazette |date=10 January 1919 |supp=y |issue=31120 |page=674 |nolink=yes}}</ref> and received three [[mentions in despatches]] from [[Field Marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] [[Douglas Haig, 1st Earl Haig|Sir Douglas Haig]], in November 1916,<ref>{{London Gazette |date=2 January 1917 |supp=y |issue=29890 |page=208 |nolink=yes}}</ref> November 1917,<ref>{{London Gazette |date=7 December 1917 |supp=y |issue=30421 |page=12912 |nolink=yes}}</ref> and November 1918,<ref>{{London Gazette |date=17 December 1918 |supp=y |issue=31077 |page=14926 |nolink=yes}}</ref> and was also awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]] in June 1917.<ref>{{London Gazette |date=1 June 1917 |supp=y |issue=30111 |pages=5468\u20135470  |nolink=yes}}</ref>\n\nAfter the war Fawcett returned to Brazil to study local wildlife and [[archaeology]]. In 1920, he made a solo attempt to search for \"Z\", but ended it after suffering from a fever and shooting his pack animal.<ref name=\"Yorker\"/>\n\n===Final expedition===\nIn 1925, with funding from a London-based group of financiers known as 'the Glove',<ref>''The London Illustrated News'', 22 June 1924</ref> Fawcett returned to Brazil with his eldest son Jack and Jack's best and longtime friend, Raleigh Rimell, for an exploratory expedition to find \"Z\". Fawcett left instructions stating that if the expedition did not return, no rescue expedition should be sent lest the rescuers suffer his fate.\n\nFawcett was a man with years of experience travelling, and had taken equipment such as canned foods, powdered milk, guns, flares, a [[sextant]], and a [[Marine chronometer|chronometer]]. His travel companions were both chosen for their health, ability, and loyalty to each other; Fawcett chose only two companions in order to travel lighter and with less notice to native tribes, as some were hostile towards outsiders.\n\nOn 20 April 1925, his final expedition departed from [[Cuiab\u00e1]]. In addition to his two principal companions, Fawcett was accompanied by two Brazilian labourers, two horses, eight mules, and a pair of dogs. The last communication from the expedition was on 29 May 1925 when Fawcett wrote, in a letter to his wife delivered by a native runner, that he was ready to go into unexplored territory with only Jack and Raleigh. They were reported to be crossing the [[Xingu River|Upper Xingu]], a [[Ordinal directions|southeastern]] [[tributary]] river of the [[Amazon River|River Amazon]]. The final letter, written from [[Dead Horse Camp]], gave their location and was generally optimistic.\n\nMany people assumed that local [[Indigenous peoples in Brazil|Indians]] killed them, as several tribes were nearby at the time: the [[Kalapalo]]s, the last tribe to have seen them, the Arum\u00e1s, the [[Suy\u00e1]]s, and the [[Xavante people|Xavantes]] whose territory they were entering. According to explorer [[John Hemming (explorer)|John Hemming]], Fawcett's party of three was too few to survive in the jungle, and his expectation that his Indian hosts would look after them was likely to have antagonized them by failing to bring any gifts to repay their generosity.<ref name=Hemming2017-04-01b>{{cite magazine |author=John Hemming|authorlink=John Hemming (explorer)|title=The Lost City of Z is a very long way from a true story \u2014 and I should know|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/the-lost-city-of-z-is-a-very-long-way-from-a-true-story-and-i-should-know/|date=1 April 2017|accessdate=11 March 2019|magazine= [[The Spectator]]|quote=Everyone in Amazonia knew that you could not cut trails and keep your team fed with fewer than eight men. ... His other dictum was that Indians would look after them. This was equally dangerous. The Xingu tribes pride themselves on generosity; but they expect visitors to reciprocate. All expeditions in the past four decades had brought plenty of presents such as machetes, knives and beads. Fawcett had none. He committed other blunders that antagonised their hosts. So it was only a matter of days before they were all dead.}}</ref> Twenty years later a Kalapalo chief called Comatzi told his people how the unwelcome strangers were killed,<ref name=Hemming2017-04-01c>{{cite magazine |author=John Hemming|authorlink=John Hemming (explorer)|title=The Lost City of Z is a very long way from a true story \u2014 and I should know|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/the-lost-city-of-z-is-a-very-long-way-from-a-true-story-and-i-should-know/|date=1 April 2017|accessdate=11 March 2019 |magazine= [[The Spectator]]|quote=Twenty years later, Chief Comatsi of the Kalapalo tribe gave a very detailed account of Fawcett\u2019s visit, reminding his assembled people of exactly how they had killed the unwelcome strangers. But the German anthropologist Max Schmidt, who was there in 1926, thought that they had plunged into the forests, got lost and starved to death; this was also the view of a missionary couple called Young who were on another Xingu headwater. The Brazilian Indian Service regretted that Fawcett, who was obsessively secretive, had not asked for their help in dealing with the Indians. They felt he was killed because of the harshness and lack of tact that all recognised in him.}} (Note: Hemming spells the chief's name 'Comatsi', but most other sources spell it 'Comatzi'.)</ref> but others have thought they got lost and died of starvation,<ref name=Hemming2017-04-01c/><ref name=\"Costin's opinion\"/> and the bones provided by Comatzi turned out not to be those of Fawcett.<ref name=phfw-Izarari01a/> Edmar Morel and Nilo Vellozo reported that Comatzi's predecessor, Kalapalos Chief Izarari, had told them he had killed Fawcett and his son Jack, seemingly by shooting them with arrows after Fawcett allegedly attacked him and other Indians when they refused to give him guides and porters to take him to their Chavante enemies, and Rolf Blomberg said Izarari had told him that Raleigh Rimell had already died of fever in a camp of Kurikuro Indians.<ref name=phfw-Izarepo01a>{{cite web |url=https://www.phfawcettsweb.org/izarepo.htm|title=Reports for Fawcett's assassination by Izarari|work=The Great Web of Percy Harrison Fawcett|accessdate=11 March 2019|quote=References for the summary & highlights of the following articles taken from: The Rolf Blomberg's book \"Chavante, An expedition to the Tribes of the Matto Grosso\", pages 70 & 71}} (Blomberg's book was first published in 1958; various editions of it can be found [https://books.google.ie/books?id=7ekCAAAAMAAJ&q=editions:cEvbW1OkopUC&dq=editions:cEvbW1OkopUC&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjJureTtPvgAhWVXhUIHVw4AmcQ6AEIKjAA here])</ref> A somewhat different version came from [[Villas-B\u00f4as brothers|Orlando Villas-B\u00f4as]] who reported that Izarari had told him that he had killed all three white men with his club the morning after Jack Fawcett had allegedly consorted with one of his wives, when he claimed that Percy Fawcett had slapped him in the face after the chief refused his demand for canoes and porters to continue his journey.<ref name=phfw-Izarepo01a/>\n\nThe Kalapalo have an oral story of the arrival of three explorers which states that the three went east, and after five days the Kalapalo noticed that the group no longer made camp fires.{{cn|reason=Contradicts reported claims by Comatzi and Izarari.|date=March 2019}} The Kalapalo say that a very violent tribe most likely killed them.{{cn|reason=Contradicts reported claims by Comatzi and Izarari.|date=March 2019}} However, both of the younger men were lame and ill when last seen,{{cn|date=March 2019}} and there is no proof that they were murdered. It is plausible that they died of natural causes in the Brazilian jungle.<ref name=Hemming2017-04-01c/><ref name=\"Costin's opinion\"/><ref name=phfw-Izarari01a/>\n\nIn 1927, a name-plate of Fawcett's was found with an Indian tribe. In June 1933, a [[theodolite]] compass belonging to Fawcett was found near the Baciary Indians of Mato Grosso by Colonel Aniceto Botelho. However, the name-plate was from Fawcett's expedition five years earlier and had most likely been given as a gift to the chief of that Indian tribe. The compass was proven to have been left behind before he entered the jungle on his final journey.<ref>{{cite web |first1=David |last1=Wallechinsky |first2=Irving |last2=Wallace |year=1981 |title=History of the Search for Percy H. Fawcett, Part 2 |work=Trivia-Library.com |url=http://www.trivia-library.com/c/history-of-the-search-for-percy-h-fawcett-part-2.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Cummins |first=Geraldine |title=The Fate of Colonel Fawcett |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t8AY1PWtIacC&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14 |date=March 1985 |publisher=Health Research Books |isbn=978-0-7873-0230-6 |page=14}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Basso |first=Ellen B. |title=The Last Cannibals: A South American Oral History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LCFoN_D2D38C |date=22 July 2010 |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn=978-0-292-79206-7}}</ref>\n\n====Dead Horse Camp====\nDead Horse Camp, or Fawcett's Camp, is one of the major camps that Fawcett made on his final journey. This encampment was his last known location.<ref name=\"last words\">{{cite web |title=Colonel Fawcett's Last Words |url=http://colonel-percy-fawcett.blog.co.uk/2010/02/26/colonel-fawcett-s-last-words-8079122/ |work=Colonel Percy Fawcett's Search For the Lost city of Z |accessdate=9 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928233142/http://colonel-percy-fawcett.blog.co.uk/2010/02/26/colonel-fawcett-s-last-words-8079122/ |archivedate=28 September 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> From Dead Horse Camp, Fawcett wrote to his wife about the hardships that he and his companions had faced, his coordinates, his doubts in Raleigh Rimell, and Fawcett's plans for the near future. He concludes his message with, \u201cYou need have no fear of any failure...\u201d<ref name=\"last words\" />\n\nOne question remaining about Dead Horse Camp concerns a discrepancy in the coordinates Fawcett gave for the camp. In the letter to his wife, he wrote: \"Here we are at Dead Horse Camp, latitude 11 degrees 43' South and longitude 54 degrees 35' West, the spot where my horse died in 1920\" ({{coord|11|43|S|54|35|W}}). However, in a report to the [[North American Newspaper Alliance]] he gave the coordinates as {{coord|13|43|S|54|35|W}}.<ref name=\"camp location\">{{cite web|title=Dead Horse Camp (Fawcett's Camp)|url=http://www.phfawcettsweb.org/dehocamp.htm|work=The Great Web of Percy Harrison Fawcett|accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe discrepancy may have been a [[typographical]] error. However, he may have intentionally concealed the location to prevent others from using his notes to find the lost city.<ref name=chronicles>{{cite web|title=The Continuing Chronicles of Colonel Fawcett|url=http://www.catchpenny.org/fawcett.html|accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref> It may have also been an attempt to dissuade any rescue attempts; Fawcett had stated that if he disappeared, no rescue party should be sent because the danger was too great.<ref name=\"camp location\"/>\n\n==Posthumous controversy and speculations==\n\n==={{anchor|Henry Costin}}Henry Costin's opinion===\nExplorer Henry Costin <!-- PLEASE DO NOT link to [[Henry Costin]]; that page redirects to a different person -->accompanied Fawcett on five of his previous expeditions. Costin expressed his doubt that Fawcett would have perished at the hands of native Indians, as he typically enjoyed good relations with them. He believed that Fawcett had succumbed to either a lack of food or exhaustion.<ref name=\"Costin's opinion\">{{cite news\n|newspaper=[[Lancashire Evening Post]] |date=25 July 1931 |page=4\n|title=Man Who Knew Fawcett |access-date=11 June 2018\n|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/BL/0000711/19310725/164/0004}}</ref>\n\n===Rumours and unverified reports===\nDuring the ensuing decades, various groups mounted several rescue expeditions, without success. They heard only various rumours that could not be verified.\n\nWhile a fictitious tale estimated that 100 would-be-rescuers died on several expeditions attempting to discover Fawcett's fate,<ref>{{cite book |last=Grann |first=David |year=2010 |title=The Lost City of Z: A Tale of Deadly Obsession in the Amazon |publisher=Vintage Books |location=New York |page=273 |isbn=978-1-4000-7845-5}}</ref> the actual toll was only one - a sole man who ventured after him alone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/the-lost-city-of-z-is-a-very-long-way-from-a-true-story-and-i-should-know/|title=The Lost City of Z is a very long way from a true story and I should know|last=Hemming|first=John|date=1 April 2017|website=The Spectator|access-date=}}</ref> One of the earliest expeditions was commanded by American explorer [[George Miller Dyott]]. In 1927 he claimed to have found evidence of Fawcett's death at the hands of the [[Aloique]] Indians, but his story was unconvincing. From 1930\u201331, [[Aloha Wanderwell#Brazil|Aloha Wanderwell]] used her seaplane to try to land on the Amazon River in the Mato Grosso to find him. After an emergency landing and living with the Bororo tribe for 6 weeks, Aloha and her husband Walter flew back to Brazil, with no luck. A 1951 expedition unearthed human bones that were found later to be unrelated to Fawcett or his companions.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Villas-B\u00f4as story===\nDanish explorer [[Arne Falk-R\u00f8nne]] journeyed to the Mato Grosso during the 1960s. In a 1991 book, he wrote that he learned of Fawcett's fate from [[Villas-B\u00f4as brothers|Orlando Villas-B\u00f4as]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=875jDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Arne+Falk-R%C3%B8nne#v=snippet&q=fawcett%20Orlando%20Villas-B%C3%B4as|title=Dr. Klapperslange|last=Falk-R\u00f8nne|first=Arne|date=2017-03-16|publisher=Lindhardt og Ringhof|isbn=9788711714096|language=da}}</ref> who had heard it from one of Fawcett's murderers. Allegedly, Fawcett and his companions had a mishap on the river and lost most of the gifts they'd brought along for the Indian tribes. Continuing without gifts was a serious breach of protocol; since the expedition members were all more or less seriously ill at the time, the Kalapalo tribe they encountered decided to kill them. The bodies of Jack Fawcett and Raleigh Rimell were thrown into the river; Colonel Fawcett, considered an old man and therefore distinguished, received a proper burial. Falk-R\u00f8nne visited the Kalapalo tribe and reported that one of the tribesmen confirmed Villas-B\u00f4as's story about how and why Fawcett had been killed.\n\n===Fawcett's bones===\nIn 1951, Orlando Villas-B\u00f4as, activist for indigenous peoples, supposedly received the actual remaining skeletal bones of Fawcett and had them analysed scientifically. The analysis allegedly confirmed the bones were Fawcett's, but his son Brian Fawcett (1906\u20131984) refused to accept this. Villas-B\u00f4as claimed that Brian was too interested in making money from books about his father's disappearance. Later scientific analysis confirmed that the bones were not Fawcett's.<ref>''The upper jaw provides the clearest possible evidence that these human remains were not those of Colonel Fawcett, whose spare upper denture is fortunately available for comparison. ''[[Royal Anthropological Institute of Great Britain and Ireland|Royal Anthropological Institute]] (London) (1951) \"Report on the human remains from Brazil\" as quoted by Grann (2009) p. 253</ref><ref name=phfw-Izarari01a>{{cite web |url=http://www.phfawcettsweb.org/apazauca.htm |title=Izarari, Chief of the Kalapalos|work=The Great Web of Percy Harrison Fawcett|accessdate=11 March 2019|quote=Comatzi, the later chief of Kalapalos after Izarari\u2019s death, was after much persuasion induced to disclose the grave of the murderer explorer, and bones were dug up and examined by a team of experts of the Royal Anthropological Institute in London, but the results indicated that those bones were not of Fawcett and there is a doubt whether they belong to a white man. The bodies of the younger ones were thrown in the river, said Comatzi. At all events, they have not been found.}}</ref> As of 1965, the bones reportedly rested in a box in the flat of one of the Villas-B\u00f4as brothers in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/1953-COL-FAWCETT-PERU-BOLIVIA-BRAZIL-SOUTH-AMERICA-LOST-EXPEDITION-EL-DORADO-/382017420937|title=1953 Col. Fawcett Peru Bolivia Brazil South America Lost Expedition El Dorado|website=eBay|access-date=2017-07-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, English explorer [[Benedict Allen]] went to talk to the Kalapalo Indians, said by Villas-B\u00f4as to have confessed to having killed the three Fawcett expedition members. An elder of the Kalapalo, Vajuvi, claimed during a filmed BBC interview with Allen that the bones found by Villas-B\u00f4as 45 years before were not really Fawcett's.<ref name=\"Orcutt\" /><ref>\"Vajuvi said that they were the bones of his grandfather, Mugikia.\" Grann (2009) pp. 252\u2013253</ref> Vajuvi also denied that his tribe had any part in the Fawcetts' disappearance.{{cn|reason=Citation needed, especially as Vajuvi would be contradicting the earlier reported claims by Comatzi and Izarari.|date=March 2019}} No conclusive evidence supports either statement.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Russian documentary===\nIn 2003, a Russian documentary film, ''The Curse of the Incas' Gold / Expedition of Percy Fawcett to the Amazon'' ({{lang-ru|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043b\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0435 \u0437\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0438\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432 / \u042d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0446\u0438\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438 \u0424\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0432 \u0410\u043c\u0430\u0437\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443}}), was released as a part of the television series ''Mysteries of the Century'' ({{lang|ru|\u0422\u0430\u0439\u043d\u044b \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430}}). Among other things, the film emphasizes the recent expedition of Oleg Aliyev to the presumed approximate place of Fawcett's last whereabouts and Aliyev's findings, impressions and presumptions about Fawcett's fate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://filmix.net/tv/28662-tayny-veka-proklyatie-zolota-inkov-ekspediciya-persi-fosseta-v-amazonku-2004.html |title=\u0422\u0430\u0439\u043d\u044b \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430. \u041f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043b\u044f\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0438\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432. \u042d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0446\u0438\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438 \u0424\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0432 \u0410\u043c\u0430\u0437\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443. |trans-title=Secrets of the century. The curse of the Inca gold. Expedition of Percy Fosset to the Amazon. |work=Filmix.net |date=2011 |language=Russian}}</ref>\n\n===Commune in the jungle===\nOn 21 March 2004, the British newspaper ''[[The Observer]]'' reported that television director Misha Williams, who had studied Fawcett's private papers, believed that Fawcett had not intended to return to Britain but rather meant to found a [[commune (intentional community)|commune]] in the jungle based on [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|theosophical]] principles and the worship of his son Jack.<ref>{{cite news |first=Vanessa |last=Thorpe |title=Veil lifts on jungle mystery of the Colonel who vanished |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |date=21 March 2004 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/mar/21/research.brazil}}</ref> Williams explained his research in some detail in the preface to his play ''AmaZonia'', first performed in April 2004.<ref>{{cite book |first=Misha |last=Williams |title=AmaZonia |url=http://www.fawcettsamazonia.co.uk/pdf/AmaZonia%20by%20Misha%20Williams.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Grann's ''Lost City of Z''===\n{{Main|The Lost City of Z (book)}}\nIn 2005, ''[[The New Yorker]]'' staff writer [[David Grann]] visited the Kalapalo tribe and reported that it had apparently preserved an oral history about Fawcett, among the first Europeans the tribe had ever seen. The oral account said that Fawcett and his party had stayed at their village and then left, heading eastward. The Kalapalos warned Fawcett and his companions that if they went that way they would be killed by the \"fierce Indians\" who occupied that territory, but Fawcett insisted on going. The Kalapalos observed smoke from the expedition's campfire each evening for five days before it disappeared. The Kalapalos said they were sure the fierce Indians had killed them.<ref name=\"Yorker\"/> The article also reports that a monumental civilisation known as [[Kuhikugu]] may have actually existed near where Fawcett was searching, as discovered recently by archaeologist [[Michael Heckenberger]] and others.<ref>For further info see the last chapter of Grann's book ''[[The Lost City of Z (book)|The Lost City of Z]]'' and Charles Mann's book ''[[1491: New Revelations of the Americas Before Columbus]]''.</ref> Grann's findings are further detailed in his book ''[[The Lost City of Z (book)|The Lost City of Z]]'' (2009).\n\n=== Film adaptation of Grann's book ===\n{{Main|The Lost City of Z (film)}}\n\n===Allegation of racism and dangerous incompetence===\nIn 2017, explorer [[John Hemming (explorer)|John Hemming]] criticized the publicity for the movie ''[[The Lost City of Z (film)|The Lost City of Z]]'' for claiming that Fawcett was one of Britain's greatest explorers, arguing that this was an insult to the many true explorers, and that Fawcett was a racist, a \"nutter\", and a dangerous incompetent who \"never discovered anything\", but caused the loss of many lives.<ref name=Hemming2017-04-01a>{{cite magazine |author=John Hemming|authorlink=John Hemming (explorer)|title=The Lost City of Z is a very long way from a true story \u2014 and I should know|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/the-lost-city-of-z-is-a-very-long-way-from-a-true-story-and-i-should-know/|date=1 April 2017|accessdate=11 March 2019 |magazine= [[The Spectator]]|quote=The new film The Lost City of Z is being advertised as based on the true story of one of Britain\u2019s greatest explorers. .... Greatest explorer? Fawcett? He was a surveyor who never discovered anything, a nutter, a racist, and so incompetent that the only expedition he organised was a five-week disaster. Calling him one of our greatest explorers ... is an insult to the huge roster of true explorers. ... Fawcett casually remarked that five out of his six peons died from the effects of this five-week disaster. ... When one aimed a drawn bow at him, Fawcett shot the man with a Mauser revolver \u2014 absolutely forbidden by Brazil\u2019s Indian Service. ... In 1925, ... Fawcett ... committed other blunders that antagonised their hosts. So it was only a matter of days before they were all dead.}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*Fawcett, Percy and Brian Fawcett (1953), ''Exploration Fawcett'', Phoenix Press (2001 reprint), {{ISBN|1-84212-468-4}}\n*Fawcett, Percy and Brian Fawcett (1953), ''Lost Trails, Lost Cities'', Funk & Wagnalls ASIN B0007DNCV4\n*Fawcett, Brian (1958), ''Ruins in the Sky'', Hutchinson of London\n\n== In popular culture ==\n{{In popular culture|date=April 2017}}\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*Fawcett is the subject of History Channel's ''[[Digging for the Truth]]'' season 2, episode 13: \"[[List of Digging for the Truth episodes|The Lost Cities of the Amazon]]\".\n\n===Fiction===\n*[[Arthur Conan Doyle]] based his [[Professor Challenger]] character partly on Fawcett, and stories of \"the Lost City of Z\" became the basis for Conan Doyle's novel ''[[The Lost World (Conan Doyle novel)|The Lost World]].''<ref>[[David Grann|Grann, David]] (2009) ''[[The Lost City of Z (book)|The Lost City of Z: A Tale of Deadly Obsession in the Amazon]].'' Doubleday, New York, pages 8 and 95, {{ISBN|978-0-385-51353-1}}</ref>\n* A contemporary reviewer of [[Evelyn Waugh]]'s novel ''[[A Handful of Dust]]'' suggested he may have derived the plot partly from Fawcett's disappearance.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Times |date=4 September 1934 |page=7}}</ref>  The novel's hero vanishes into the Brazilian jungle and is kept prisoner there.\n*Fawcett has been proposed as a possible inspiration for [[Indiana Jones]], the fictional archaeologist/adventurer.<ref>Neither [[George Lucas]] nor [[Steven Spielberg]] \u2014 co-creators of the successful concept and franchise \u2014 have indicated that any specific individual inspired their character, other than the generic stock heroes popularised in the [[wikt:matin\u00e9e|matin\u00e9e]] serials and [[pulp magazines]] of the 1930s and 1940s they admired and wished to modernise, or later exotic-culture [[adventure film]]s such as 1954's ''[[Secret of the Incas]]''.</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Making ''Raiders of the Lost Ark'' |date=23 September 2003 |url=http://www.indianajones.com/raiders/bts/news/news20030923.html |work=Raiders News |accessdate=14 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031207015023/http://www.indianajones.com/raiders/bts/news/news20030923.html |archivedate=7 December 2003}}</ref> A fictionalised version of Fawcett aids Jones in the novel ''[[Indiana Jones and the Seven Veils]]''.<ref>{{cite book |first=Rob |last=MacGregor |title=Indiana Jones and the Seven Veils |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |date=November 1991 |url=http://www.randomhouse.com/bantamdell/catalog/display.pperl?isbn=9780553293340 |isbn=978-0-553-29035-6}}</ref>)\n*According to an article in ''Comics Scene'' No. 45, Fawcett was the inspiration of Kent Allard, an [[alter ego]] of [[The Shadow]].<ref name=\"Orcutt\">{{cite web |url=http://home.earthlink.net/~larryorcutt/fawcett.html |first=Larry |last=Orcutt |year=2000 |title=Colonel Percy Harrison Fawcett}}</ref>\n*Fawcett's is one of the past lives experienced under hypnosis by the protagonist of Charles MacLean's novel ''The Watcher'', a psychological thriller about a man who has a violent dissociative episode and seeks psychiatric help in the form of past lives regression therapy.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Aloha Wanderwell]]\n* [[Amazon River]]\n* [[Archaeology]]\n* [[Exploration|Explorers]]\n* [[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: pre-1970|List of people who disappeared]]\n* [[Paititi]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Falk-R\u00f8nne, Arne. (1991). ''Klodens Forunderlige Mysterier''. Roth Forlag.\n* [[Peter Fleming (writer)|Fleming, Peter]]. (1933) ''[[Brazilian Adventure]]'', Charles Scribner's Sons {{ISBN|0-87477-246-X}}\n* [[David Grann|Grann, David]] (2009) ''[[The Lost City of Z (book)|The Lost City of Z: A Tale of Deadly Obsession in the Amazon]]'' {{ISBN|978-0-385-51353-1}}\n* Leal, Hermes (1996), ''Enigma do Coronel Fawcett, o verdadeiro Indiana Jones'' (''Colonel Fawcett: The Real-Life Indiana Jones''; Published in Portuguese)\n* La Gazette des Fran\u00e7ais du Paraguay, ''Percy Fawcett - Un monument de l'Exploration et de l'Aventure en Am\u00e9rique Latine - Exp\u00e9dition du Rio Verde'' - bilingue fran\u00e7ais espagnol - num\u00e9ro 6, Ann\u00e9e 1, Asuncion Paraguay.\n* Scriblerius, C.S. (2015), \"Percyfaw Code, the secret dossier\" Published by Amazon.com.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://duncanjdsmith.com/uploads/documents/Forgotten/fawcett_18.pdf Forgotten Travellers: The Hunt for Colonel Fawcett]  Essay on Lt.-Col. Percy Harrison Fawcett\n*[http://www.unmuseum.org/fawcett.htm Virtual Exploration Society \u2013 Colonel Percy Fawcett]\n*[http://www.catchpenny.org/fawcett.html Colonel Fawcett]\n*[http://www.nybooks.com/articles/22662 Mad Dreams in the Amazon] Essay on Fawcett from ''[[The New York Review of Books]]''\n*[http://www.gryphonproductions.com/blog Lost in the Amazon: The Enigma of Col. Percy Fawcett] PBS Secrets of the Dead documentary\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090625171723/http://www.bfronline.biz/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=123&Itemid=9 ''B. Fletcher Robinson & 'The Lost World'''] by Paul Spiring\n*[https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/the-lost-city-of-z-is-a-very-long-way-from-a-true-story-and-i-should-know/ The Lost City of Z is a Long Way From a True Story and I Should Know by John Hemming in [[The Spectator]] ]\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/005015}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fawcett, Percy}}\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1920s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:People from Torquay]]\n[[Category:English archaeologists]]\n[[Category:English explorers]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Amazonia]]\n[[Category:Lost explorers]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Professor Challenger]]\n[[Category:Royal Artillery officers]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Distinguished Service Order]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n| name               = Percy Harrison Fawcett\n| honorific_suffix   = {{Post-nominals|GBR|DSO|size=100}}\n| image              = PercyFawcett.jpg\n| caption            = Fawcett in 1911\n| birth_name         = Percy Harrison Fawcett\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1867|8|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Torquay]], [[Devon]], United Kingdom\n| disappeared_date   = {{Disappeared date and age|df=yes|1925|5|29|1867|8|18}}\n| disappeared_place  = [[Mato Grosso]], Brazil\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Nina Agnes Paterson|January 1901}}\n| children           = 3\n| occupation         = Artillery officer, archaeologist, geologist, explorer\n| module             = {{Infobox military person | embed=yes\n| allegiance = United Kingdom\n| branch = British Army\n| serviceyears = 1886\u20131910<br/>{{Circa}}1914\u20131919\n| rank = [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant Colonel]]\n| unit = [[Royal Artillery]]\n| commands =\n| battles = [[World War I]]\n| awards = [[Distinguished Service Order]]<br/>3 \u00d7 [[Mentioned in despatches]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Percy Harrison Fawcett''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|DSO}} (18 August 1867{{spaced ndash}}[[Declared death in absentia|during or after]] 1925) was a British [[geography|geographer]], [[Royal Artillery|artillery officer]], [[cartography|cartographer]], [[archaeology|archaeologist]], and [[exploration|explorer]] of South America. Fawcett disappeared in 1925 (along with his eldest son, Jack, and one of Jack's friends, Raleigh Rimell) during an expedition to find \"[[Lost City of Z|Z]]\"\u2014his name for an ancient [[lost city]] which he and others believed existed in the [[Amazon rainforest|jungles of Brazil]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Heckenberger |first=Michael J. |date=2009 |title=Lost Cities of the Amazon |journal=[[Scientific American]] |volume=301 |issue=4 |pages=64\u201371|doi=10.1038/scientificamerican1009-64 |pmid=19780454 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nPercy Fawcett was born on 18 August 1867 in [[Torquay]], [[Devon]], England, to [[Edward Fawcett|Edward Boyd Fawcett]] and Myra Elizabeth (n\u00e9e MacDougall).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keverelchess.com/e-douglas-fawcett-1866-1960/ |work=Keverel Chess |title=E. Douglas Fawcett (1866\u20131960) |date=10 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403012650/http://www.keverelchess.com/e-douglas-fawcett-1866-1960/ |archivedate=3 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Fawcett received his early education at [[Newton Abbot]] Proprietary College, alongside the sportsman and journalist [[Bertram Fletcher Robinson]]. Fawcett's father, who had been born in India, was a Fellow of the [[Royal Geographical Society]] (RGS), while his elder brother, [[Edward Douglas Fawcett]] (1866\u20131960), was a mountain climber, an Eastern [[occultist]], and the author of philosophical books and popular [[Adventure fiction|adventure novels]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/fawcett_e_douglas |title=Fawcett, E Douglas |date=18 January 2017 |encyclopedia=[[The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction]]}}</ref>\n\nFawcett attended the [[Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]], as a cadet, and was commissioned as a lieutenant of the [[Royal Artillery]] on 24 July 1886.<ref>{{London Gazette |date=10 August 1886 |issue=25615 |page=3855 }}</ref> On 13 January 1896, he was appointed [[adjutant]]<ref>{{London Gazette |date=24 January 1896 |issue=26703 |page=424 |nolink=yes}}</ref> of the [[1st Cornwall (Duke of Cornwall's) Artillery Volunteers]],<ref>{{London Gazette |date=31 January 1896 |issue=26705 |page=589 |nolink=yes}}</ref> and was promoted to captain on 15 June 1897.<ref>{{London Gazette |date=2 July 1897 |issue=26869 |page=3635 |nolink=yes}}</ref> He later served in [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]], [[Crown Colony of Malta|Malta]], and [[Trincomalee]], [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Percy |title=Exploration Fawcett: Journey to the Lost City of Z |publisher=The Overlook Press |isbn=978-1590208366 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vHsjCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT27|date=2010-05-04 }}</ref> where he met his future wife Nina Agnes Paterson, whom he married in January 1901 after having previously ended their engagement. They had two sons, Jack (1903-?1925), and Brian (1906\u20131984), and one daughter, Joan (1910\u20132005).\n\nFawcett joined the [[Royal Geographical Society|RGS]] in 1901, in order to study [[surveying]] and [[mapmaking]]. Later, he worked for the [[Secret Intelligence Service|British Secret Service]] in [[North Africa]] while pursuing the surveyor's craft. He served for the [[War Office]] on [[Spike Island, County Cork|Spike Island]] in [[County Cork]] from 1903 to 1906, where he was promoted to major on 11 January 1905.<ref>{{London Gazette |date=12 May 1905 |issue=27792 |page=3426 |nolink=yes}}</ref> He became friends with authors [[Sir Henry Rider Haggard]] and [[Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]]; the latter used Fawcett's [[Amazon basin|Amazonian]] field reports as an inspiration for his novel ''[[The Lost World (Conan Doyle novel)|The Lost World]]''.\n\n===Early expeditions===\nFawcett's first expedition to South America was in 1906 (he was seconded for service there on 2 May<ref>{{London Gazette |date=25 May 1906 |issue=27916 |page=3657 |nolink=yes}}</ref>) when at the age of 39 he travelled to Brazil to map a jungle area at the border of Brazil and Bolivia at the behest of the [[Royal Geographical Society]]. The Society had been commissioned to map the area as a third party unbiased by local [[Nationalism|national interests]]. He arrived in [[La Paz]], [[Bolivia]], in June. While on the expedition in 1907, Fawcett claimed to have seen and shot a {{convert|62|ft|m|adj=mid}} long giant anaconda, a claim for which he was ridiculed by scientists. He reported other mysterious animals unknown to zoology, such as a small cat-like dog about the size of a [[foxhound]], which he claimed to have seen twice, and the giant Apazauca spider which was said to have poisoned a number of locals.<ref>Fawcett, P. H. and Fawcett, B. ''Exploration Fawcett'' (1953)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phfawcettsweb.org/apazauca.htm |title=Apazauca spider |work=The Great Web of Percy Harrison Fawcett}}</ref>\n\nFawcett made seven expeditions between 1906 and 1924. He was mostly amicable with the locals through gifts, patience, and courteous behaviour. In 1908, he traced the source of the [[Verde River (Guapor\u00e9 River)|Rio Verde]] (Brazil) and in 1910 made a journey to [[Heath River]] (on the border between [[Peru]] and Bolivia) to find its source, having retired from the British army on 19 January.<ref>{{London Gazette |date=18 January 1910 |issue=28330 |page=434 |nolink=yes}}</ref>\n\nAfter a 1913 expedition, he supposedly claimed to have seen dogs with double noses. These may have been [[double-nosed Andean tiger hound]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/6940289.stm |title=Double-nosed dog not to be sniffed at |work=BBC News |date=10 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nBased on documentary research, Fawcett had by 1914 formulated ideas about a \"lost city\" he named \"Z\" (''Zed'') somewhere in the [[Mato Grosso]] region of Brazil. He theorized that a complex civilization once existed in the Amazon region and that isolated ruins may have survived.<ref name=\"Yorker\">{{cite journal |last=Grann |first=David |title=The Lost City of Z |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |date=19 September 2005 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2005/09/19/the-lost-city-of-z |accessdate=23 December 2016}}</ref> Fawcett also found a document known as \"Manuscript 512\", written after explorations made in the ''[[sert\u00e3o]]'' of the state of [[Bahia]], and housed at the National Library of [[Rio de Janeiro]]. It is believed to be by Portuguese [[bandeirante]] {{ill|Jo\u00e3o da Silva Guimar\u00e3es|pt}}, who wrote that in 1753 he'd discovered the ruins of an ancient city that contained arches, a statue, and a temple with [[hieroglyphics]]; the city is described in great detail without providing a specific location. This city became a secondary destination for Fawcett, after \"Z\". (See Fawcett's own book ''Exploration Fawcett''.)\n\nAt the beginning of the [[First World War]] Fawcett returned to Britain to serve with the Army as a Reserve Officer in the Royal Artillery, volunteering for duty in [[Flanders]], and commanding an [[artillery brigade]] despite being nearly 50 years old. He was promoted from major to lieutenant-colonel on 1 March 1918,<ref>{{London Gazette |date=10 January 1919 |supp=y |issue=31120 |page=674 |nolink=yes}}</ref> and received three [[mentions in despatches]] from [[Field Marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] [[Douglas Haig, 1st Earl Haig|Sir Douglas Haig]], in November 1916,<ref>{{London Gazette |date=2 January 1917 |supp=y |issue=29890 |page=208 |nolink=yes}}</ref> November 1917,<ref>{{London Gazette |date=7 December 1917 |supp=y |issue=30421 |page=12912 |nolink=yes}}</ref> and November 1918,<ref>{{London Gazette |date=17 December 1918 |supp=y |issue=31077 |page=14926 |nolink=yes}}</ref> and was also awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]] in June 1917.<ref>{{London Gazette |date=1 June 1917 |supp=y |issue=30111 |pages=5468\u20135470  |nolink=yes}}</ref>\n\nAfter the war Fawcett returned to Brazil to study local wildlife and [[archaeology]]. In 1920, he made a solo attempt to search for \"Z\", but ended it after suffering from a fever and shooting his pack animal.<ref name=\"Yorker\"/>\n\n===Final expedition===\nIn 1925, with funding from a London-based group of financiers known as 'the Glove',<ref>''The London Illustrated News'', 22 June 1924</ref> Fawcett returned to Brazil with his eldest son Jack and Jack's best and longtime friend, Raleigh Rimell, for an exploratory expedition to find \"Z\". Fawcett left instructions stating that if the expedition did not return, no rescue expedition should be sent lest the rescuers suffer his fate.\n\nFawcett was a man with years of experience travelling, and had taken equipment such as canned foods, powdered milk, guns, flares, a [[sextant]], and a [[Marine chronometer|chronometer]]. His travel companions were both chosen for their health, ability, and loyalty to each other; Fawcett chose only two companions in order to travel lighter and with less notice to native tribes, as some were hostile towards outsiders.\n\nOn 20 April 1925, his final expedition departed from [[Cuiab\u00e1]]. In addition to his two principal companions, Fawcett was accompanied by two Brazilian labourers, two horses, eight mules, and a pair of dogs. The last communication from the expedition was on 29 May 1925 when Fawcett wrote, in a letter to his wife delivered by a native runner, that he was ready to go into unexplored territory with only Jack and Raleigh. They were reported to be crossing the [[Xingu River|Upper Xingu]], a [[Ordinal directions|southeastern]] [[tributary]] river of the [[Amazon River|River Amazon]]. The final letter, written from [[Dead Horse Camp]], gave their location and was generally optimistic.\n\nMany people assumed that local [[Indigenous peoples in Brazil|Indians]] killed them, as several tribes were nearby at the time: the [[Kalapalo]]s, the last tribe to have seen them, the Arum\u00e1s, the [[Suy\u00e1]]s, and the [[Xavante people|Xavantes]] whose territory they were entering. According to explorer [[John Hemming (explorer)|John Hemming]], Fawcett's party of three was too few to survive in the jungle, and his expectation that his Indian hosts would look after them was likely to have antagonized them by failing to bring any gifts to repay their generosity.<ref name=Hemming2017-04-01b>{{cite magazine |author=John Hemming|authorlink=John Hemming (explorer)|title=The Lost City of Z is a very long way from a true story \u2014 and I should know|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/the-lost-city-of-z-is-a-very-long-way-from-a-true-story-and-i-should-know/|date=1 April 2017|accessdate=11 March 2019|magazine= [[The Spectator]]|quote=Everyone in Amazonia knew that you could not cut trails and keep your team fed with fewer than eight men. ... His other dictum was that Indians would look after them. This was equally dangerous. The Xingu tribes pride themselves on generosity; but they expect visitors to reciprocate. All expeditions in the past four decades had brought plenty of presents such as machetes, knives and beads. Fawcett had none. He committed other blunders that antagonised their hosts. So it was only a matter of days before they were all dead.}}</ref> Twenty years later a Kalapalo chief called Comatzi told his people how the unwelcome strangers were killed,<ref name=Hemming2017-04-01c>{{cite magazine |author=John Hemming|authorlink=John Hemming (explorer)|title=The Lost City of Z is a very long way from a true story \u2014 and I should know|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/the-lost-city-of-z-is-a-very-long-way-from-a-true-story-and-i-should-know/|date=1 April 2017|accessdate=11 March 2019 |magazine= [[The Spectator]]|quote=Twenty years later, Chief Comatsi of the Kalapalo tribe gave a very detailed account of Fawcett\u2019s visit, reminding his assembled people of exactly how they had killed the unwelcome strangers. But the German anthropologist Max Schmidt, who was there in 1926, thought that they had plunged into the forests, got lost and starved to death; this was also the view of a missionary couple called Young who were on another Xingu headwater. The Brazilian Indian Service regretted that Fawcett, who was obsessively secretive, had not asked for their help in dealing with the Indians. They felt he was killed because of the harshness and lack of tact that all recognised in him.}} (Note: Hemming spells the chief's name 'Comatsi', but most other sources spell it 'Comatzi'.)</ref> but others have thought they got lost and died of starvation,<ref name=Hemming2017-04-01c/><ref name=\"Costin's opinion\"/> and the bones provided by Comatzi turned out not to be those of Fawcett.<ref name=phfw-Izarari01a/> Edmar Morel and Nilo Vellozo reported that Comatzi's predecessor, Kalapalos Chief Izarari, had told them he had killed Fawcett and his son Jack, seemingly by shooting them with arrows after Fawcett allegedly attacked him and other Indians when they refused to give him guides and porters to take him to their Chavante enemies, and Rolf Blomberg said Izarari had told him that Raleigh Rimell had already died of fever in a camp of Kurikuro Indians.<ref name=phfw-Izarepo01a>{{cite web |url=https://www.phfawcettsweb.org/izarepo.htm|title=Reports for Fawcett's assassination by Izarari|work=The Great Web of Percy Harrison Fawcett|accessdate=11 March 2019|quote=References for the summary & highlights of the following articles taken from: The Rolf Blomberg's book \"Chavante, An expedition to the Tribes of the Matto Grosso\", pages 70 & 71}} (Blomberg's book was first published in 1958; various editions of it can be found [https://books.google.ie/books?id=7ekCAAAAMAAJ&q=editions:cEvbW1OkopUC&dq=editions:cEvbW1OkopUC&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjJureTtPvgAhWVXhUIHVw4AmcQ6AEIKjAA here])</ref> A somewhat different version came from [[Villas-B\u00f4as brothers|Orlando Villas-B\u00f4as]] who reported that Izarari had told him that he had killed all three white men with his club the morning after Jack Fawcett had allegedly consorted with one of his wives, when he claimed that Percy Fawcett had slapped him in the face after the chief refused his demand for canoes and porters to continue his journey.<ref name=phfw-Izarepo01a/>\n\nThe Kalapalo have an oral story of the arrival of three explorers which states that the three went east, and after five days the Kalapalo noticed that the group no longer made camp fires.{{cn|reason=Contradicts reported claims by Comatzi and Izarari.|date=March 2019}} The Kalapalo say that a very violent tribe most likely killed them.{{cn|reason=Contradicts reported claims by Comatzi and Izarari.|date=March 2019}} However, both of the younger men were lame and ill when last seen,{{cn|date=March 2019}} and there is no proof that they were murdered. It is plausible that they died of natural causes in the Brazilian jungle.<ref name=Hemming2017-04-01c/><ref name=\"Costin's opinion\"/><ref name=phfw-Izarari01a/>\n\nIn 1927, a name-plate of Fawcett's was found with an Indian tribe. In June 1933, a [[theodolite]] compass belonging to Fawcett was found near the Baciary Indians of Mato Grosso by Colonel Aniceto Botelho. However, the name-plate was from Fawcett's expedition five years earlier and had most likely been given as a gift to the chief of that Indian tribe. The compass was proven to have been left behind before he entered the jungle on his final journey.<ref>{{cite web |first1=David |last1=Wallechinsky |first2=Irving |last2=Wallace |year=1981 |title=History of the Search for Percy H. Fawcett, Part 2 |work=Trivia-Library.com |url=http://www.trivia-library.com/c/history-of-the-search-for-percy-h-fawcett-part-2.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Cummins |first=Geraldine |title=The Fate of Colonel Fawcett |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t8AY1PWtIacC&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14 |date=March 1985 |publisher=Health Research Books |isbn=978-0-7873-0230-6 |page=14}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Basso |first=Ellen B. |title=The Last Cannibals: A South American Oral History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LCFoN_D2D38C |date=22 July 2010 |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn=978-0-292-79206-7}}</ref>\n\n====Dead Horse Camp====\nDead Horse Camp, or Fawcett's Camp, is one of the major camps that Fawcett made on his final journey. This encampment was his last known location.<ref name=\"last words\">{{cite web |title=Colonel Fawcett's Last Words |url=http://colonel-percy-fawcett.blog.co.uk/2010/02/26/colonel-fawcett-s-last-words-8079122/ |work=Colonel Percy Fawcett's Search For the Lost city of Z |accessdate=9 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928233142/http://colonel-percy-fawcett.blog.co.uk/2010/02/26/colonel-fawcett-s-last-words-8079122/ |archivedate=28 September 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> From Dead Horse Camp, Fawcett wrote to his wife about the hardships that he and his companions had faced, his coordinates, his doubts in Raleigh Rimell, and Fawcett's plans for the near future. He concludes his message with, \u201cYou need have no fear of any failure...\u201d<ref name=\"last words\" />\n\nOne question remaining about Dead Horse Camp concerns a discrepancy in the coordinates Fawcett gave for the camp. In the letter to his wife, he wrote: \"Here we are at Dead Horse Camp, latitude 11 degrees 43' South and longitude 54 degrees 35' West, the spot where my horse died in 1920\" ({{coord|11|43|S|54|35|W}}). However, in a report to the [[North American Newspaper Alliance]] he gave the coordinates as {{coord|13|43|S|54|35|W}}.<ref name=\"camp location\">{{cite web|title=Dead Horse Camp (Fawcett's Camp)|url=http://www.phfawcettsweb.org/dehocamp.htm|work=The Great Web of Percy Harrison Fawcett|accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe discrepancy may have been a [[typographical]] error. However, he may have intentionally concealed the location to prevent others from using his notes to find the lost city.<ref name=chronicles>{{cite web|title=The Continuing Chronicles of Colonel Fawcett|url=http://www.catchpenny.org/fawcett.html|accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref> It may have also been an attempt to dissuade any rescue attempts; Fawcett had stated that if he disappeared, no rescue party should be sent because the danger was too great.<ref name=\"camp location\"/>\n\n==Posthumous controversy and speculations==\n\n==={{anchor|Henry Costin}}Henry Costin's opinion===\nExplorer Henry Costin <!-- PLEASE DO NOT link to [[Henry Costin]]; that page redirects to a different person -->accompanied Fawcett on five of his previous expeditions. Costin expressed his doubt that Fawcett would have perished at the hands of native Indians, as he typically enjoyed good relations with them. He believed that Fawcett had succumbed to either a lack of food or exhaustion.<ref name=\"Costin's opinion\">{{cite news\n|newspaper=[[Lancashire Evening Post]] |date=25 July 1931 |page=4\n|title=Man Who Knew Fawcett |access-date=11 June 2018\n|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/BL/0000711/19310725/164/0004}}</ref>\n\n===Rumours and unverified reports===\nDuring the ensuing decades, various groups mounted several rescue expeditions, without success. They heard only various rumours that could not be verified.\n\nWhile a fictitious tale estimated that 100 would-be-rescuers died on several expeditions attempting to discover Fawcett's fate,<ref>{{cite book |last=Grann |first=David |year=2010 |title=The Lost City of Z: A Tale of Deadly Obsession in the Amazon |publisher=Vintage Books |location=New York |page=273 |isbn=978-1-4000-7845-5}}</ref> the actual toll was only one - a sole man who ventured after him alone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/the-lost-city-of-z-is-a-very-long-way-from-a-true-story-and-i-should-know/|title=The Lost City of Z is a very long way from a true story and I should know|last=Hemming|first=John|date=1 April 2017|website=The Spectator|access-date=}}</ref> One of the earliest expeditions was commanded by American explorer [[George Miller Dyott]]. In 1927 he claimed to have found evidence of Fawcett's death at the hands of the [[Aloique]] Indians, but his story was unconvincing. From 1930\u201331, [[Aloha Wanderwell#Brazil|Aloha Wanderwell]] used her seaplane to try to land on the Amazon River in the Mato Grosso to find him. After an emergency landing and living with the Bororo tribe for 6 weeks, Aloha and her husband Walter flew back to Brazil, with no luck. A 1951 expedition unearthed human bones that were found later to be unrelated to Fawcett or his companions.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Villas-B\u00f4as story===\nDanish explorer [[Arne Falk-R\u00f8nne]] journeyed to the Mato Grosso during the 1960s. In a 1991 book, he wrote that he learned of Fawcett's fate from [[Villas-B\u00f4as brothers|Orlando Villas-B\u00f4as]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=875jDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Arne+Falk-R%C3%B8nne#v=snippet&q=fawcett%20Orlando%20Villas-B%C3%B4as|title=Dr. Klapperslange|last=Falk-R\u00f8nne|first=Arne|date=2017-03-16|publisher=Lindhardt og Ringhof|isbn=9788711714096|language=da}}</ref> who had heard it from one of Fawcett's murderers. Allegedly, Fawcett and his companions had a mishap on the river and lost most of the gifts they'd brought along for the Indian tribes. Continuing without gifts was a serious breach of protocol; since the expedition members were all more or less seriously ill at the time, the Kalapalo tribe they encountered decided to kill them. The bodies of Jack Fawcett and Raleigh Rimell were thrown into the river; Colonel Fawcett, considered an old man and therefore distinguished, received a proper burial. Falk-R\u00f8nne visited the Kalapalo tribe and reported that one of the tribesmen confirmed Villas-B\u00f4as's story about how and why Fawcett had been killed.\n\n===Fawcett's bones===\nIn 1951, Orlando Villas-B\u00f4as, activist for indigenous peoples, supposedly received the actual remaining skeletal bones of Fawcett and had them analysed scientifically. The analysis allegedly confirmed the bones were Fawcett's, but his son Brian Fawcett (1906\u20131984) refused to accept this. Villas-B\u00f4as claimed that Brian was too interested in making money from books about his father's disappearance. Later scientific analysis confirmed that the bones were not Fawcett's.<ref>''The upper jaw provides the clearest possible evidence that these human remains were not those of Colonel Fawcett, whose spare upper denture is fortunately available for comparison. ''[[Royal Anthropological Institute of Great Britain and Ireland|Royal Anthropological Institute]] (London) (1951) \"Report on the human remains from Brazil\" as quoted by Grann (2009) p. 253</ref><ref name=phfw-Izarari01a>{{cite web |url=http://www.phfawcettsweb.org/apazauca.htm |title=Izarari, Chief of the Kalapalos|work=The Great Web of Percy Harrison Fawcett|accessdate=11 March 2019|quote=Comatzi, the later chief of Kalapalos after Izarari\u2019s death, was after much persuasion induced to disclose the grave of the murderer explorer, and bones were dug up and examined by a team of experts of the Royal Anthropological Institute in London, but the results indicated that those bones were not of Fawcett and there is a doubt whether they belong to a white man. The bodies of the younger ones were thrown in the river, said Comatzi. At all events, they have not been found.}}</ref> As of 1965, the bones reportedly rested in a box in the flat of one of the Villas-B\u00f4as brothers in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/1953-COL-FAWCETT-PERU-BOLIVIA-BRAZIL-SOUTH-AMERICA-LOST-EXPEDITION-EL-DORADO-/382017420937|title=1953 Col. Fawcett Peru Bolivia Brazil South America Lost Expedition El Dorado|website=eBay|access-date=2017-07-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, English explorer [[Benedict Allen]] went to talk to the Kalapalo Indians, said by Villas-B\u00f4as to have confessed to having killed the three Fawcett expedition members. An elder of the Kalapalo, Vajuvi, claimed during a filmed BBC interview with Allen that the bones found by Villas-B\u00f4as 45 years before were not really Fawcett's.<ref name=\"Orcutt\" /><ref>\"Vajuvi said that they were the bones of his grandfather, Mugikia.\" Grann (2009) pp. 252\u2013253</ref> Vajuvi also denied that his tribe had any part in the Fawcetts' disappearance.{{cn|reason=Citation needed, especially as Vajuvi would be contradicting the earlier reported claims by Comatzi and Izarari.|date=March 2019}} No conclusive evidence supports either statement.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Russian documentary===\nIn 2003, a Russian documentary film, ''The Curse of the Incas' Gold / Expedition of Percy Fawcett to the Amazon'' ({{lang-ru|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043b\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0435 \u0437\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0438\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432 / \u042d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0446\u0438\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438 \u0424\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0432 \u0410\u043c\u0430\u0437\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443}}), was released as a part of the television series ''Mysteries of the Century'' ({{lang|ru|\u0422\u0430\u0439\u043d\u044b \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430}}). Among other things, the film emphasizes the recent expedition of Oleg Aliyev to the presumed approximate place of Fawcett's last whereabouts and Aliyev's findings, impressions and presumptions about Fawcett's fate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://filmix.net/tv/28662-tayny-veka-proklyatie-zolota-inkov-ekspediciya-persi-fosseta-v-amazonku-2004.html |title=\u0422\u0430\u0439\u043d\u044b \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430. \u041f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043b\u044f\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0438\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432. \u042d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0446\u0438\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438 \u0424\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0432 \u0410\u043c\u0430\u0437\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443. |trans-title=Secrets of the century. The curse of the Inca gold. Expedition of Percy Fosset to the Amazon. |work=Filmix.net |date=2011 |language=Russian}}</ref>\n\n===Commune in the jungle===\nOn 21 March 2004, the British newspaper ''[[The Observer]]'' reported that television director Misha Williams, who had studied Fawcett's private papers, believed that Fawcett had not intended to return to Britain but rather meant to found a [[commune (intentional community)|commune]] in the jungle based on [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|theosophical]] principles and the worship of his son Jack.<ref>{{cite news |first=Vanessa |last=Thorpe |title=Veil lifts on jungle mystery of the Colonel who vanished |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |date=21 March 2004 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/mar/21/research.brazil}}</ref> Williams explained his research in some detail in the preface to his play ''AmaZonia'', first performed in April 2004.<ref>{{cite book |first=Misha |last=Williams |title=AmaZonia |url=http://www.fawcettsamazonia.co.uk/pdf/AmaZonia%20by%20Misha%20Williams.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Grann's ''Lost City of Z''===\n{{Main|The Lost City of Z (book)}}\nIn 2005, ''[[The New Yorker]]'' staff writer [[David Grann]] visited the Kalapalo tribe and reported that it had apparently preserved an oral history about Fawcett, among the first Europeans the tribe had ever seen. The oral account said that Fawcett and his party had stayed at their village and then left, heading eastward. The Kalapalos warned Fawcett and his companions that if they went that way they would be killed by the \"fierce Indians\" who occupied that territory, but Fawcett insisted on going. The Kalapalos observed smoke from the expedition's campfire each evening for five days before it disappeared. The Kalapalos said they were sure the fierce Indians had killed them.<ref name=\"Yorker\"/> The article also reports that a monumental civilisation known as [[Kuhikugu]] may have actually existed near where Fawcett was searching, as discovered recently by archaeologist [[Michael Heckenberger]] and others.<ref>For further info see the last chapter of Grann's book ''[[The Lost City of Z (book)|The Lost City of Z]]'' and Charles Mann's book ''[[1491: New Revelations of the Americas Before Columbus]]''.</ref> Grann's findings are further detailed in his book ''[[The Lost City of Z (book)|The Lost City of Z]]'' (2009).\n\n=== Film adaptation of Grann's book ===\n{{Main|The Lost City of Z (film)}}\n\n===Allegation of racism and dangerous incompetence===\nIn 2017, explorer [[John Hemming (explorer)|John Hemming]] criticized the publicity for the movie ''[[The Lost City of Z (film)|The Lost City of Z]]'' for claiming that Fawcett was one of Britain's greatest explorers, arguing that this was an insult to the many true explorers, and that Fawcett was a racist, a \"nutter\", and a dangerous incompetent who \"never discovered anything\", but caused the loss of many lives.<ref name=Hemming2017-04-01a>{{cite magazine |author=John Hemming|authorlink=John Hemming (explorer)|title=The Lost City of Z is a very long way from a true story \u2014 and I should know|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/the-lost-city-of-z-is-a-very-long-way-from-a-true-story-and-i-should-know/|date=1 April 2017|accessdate=11 March 2019 |magazine= [[The Spectator]]|quote=The new film The Lost City of Z is being advertised as based on the true story of one of Britain\u2019s greatest explorers. .... Greatest explorer? Fawcett? He was a surveyor who never discovered anything, a nutter, a racist, and so incompetent that the only expedition he organised was a five-week disaster. Calling him one of our greatest explorers ... is an insult to the huge roster of true explorers. ... Fawcett casually remarked that five out of his six peons died from the effects of this five-week disaster. ... When one aimed a drawn bow at him, Fawcett shot the man with a Mauser revolver \u2014 absolutely forbidden by Brazil\u2019s Indian Service. ... In 1925, ... Fawcett ... committed other blunders that antagonised their hosts. So it was only a matter of days before they were all dead.}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*Fawcett, Percy and Brian Fawcett (1953), ''Exploration Fawcett'', Phoenix Press (2001 reprint), {{ISBN|1-84212-468-4}}\n*Fawcett, Percy and Brian Fawcett (1953), ''Lost Trails, Lost Cities'', Funk & Wagnalls ASIN B0007DNCV4\n*Fawcett, Brian (1958), ''Ruins in the Sky'', Hutchinson of London\n\n== In popular culture ==\n{{In popular culture|date=April 2017}}\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*Fawcett is the subject of History Channel's ''[[Digging for the Truth]]'' season 2, episode 13: \"[[List of Digging for the Truth episodes|The Lost Cities of the Amazon]]\".\n\n===Fiction===\n*[[Arthur Conan Doyle]] based his [[Professor Challenger]] character partly on Fawcett, and stories of \"the Lost City of Z\" became the basis for Conan Doyle's novel ''[[The Lost World (Conan Doyle novel)|The Lost World]].''<ref>[[David Grann|Grann, David]] (2009) ''[[The Lost City of Z (book)|The Lost City of Z: A Tale of Deadly Obsession in the Amazon]].'' Doubleday, New York, pages 8 and 95, {{ISBN|978-0-385-51353-1}}</ref>\n* A contemporary reviewer of [[Evelyn Waugh]]'s novel ''[[A Handful of Dust]]'' suggested he may have derived the plot partly from Fawcett's disappearance.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Times |date=4 September 1934 |page=7}}</ref>  The novel's hero vanishes into the Brazilian jungle and is kept prisoner there.\n*Fawcett has been proposed as a possible inspiration for [[Indiana Jones]], the fictional archaeologist/adventurer.<ref>Neither [[George Lucas]] nor [[Steven Spielberg]] \u2014 co-creators of the successful concept and franchise \u2014 have indicated that any specific individual inspired their character, other than the generic stock heroes popularised in the [[wikt:matin\u00e9e|matin\u00e9e]] serials and [[pulp magazines]] of the 1930s and 1940s they admired and wished to modernise, or later exotic-culture [[adventure film]]s such as 1954's ''[[Secret of the Incas]]''.</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Making ''Raiders of the Lost Ark'' |date=23 September 2003 |url=http://www.indianajones.com/raiders/bts/news/news20030923.html |work=Raiders News |accessdate=14 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031207015023/http://www.indianajones.com/raiders/bts/news/news20030923.html |archivedate=7 December 2003}}</ref> A fictionalised version of Fawcett aids Jones in the novel ''[[Indiana Jones and the Seven Veils]]''.<ref>{{cite book |first=Rob |last=MacGregor |title=Indiana Jones and the Seven Veils |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |date=November 1991 |url=http://www.randomhouse.com/bantamdell/catalog/display.pperl?isbn=9780553293340 |isbn=978-0-553-29035-6}}</ref>)\n*According to an article in ''Comics Scene'' No. 45, Fawcett was the inspiration of Kent Allard, an [[alter ego]] of [[The Shadow]].<ref name=\"Orcutt\">{{cite web |url=http://home.earthlink.net/~larryorcutt/fawcett.html |first=Larry |last=Orcutt |year=2000 |title=Colonel Percy Harrison Fawcett}}</ref>\n*Fawcett's is one of the past lives experienced under hypnosis by the protagonist of Charles MacLean's novel ''The Watcher'', a psychological thriller about a man who has a violent dissociative episode and seeks psychiatric help in the form of past lives regression therapy.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Aloha Wanderwell]]\n* [[Amazon River]]\n* [[Archaeology]]\n* [[Exploration|Explorers]]\n* [[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: pre-1970|List of people who disappeared]]\n* [[Paititi]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Falk-R\u00f8nne, Arne. (1991). ''Klodens Forunderlige Mysterier''. Roth Forlag.\n* [[Peter Fleming (writer)|Fleming, Peter]]. (1933) ''[[Brazilian Adventure]]'', Charles Scribner's Sons {{ISBN|0-87477-246-X}}\n* [[David Grann|Grann, David]] (2009) ''[[The Lost City of Z (book)|The Lost City of Z: A Tale of Deadly Obsession in the Amazon]]'' {{ISBN|978-0-385-51353-1}}\n* Leal, Hermes (1996), ''Enigma do Coronel Fawcett, o verdadeiro Indiana Jones'' (''Colonel Fawcett: The Real-Life Indiana Jones''; Published in Portuguese)\n* La Gazette des Fran\u00e7ais du Paraguay, ''Percy Fawcett - Un monument de l'Exploration et de l'Aventure en Am\u00e9rique Latine - Exp\u00e9dition du Rio Verde'' - bilingue fran\u00e7ais espagnol - num\u00e9ro 6, Ann\u00e9e 1, Asuncion Paraguay.\n* Scriblerius, C.S. (2015), \"Percyfaw Code, the secret dossier\" Published by Amazon.com.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://duncanjdsmith.com/uploads/documents/Forgotten/fawcett_18.pdf Forgotten Travellers: The Hunt for Colonel Fawcett]  Essay on Lt.-Col. Percy Harrison Fawcett\n*[http://www.unmuseum.org/fawcett.htm Virtual Exploration Society \u2013 Colonel Percy Fawcett]\n*[http://www.catchpenny.org/fawcett.html Colonel Fawcett]\n*[http://www.nybooks.com/articles/22662 Mad Dreams in the Amazon] Essay on Fawcett from ''[[The New York Review of Books]]''\n*[http://www.gryphonproductions.com/blog Lost in the Amazon: The Enigma of Col. Percy Fawcett] PBS Secrets of the Dead documentary\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090625171723/http://www.bfronline.biz/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=123&Itemid=9 ''B. Fletcher Robinson & 'The Lost World'''] by Paul Spiring\n*[https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/the-lost-city-of-z-is-a-very-long-way-from-a-true-story-and-i-should-know/ The Lost City of Z is a Long Way From a True Story and I Should Know by John Hemming in [[The Spectator]] ]\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/005015}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fawcett, Percy}}\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1920s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:People from Torquay]]\n[[Category:English archaeologists]]\n[[Category:English explorers]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Amazonia]]\n[[Category:Lost explorers]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Professor Challenger]]\n[[Category:Royal Artillery officers]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Distinguished Service Order]]\n", "name_user": "David J Johnson", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly expeditions:Revert overlinking, already linked earlier in article.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Fawcett"}
{"title_page": "Child Bride of Short Creek", "text_new": "{{one source|date=November 2009}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Child Bride of Short Creek\n| image                = Childbrideofshortcreek2.jpg\n| image_size           = 220\n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = DVD cover\n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = [[Joyce Eliason]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = Michael Fessier Jr.\n| director             = Robert Michael Lewis\n| starring             = [[Christopher Atkins]]<br />[[Diane Lane]]<br />[[Conrad Bain]]<br />[[Helen Hunt]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = [[John Cacavas]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = [[Paul Monash]]<br />[[Lawrence Schiller]]\n| editor               = John J. Dumas<br />Michael Economou\n| cinematography       = [[Gary Graver]]\n| runtime              = 120 minutes\n| company              = Schiller-Monash Productions\n| distributor          = [[NBC]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = NBC\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| first_aired          = December 7, 1981\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Child Bride of Short Creek''''' is a 1981 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] written by [[Joyce Eliason]],  starring  [[Christopher Atkins]], [[Diane Lane]], [[Conrad Bain]],  [[Helen Hunt]] and [[Dee Wallace]]. The film is a dramatization of the lives of the people of [[Colorado City, Arizona]], and [[Hildale, Utah]], United States, collectively known as \"Short Creek,\" a community of members of the [[Fundamentalist Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints]], a group that practices [[child marriage]] and [[polygamy]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1953 Arizona, teenagers Jessica Rae \"Jessie\" Jacobs (Diane Lane) and her friend Naomi (Helen Hunt) have grown up in Short Creek as members of an isolated patriarchal polygamist religious community, led by President Frank King (Conrad Bain). The members of the small group dress in old-fashioned clothing and spend many hours a day doing domestic and agricultural chores with traditional equipment and few modern conveniences. The women are trained to serve and be subservient to their husbands. They rarely travel away from the community and are usually kept away from outside influences such as magazines and radio. Jessie's father Jay Jacobs has three wives, including Jessie's mother Mary, who only sees her husband on certain days when he is not with his other wives, and has mixed feelings about the arrangement. State authorities are also investigating the group due to its unlawful customs of polygamy and [[child marriage]] of young girls to older men.\n\nPresident King's 19-year-old son Isaac (Christopher Atkins) returns home safely from serving in the [[Korean War]], having gained knowledge of the outside world through his travels. At his homecoming party, he and Jessie become attracted to each other, and over time they fall in love. To his father's chagrin, Isaac begins to reject the group's lifestyle, including the polygamy which allows the older men of the group to regularly take new young women as wives. Isaac further questions the group's beliefs when his younger sisters accidentally drown because they were not allowed to learn how to swim. Meanwhile, President King has confided to the men of the group that God has told him to take Jessie as his wife, in addition to the three wives he already has. Despite Jessie's youth, her father Jay accepts this as God's will. \n\nJessie's friend Naomi attempts to run away from Short Creek, planning to go to Las Vegas and become an actress. She naively accepts a ride from two young men who get her to drink alcohol for the first time and then try to rape her. She is rescued just in time by President King and driven back to Short Creek, where she is immediately married off to an old man to settle her down. \n\nIsaac learns that his father is planning to marry Jessie and is furious, not only because of his own feelings for Jessie but because an additional wife will cause his mother to be further neglected by his father. President King also tells Jessie of his plan to marry her. A reluctant Jessie goes along with his plan because she wants to please her parents and do the will of God, but she is very unhappy.\n\nJessie and Isaac secretly confess their love for each other and plan to run away together. However, after going a short distance they see many armed police preparing to launch a raid on the group. Fearing for the lives of her mother and family, Jessie decides she must go back to warn them, and says an emotional goodbye to Isaac, who boards a bus alone as Jessie rushes back to warn the community just ahead of the police. The police arrive and separate the families, sending the women and children to barracks where they will be re-educated in a modern lifestyle, while the men are sent to jail. \n\nTwo years later, Jessie and her mother Mary, along with the other community women, are being transferred once again from one barracks to another and are in line to board the bus when Jessie sees Isaac, who has just arrived in a car. Mary, seeing that Isaac and Jessie still love each other, tells her daughter to \"run, while you still have a chance\". Jessie hugs Mary goodbye, and goes to join Isaac; they drive away together.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Christopher Atkins]]: Isaac King\n* [[Diane Lane]]: Jessica Jacobs\n* [[Conrad Bain]] : Frank King \n* [[Helen Hunt]]: Naomi\n* [[Kiel Martin]] : Bob Kalish \n* [[Dee Wallace]]: Mary Jacobs\n* Julianne Slocum: Jacobs Daughter\n* Jake Johnston: Garth Jacobs\n*Karyn Christensen: Ada King\n*Sharyn Christensen: Alma King\n\n==Production==\nParts of the film were shot in [[Grafton, Utah|Grafton]], Rockville Road, and [[Rockville Bridge (Rockville, Utah)|Rockville Bridge]] in [[Utah]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Arc|first1=James V.|title=When Hollywood came to town: a history of moviemaking in Utah|date=2010|publisher=Gibbs Smith|location=Layton, Utah|isbn=9781423605874|edition=1st}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0082169}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Child Bride Of Short Creek}}\n[[Category:1981 television films]]\n[[Category:1980s drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Utah]]\n[[Category:NBC network original films]]\n", "text_old": "{{one source|date=November 2009}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Child Bride of Short Creek\n| image                = Childbrideofshortcreek2.jpg\n| image_size           = 220\n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = DVD cover\n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = [[Joyce Eliason]]<br />\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = [[Michael Fessier Jr.]]\n| director             = [[Robert Michael Lewis]]\n| starring             = [[Christopher Atkins]]<br />[[Diane Lane]]<br />[[Conrad Bain]]<br />[[Helen Hunt]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = [[John Cacavas]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = [[Paul Monash]]<br />[[Lawrence Schiller]]\n| editor               = [[John J. Dumas]]<br />[[Michael Economou]]\n| cinematography       = [[Gary Graver]]\n| runtime              = 120 minutes\n| company              = [[Schiller-Monash Productions]]\n| distributor          = [[NBC]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = NBC\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| first_aired          = December 7, 1981\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Child Bride of Short Creek''''' is a 1981 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] written by [[Joyce Eliason]],  starring  [[Christopher Atkins]], [[Diane Lane]], [[Conrad Bain]],  [[Helen Hunt]] and [[Dee Wallace]]. The film is a dramatization of the lives of the people of [[Colorado City, Arizona]], and [[Hildale, Utah]], United States, collectively known as \"Short Creek,\" a community of members of the [[Fundamentalist Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints]], a group that practices [[child marriage]] and [[polygamy]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1953 Arizona, teenagers Jessica Rae \"Jessie\" Jacobs (Diane Lane) and her friend Naomi (Helen Hunt) have grown up in Short Creek as members of an isolated patriarchal polygamist religious community, led by President Frank King (Conrad Bain). The members of the small group dress in old-fashioned clothing and spend many hours a day doing domestic and agricultural chores with traditional equipment and few modern conveniences. The women are trained to serve and be subservient to their husbands. They rarely travel away from the community and are usually kept away from outside influences such as magazines and radio. Jessie's father Jay Jacobs has three wives, including Jessie's mother Mary, who only sees her husband on certain days when he is not with his other wives, and has mixed feelings about the arrangement. State authorities are also investigating the group due to its unlawful customs of polygamy and [[child marriage]] of young girls to older men.\n\nPresident King's 19-year-old son Isaac (Christopher Atkins) returns home safely from serving in the [[Korean War]], having gained knowledge of the outside world through his travels. At his homecoming party, he and Jessie become attracted to each other, and over time they fall in love. To his father's chagrin, Isaac begins to reject the group's lifestyle, including the polygamy which allows the older men of the group to regularly take new young women as wives. Isaac further questions the group's beliefs when his younger sisters accidentally drown because they were not allowed to learn how to swim. Meanwhile, President King has confided to the men of the group that God has told him to take Jessie as his wife, in addition to the three wives he already has. Despite Jessie's youth, her father Jay accepts this as God's will. \n\nJessie's friend Naomi attempts to run away from Short Creek, planning to go to Las Vegas and become an actress. She naively accepts a ride from two young men who get her to drink alcohol for the first time and then try to rape her. She is rescued just in time by President King and driven back to Short Creek, where she is immediately married off to an old man to settle her down. \n\nIsaac learns that his father is planning to marry Jessie and is furious, not only because of his own feelings for Jessie but because an additional wife will cause his mother to be further neglected by his father. President King also tells Jessie of his plan to marry her. A reluctant Jessie goes along with his plan because she wants to please her parents and do the will of God, but she is very unhappy.\n\nJessie and Isaac secretly confess their love for each other and plan to run away together. However, after going a short distance they see many armed police preparing to launch a raid on the group. Fearing for the lives of her mother and family, Jessie decides she must go back to warn them, and says an emotional goodbye to Isaac, who boards a bus alone as Jessie rushes back to warn the community just ahead of the police. The police arrive and separate the families, sending the women and children to barracks where they will be re-educated in a modern lifestyle, while the men are sent to jail. \n\nTwo years later, Jessie and her mother Mary, along with the other community women, are being transferred once again from one barracks to another and are in line to board the bus when Jessie sees Isaac, who has just arrived in a car. Mary, seeing that Isaac and Jessie still love each other, tells her daughter to \"run, while you still have a chance\". Jessie hugs Mary goodbye, and goes to join Isaac; they drive away together.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Christopher Atkins]]: Isaac King\n* [[Diane Lane]]: Jessica Jacobs\n* [[Conrad Bain]] : Frank King \n* [[Helen Hunt]]: Naomi\n* [[Kiel Martin]] : Bob Kalish \n* [[Dee Wallace]]: Mary Jacobs\n* Julianne Slocum: Jacobs Daughter\n* Jake Johnston: Garth Jacobs\n*Karyn Christensen: Ada King\n*Sharyn Christensen: Alma King\n\n==Production==\nParts of the film were shot in [[Grafton, Utah|Grafton]], Rockville Road, and [[Rockville Bridge (Rockville, Utah)|Rockville Bridge]] in [[Utah]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Arc|first1=James V.|title=When Hollywood came to town: a history of moviemaking in Utah|date=2010|publisher=Gibbs Smith|location=Layton, Utah|isbn=9781423605874|edition=1st}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0082169}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Child Bride Of Short Creek}}\n[[Category:1981 television films]]\n[[Category:1980s drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Utah]]\n[[Category:NBC network original films]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Child_Bride_of_Short_Creek"}
{"title_page": "Luca Fusi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name                = Luca Fusi\n | image                = \n | height               = 1.75 m\n | birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1963|6|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Lecco]], [[Italy]]\n | currentclub          = [[Castel Rigone Calcio|Castel Rigone]]\n | clubnumber           = \n | position             = [[Midfielder]], [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n | youthyears1   =  | youthclubs1   = [[Calcio Como|Como]]\n | years1   = 1981\u20131986 | clubs1   = [[Calcio Como|Como]] | caps1   = 125 | goals1   = 5\n | years2   = 1986\u20131988 | clubs2   = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] | caps2   = 60 | goals2   = 0\n | years3   = 1988\u20131990 | clubs3   = [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] | caps3   = 60 | goals3   = 2\n | years4   = 1990\u20131994 | clubs4   = [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] | caps4   = 119 | goals4   = 1\n | years5   = 1994\u20131995 | clubs5   = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] | caps5   = 10 | goals5   = 0\n | years6   = 1995\u20131997 | clubs6   = [[AC Lugano|Lugano]] | caps6   = 20 | goals6   = 0\n | nationalyears1   = 1988\u20131992 | nationalteam1   = [[Italy national football team|Italy]] | nationalcaps1   = 8 | nationalgoals1   = 0\n | manageryears1   = 2007\u20132008 | managerclubs1   = [[A.C. Bellaria Igea Marina|Bellaria Igea]]\n | manageryears2   = 2008\u20132009 | managerclubs2   = [[Real Marcianise Calcio|Real Marcianise]]\n | manageryears3   = 2009\u20132010 | managerclubs3   = [[Foligno Calcio|Foligno]]\n | manageryears4  = 2013\u2013 | managerclubs4   = [[Castel Rigone Calcio|Castel Rigone]]\n| pcupdate             = 7 December 2008\n | ntupdate             = 7 December 2008<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/player/15437.html |title=Fusi, Luca |website=National-Football-Teams.com |access-date=7 December 2008}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Luca Fusi''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8lu\u02d0ka \u02c8fu\u02d0zi; \u02c8fu\u02d0si}}; born 7 June 1963) is a retired [[Italians|Italian]] [[Association football|footballer]] turned [[Manager (association football)|manager]], who played as a [[midfielder]] or [[defender (association football)|defender]]. He is the current head coach of [[Lega Pro Seconda Divisione]] team [[Castel Rigone Calcio|Castel Rigone]].<ref name=\"Il Pallone Racconta: Luca FUSI\">{{cite web|url=http://ilpalloneracconta.blogspot.ca/2008/06/luca-fusi.html|title=Il Pallone Racconta: Luca FUSI|publisher=Il Pallone Racconta|language=Italian|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"tuttojuve\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-luca-fusi-303721|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Luca FUSI|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|author1=Stefano Bedeschi|date=7 June 2016|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring his club career he played for [[Como Calcio 1907|Como]], [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] and [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. He earned 8 caps for the [[Italy national football team]] and took part in the [[1988 UEFA European Football Championship]]. He was known as an intelligent, hardworking, tactically versatile, and correct player throughout his career, with good technique and determination, and could also play as a [[Sweeper (association football)|sweeper]], a role in which he was frequently deployed in his later career, following his athletic decline, due to his [[Playmaker|playmaking]] ability.<ref name=\"Il Pallone Racconta: Luca FUSI\"/><ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n\n== Club career ==\nFusi began his career with [[Como Calcio 1907|Como]], then playing for [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] from 1986 to 1988, and also winning a [[Coppa Italia]] with the Genoan side.<ref name=\"Il Pallone Racconta: Luca FUSI\"/><ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n\nIn 1988, he left Sampdoria to join [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], winning a [[UEFA Cup]] in 1989 and a [[Serie A]] championship type in 1990. In June 1990 he successively left Napoli to become part of the [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] midfield. Ironically for him, he scored his only Serie A goal for Torino away to Napoli on 16 February 1992, a left-footed strike from outside the area. Having won another [[Coppa Italia]] title in [[1992\u201393 Coppa Italia|1993]], also reaching the [[1991\u201392 UEFA Cup|1992 UEFA Cup final]], he moved to crosstown rivals [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], where he won another [[Serie A]] title and a personal third [[Coppa Italia]] in 1995, although he began to be deployed less frequently when Lippi switched to a zonal marking defensive system, which did not feature a sweeper, and collected only 10 appearances in the league in total, and 18 in all competitions throughout the season. He ended his career with [[Switzerland|Swiss]] side [[AC Lugano]], where he played from 1996 to 1997.<ref name=\"Il Pallone Racconta: Luca FUSI\"/><ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n\n== International career ==\nFusi made his Italian national team debut on 31 March 1988 in [[Split (city)|Split]], against [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]], as a substitute for [[Luigi De Agostini]]. He was also called up for Italy at [[UEFA Euro 1988]] under manager [[Azeglio Vicini]], but did not play in any of Italy's games during the tournament as the team reached the semi-finals. In total, Fusi made 8 appearances for Italy between 1988 and 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=47&squadra=1|title=Convocazioni e presenze in campo: Luca Fusi|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=23 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727181304/http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=47&squadra=1|archive-date=27 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Coaching career ==\nAfter two seasons as assistant coach at [[A.C. Cesena|Cesena]], in 2007\u201308 season Fusi served as head coach of [[A.C. Bellaria Igea Marina|Bellaria Igea]] of [[Serie C2]] (fourth tier).\n\nOn June 2008 he signed for [[Real Marcianise Calcio|Real Marcianise]] of [[Lega Pro Prima Divisione]] (third tier), guiding them to a mid-table finish.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/index.php?action=read&id=109712 |publisher=TuttoMercatoWeb |accessdate=20 June 2008 |date=20 June 2008 |language=Italian |title=UFFICIALE: Marcianise, panchina a Luca Fusi}}</ref> He is currently serving as head coach of [[Foligno Calcio|Foligno]], another Lega Pro Prima Divisione team, for the 2009\u201310 season. He was removed from his managerial duties on 27 April 2010 due to poor results, with Foligno in 15th place, and replaced by [[Salvatore Matrecano]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/notizie-ultima-ora/Calcio/Calcio-Foligno-esonera-Fusi/27-04-2010/2-A_000100227.shtml |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |accessdate=27 April 2010 |date=27 April 2010 |title=Calcio: Foligno esonera Fusi }}</ref>\n\nSince 23 October 2013 Fusi is the new coach of [[Castel Rigone Calcio|Castel Rigone]].\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n;[[UC Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]<ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[1987\u201388 Coppa Italia|1987\u201388]]\n\n;[[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]]<ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1989\u201390 Serie A|1989\u201390]]\n*[[UEFA Cup]]: [[1988\u201389 UEFA Cup|1988\u201389]]\n\n;[[Torino F.C.|Torino]]<ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n*[[Mitropa Cup]]: 1991\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[1992\u201393 Coppa Italia|1992\u201393]]\n\n;[[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]<ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1994\u201395 Serie A|1994\u201395]]\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[1994\u201395 Coppa Italia|1994\u201395]]\n*[[Supercoppa Italiana]]: [[1995 Supercoppa Italiana|1995]]\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[1995\u201396 UEFA Champions League|1995\u201396]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080327090757/http://www.footballplus.com/players/10134/Luca-Fusi.html Career profile]\n*{{TuttoCalciatori|Fusi_Luca}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180727181304/http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=47&squadra=1 Profile at FIGC.it] {{in lang|it}} {{dead link|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Italy Squad 1988 UEFA Euro}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fusi, Luca}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lecco]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1988 players]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Como 1907 players]]\n[[Category:U.C. Sampdoria players]]\n[[Category:S.S.C. Napoli players]]\n[[Category:Torino F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Lugano players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:A.C. Bellaria Igea Marina managers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n | name                = Luca Fusi\n | image                = \n | height               = 1.75 m\n | birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1963|6|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Lecco]], [[Italy]]\n | currentclub          = [[Castel Rigone Calcio|Castel Rigone]]\n | clubnumber           = \n | position             = [[Midfielder]], [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n | youthyears1   =  | youthclubs1   = [[Calcio Como|Como]]\n | years1   = 1981\u20131986 | clubs1   = [[Calcio Como|Como]] | caps1   = 125 | goals1   = 5\n | years2   = 1986\u20131988 | clubs2   = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] | caps2   = 60 | goals2   = 0\n | years3   = 1988\u20131990 | clubs3   = [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] | caps3   = 60 | goals3   = 2\n | years4   = 1990\u20131994 | clubs4   = [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] | caps4   = 119 | goals4   = 1\n | years5   = 1994\u20131995 | clubs5   = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] | caps5   = 10 | goals5   = 0\n | years6   = 1995\u20131997 | clubs6   = [[AC Lugano|Lugano]] | caps6   = 20 | goals6   = 0\n | nationalyears1   = 1988\u20131992 | nationalteam1   = [[Italy national football team|Italy]] | nationalcaps1   = 8 | nationalgoals1   = 0\n | manageryears1   = 2007\u20132008 | managerclubs1   = [[A.C. Bellaria Igea Marina|Bellaria Igea]]\n | manageryears2   = 2008\u20132009 | managerclubs2   = [[Real Marcianise Calcio|Real Marcianise]]\n | manageryears3   = 2009\u20132010 | managerclubs3   = [[Foligno Calcio|Foligno]]\n | manageryears4  = 2013\u2013 | managerclubs4   = [[Castel Rigone Calcio|Castel Rigone]]\n| pcupdate             = 7 December 2008\n | ntupdate             = 7 December 2008<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/player/15437.html |title=Fusi, Luca |website=National-Football-Teams.com |access-date=2008-12-07}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Luca Fusi''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8lu\u02d0ka \u02c8fu\u02d0zi; \u02c8fu\u02d0si}}; born 7 June 1963) is a retired [[Italians|Italian]] [[Association football|footballer]] turned [[Manager (association football)|manager]], who played as a [[midfielder]] or [[defender (association football)|defender]]. He is the current head coach of [[Lega Pro Seconda Divisione]] team [[Castel Rigone Calcio|Castel Rigone]].<ref name=\"Il Pallone Racconta: Luca FUSI\">{{cite web|url=http://ilpalloneracconta.blogspot.ca/2008/06/luca-fusi.html|title=Il Pallone Racconta: Luca FUSI|publisher=Il Pallone Racconta|language=Italian|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"tuttojuve\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-luca-fusi-303721|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Luca FUSI|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|author1=Stefano Bedeschi|date=7 June 2016|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring his club career he played for [[Como Calcio 1907|Como]], [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] and [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. He earned 8 caps for the [[Italy national football team]] and took part in the [[1988 UEFA European Football Championship]]. He was known as an intelligent, hardworking, tactically versatile, and correct player throughout his career, with good technique and determination, and could also play as a [[Sweeper (association football)|sweeper]], a role in which he was frequently deployed in his later career, following his athletic decline, due to his [[Playmaker|playmaking]] ability.<ref name=\"Il Pallone Racconta: Luca FUSI\"/><ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n\n== Club career ==\nFusi began his career with [[Como Calcio 1907|Como]], then playing for [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] from 1986 to 1988, and also winning a [[Coppa Italia]] with the Genoan side.<ref name=\"Il Pallone Racconta: Luca FUSI\"/><ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n\nIn 1988, he left Sampdoria to join [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], winning a [[UEFA Cup]] in 1989 and a [[Serie A]] championship type in 1990. In June 1990 he successively left Napoli to become part of the [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] midfield. Ironically for him, he scored his only Serie A goal for Torino away to Napoli on 16 February 1992, a left-footed strike from outside the area. Having won another [[Coppa Italia]] title in [[1992\u201393 Coppa Italia|1993]], also reaching the [[1991\u201392 UEFA Cup|1992 UEFA Cup final]], he moved to crosstown rivals [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], where he won another [[Serie A]] title and a personal third [[Coppa Italia]] in 1995, although he began to be deployed less frequently when Lippi switched to a zonal marking defensive system, which did not feature a sweeper, and collected only 10 appearances in the league in total, and 18 in all competitions throughout the season. He ended his career with [[Switzerland|Swiss]] side [[AC Lugano]], where he played from 1996 to 1997.<ref name=\"Il Pallone Racconta: Luca FUSI\"/><ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n\n== International career ==\nFusi made his Italian national team debut on 31 March 1988 in [[Split (city)|Split]], against [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]], as a substitute for [[Luigi De Agostini]]. He was also called up for Italy at [[UEFA Euro 1988]] under manager [[Azeglio Vicini]], but did not play in any of Italy's games during the tournament as the team reached the semi-finals. In total, Fusi made 8 appearances for Italy between 1988 and 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=47&squadra=1|title=Convocazioni e presenze in campo: Luca Fusi|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=23 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727181304/http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=47&squadra=1|archive-date=27 July 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Coaching career ==\nAfter two seasons as assistant coach at [[A.C. Cesena|Cesena]], in 2007\u201308 season Fusi served as head coach of [[A.C. Bellaria Igea Marina|Bellaria Igea]] of [[Serie C2]] (fourth tier).\n\nOn June 2008 he signed for [[Real Marcianise Calcio|Real Marcianise]] of [[Lega Pro Prima Divisione]] (third tier), guiding them to a mid-table finish.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/index.php?action=read&id=109712 |publisher=TuttoMercatoWeb |accessdate=2008-06-20 |date=2008-06-20 |language=Italian |title=UFFICIALE: Marcianise, panchina a Luca Fusi}}</ref> He is currently serving as head coach of [[Foligno Calcio|Foligno]], another Lega Pro Prima Divisione team, for the 2009\u201310 season. He was removed from his managerial duties on April 27, 2010 due to poor results, with Foligno in 15th place, and replaced by [[Salvatore Matrecano]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/notizie-ultima-ora/Calcio/Calcio-Foligno-esonera-Fusi/27-04-2010/2-A_000100227.shtml |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |accessdate=2010-04-27 |date=2010-04-27 |title=Calcio: Foligno esonera Fusi }}</ref>\n\nSince 23 October 2013 Fusi is the new coach of [[Castel Rigone Calcio|Castel Rigone]].\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n;[[UC Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]<ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[1987\u201388 Coppa Italia|1987\u201388]]\n\n;[[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]]<ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1989\u201390 Serie A|1989\u201390]]\n*[[UEFA Cup]]: [[1988\u201389 UEFA Cup|1988\u201389]]\n\n;[[Torino F.C.|Torino]]<ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n*[[Mitropa Cup]]: 1991\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[1992\u201393 Coppa Italia|1992\u201393]]\n\n;[[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]<ref name=\"tuttojuve\"/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1994\u201395 Serie A|1994\u201395]]\n*[[Coppa Italia]]: [[1994\u201395 Coppa Italia|1994\u201395]]\n*[[Supercoppa Italiana]]: [[1995 Supercoppa Italiana|1995]]\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[1995\u201396 UEFA Champions League|1995\u201396]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080327090757/http://www.footballplus.com/players/10134/Luca-Fusi.html Career profile]\n*{{TuttoCalciatori|Fusi_Luca}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180727181304/http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=47&squadra=1 Profile at FIGC.it] {{in lang|it}} {{dead link|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Italy Squad 1988 UEFA Euro}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fusi, Luca}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lecco]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1988 players]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Como 1907 players]]\n[[Category:U.C. Sampdoria players]]\n[[Category:S.S.C. Napoli players]]\n[[Category:Torino F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Lugano players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:A.C. Bellaria Igea Marina managers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup 